<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 00:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senator invites New York Jets to move to Yonkers as bidding war  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The Yonkers Jets?
<P>
	   State Sen. Nick Spano of Westchester thinks the team and the town would be
great together.
</P>
<P>
	   Spano, a Republican, wrote new Jets owner Robert Wood Johnson Wednesday and
asked him to think about moving the team up the Hudson River to the Yonkers
Raceway when its lease is up at the New Jersey Meadowlands.
</P>
<P>
	   The Yonkers facility has 97 acres of land just waiting for someone to do
something with it and "Jets Stadium" would be the perfect fit, the senator said.
"It's feasible, it's accessible and it's available," Spano said.
</P>
<P>
	   And it already has an NFL connection: The Yonkers Raceway is owned by the
Rooney family, owner of the Pittsburgh Steelers, Spano said.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think Yonkers, for sure, is ready for the big time," said Spano, noting
the recent additions of Home Depot, Costco and Stew Leonard's to the city of
180,000 that sits 17 miles north of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
	   New York Jets spokesman Frank Ramos refused to comment, saying he had not
heard about Spano's offer.
</P>
<P>
	   Yonkers Mayor John Spencer cheered the proposal, saying it would be great if
all of the details could be worked out. "You're talking to a lifelong Giants
fan, but I'd gladly be a Jets fan if they moved to Yonkers," Spencer said.
</P>
<P>
	   The Jets still have eight more years to play in New Jersey but jockeying for
the football team has already begun. Johnson noted in his inaugural news
conference that the Jets have never had their own stadium.
</P>
<P>
	   After starting in the Polo Grounds, former owner Leon Hess moved the Jets
out of Shea Stadium in 1984 and since then they have shared Giants Stadium in
East Rutherford, N.J.
</P>
<P>
	   "They have been in the Mets Stadium, Shea Stadium and now this since 1984,
and we want to do everything in our power to provide them with their own
stadium," Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
	   New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has raised the possibility of
constructing a stadium on the West Side and Newark also could be a possibility
for the nomadic team. The Meadowlands also wants the Jets to stay but is feeling
pressure with all the speculation.
</P>
<P>
	   "The only things that's changed about your call is the place," New Jersey
Sports Authority spokesman Dan Emmer said. "Yesterday, it was Mayor Giuliani
with a stadium on the West Side, then it was Newark, and now it's Yonkers."
</P>
<P>
	   Spano thinks he has the best idea, however. "Geographically, there's no
better place" than Yonkers, Spano said. "It's located just eight miles from the
George Washington Bridge, less than five miles from the Tappan Zee, and it's
easily accessible to several major highways."
</P>
<P>
	   And "let's face it, are there sites in New York City that are accessible,
that are available and that are feasible?" Spano said. "I don't think so. Let's
not lose the Jets to New Jersey again."
</P>
<P>
	   Spano is trying to recruit Gov. George Pataki to his cause, forwarding him a
copy of his letter.
</P>
<P>
	   "There are a number of communities in New York that would love to be home to
the Jets," Pataki spokesman Michael McKeon said. "We would love to put the New
York back in the New York Jets."
</P>
<P>
	   However, if his plan works, Spano still wouldn't be in favor of an offical
name change to the Yonkers Jets. "Let's keep it the way it is," he said,
laughing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
