<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 00:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll: Gore picks up, Bush GOP choice among New Yorkers  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Democrats are watching New Hampshire to see if its
Feb. 1 primary breaks open a tight race for the Democratic vote in New York.
<P>
	   A Quinnipiac College Polling Institute survey released Wednesday found the
race between Vice President Al Gore and former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley a
statistical tie - just like it was in December.
</P>
<P>
	   But either Democrat would have an edge in a general election against
Republican favorites George W. Bush and Sen. John McCain of Arizona, according
to the poll.
</P>
<P>
	   Maurice Carroll, director of the polling institute, emphasized that a big
win by Bradley in New Hampshire's Feb. 1 primary could pay off in unstoppable
momentum for the former New York Knicks star in New York's March 7 primary.
</P>
<P>
	   "A Bradley win in New Hampshire next month could scramble the mix in New
York," Carroll said.
</P>
<P>
	   "Polls go up and polls go down," said Julia Rothwax of the Bradley campaign,
downplaying the slight rise for Gore. The former senator has consistently polled
well against Republicans, so the picture in New York is no surprise, she said.
</P>
<P>
	   The Gore camp says it isn't surprised by the neck-and-neck battle.
</P>
<P>
	   "We've always known we'd face a tough fight in Bill Bradley's backyard,"
said Gore spokesman Peter Ragone, "and Al Gore intends to fight his heart and
soul out for every vote in New York."
</P>
<P>
	   The poll questioned 812 registered voters in the state from Jan. 11-17. It
found Gore and Bradley in a statistical tie: 44 percent for Gore, 39 percent for
Bradley. In December, the same pollsters found Gore supported by 42 percent and
Bradley by 39 percent - also a statistical tie. Bradley led in November,
however, 47 percent to 38 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   The poll released Wednesday has a margin of error of 3 percentage points
when both Republicans and Democrats were questioned. The margin of error
increased to 5.5 percentage points for the answers from the 330 Democrats
questioned, and to 6 percent for the responses of the 246 Republicans
questioned.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush, the Texas governor, maintained a solid lead in the Republican race
with 47 percent to the 28 percent for McCain.
</P>
<P>
	   New York's primary is seen as a critical test for Bradley because of his
near favorite-son status here.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley led Bush 52 percent to 35 percent, according to the poll. Gore had a
47 percent-to-39 percent lead over the Texas governor, the poll showed.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore would beat McCain 47 percent to 38 percent and Bradley would beat
McCain 49 percent to 39 percent, according to the Quinnipiac pollster.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is a Democratic town," Carroll said, referring to the state. "And
Bradley looks better with independents."
</P>
<P>
	   "It's not surprising," said Daniel Allen, spokesman for the state Republican
Committee of the Democrats' apparent narrow edge. He said the front-runner is
often the target of other candidates and reporters and that can hurt Bush.
</P>
<P>
	   However, there's time before the primary, Allen emphasized.
</P>
<P>
	   "Governor Bush has a message that really resonates with the families of New
York more than Gore or Bradley," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
