<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 00:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bruno pledges support for expanded program  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The state Senate will approve a measure to double
the number of elderly New Yorkers eligible for a state-subsidized prescription
drug program, Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno pledged Wednesday.
<P>
	   "New Yorkers don't need to go to Canada," Bruno said, recounting tales of
seniors crossing the border to obtain affordable medications. "They need to stay
in New York to buy prescriptions."
</P>
<P>
	   The Senate measure would raise income ceilings for eligibility in the
state's 12-year-old Elderly Pharmaceutical Insurance Program (EPIC), which
subsidizes prescription drug costs for some senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
	   Seniors who earn less than $35,000 and couples who earn less than $50,000
would qualify for the program - doubling the eligibility pool to about 229,900
senior citizens statewide. The current cutoff is $18,500 for individuals and
$24,400 for couples. The proposal also cuts average out-of-pocket expenses for
seniors' pharmaceutical purchases from $549 to $429 - or by about 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   New Yorkers age 65 and older are eligible for the program.
</P>
<P>
	   Bruno proposed dedicating $125 million of the state's settlement with
tobacco companies to pay for the program's expansion.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's an offer no one can refuse," said Sen. Thomas Morahan, the Rockland
County Republican who is cosponsoring the bill with Sen. George Maziarz, a
Niagara County Republican.
</P>
<P>
	   According to the American Association of Retired Persons, Americans age 65
and older account for one third of all prescription drug spending, despite
making up only 12 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
	   Families USA, a consumer group based in Washington, found that the price of
the 50 prescription drugs most often used by senior citizens is rising at four
times the rate of the consumer price index.
</P>
<P>
	   For the elderly, it can become a choice of "paying their bills or taking
their pills," AARP Spokeswoman Jo Freedman said.
</P>
<P>
	   Even if the bill sails through the Republican-controlled Senate next week,
its fate in the Democrat-controlled Assembly is unclear.
</P>
<P>
	   Eileen Larrabee, spokeswoman for Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver, said
Assembly Democrats have long advocated broadened EPIC and would be drawing up
their own suggestions.
</P>
<P>
	   "We welcome the Senate aboard," Larrabee said. "The Assembly has been
working to make prescription drugs more affordable for years."
</P>
<P>
	   Though he did not include funding increases for EPIC in his 2000-01 budget
proposal, Gov. George E. Pataki is behind the Senate's efforts, Bruno said.
</P>
<P>
	   Also Wednesday, Bruno said the Senate would soon begin investigating
disparities between prescription drug prices in New York and in other parts of
the country.
</P>
<P>
	   Sen. John Marchi, a Staten Island Republican, has filed a bill to prohibit
prescription drugs from being sold at prices higher in New York than in other
jurisdictions and nations.
</P>
<P>
	   "We want pharmaceutical manufacturers to explain to us why this is the
case," Bruno said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-20-00 0035 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
