<DOCNO> APW20000120.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 00:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Group calls on Bush not to pick pro-casino Pataki as VP  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - George Bush should not pick George Pataki as a
running mate because the New York governor has authorized Indian casinos and
wants to legalize non-Indian casinos as well, a group is contending.
<P>
	   The organization, the New York Institute for Law in Society, took out a
full-page advertisement in Wednesday's Manchester (N.H.) Union Leader newspaper
urging Bush not to select Pataki.
</P>
<P>
	   The Union Leader will be the first of several newspapers to run the ad as
the Republican presidential primaries near, according to the group.
</P>
<P>
	   The ad is designed as an open letter to Texas Gov. Bush, the frontrunner to
capture the Republican nomination for president in 2000. It urges Bush to
"review" Pataki's record on casinos before considering him as a vice
presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
	   "The 2000 Republican National ticket cannot have a candidate who supports
the proliferation of casino gambling," the organization said.
</P>
<P>
	   A leader of the Rome, N.Y.-based group, Tom Hunter, said it believes Pataki
has illegally entered into a compact which is allowing Mohawk Indians to operate
a casino on their land near the United States-Canadian border. The group is
arguing - along with other gambling foes and Democratic state legislators - that
Pataki needed the approval of the Legislature before the state could enter into
any gaming compacts with tribes.
</P>
<P>
	   Indians are also seeking to open other casinos in New York, and the Pataki
administration is involved in wide-ranging discussions with New York tribes
about casinos, Indian land claims and other issues.
</P>
<P>
	   Pataki has said he does not like casinos, but believes that since two Indian
casinos are already operating, the state should allow non-Indian casinos to open
in some areas of New York. That way, the state can profit from the gambling
revenues, he said. The Legislature has refused to go along with his casino
legislation.
</P>
<P>
	   Hunter said the group may take out the ad again in New Hampshire, where the
first-in-the-nation presidential primary will be held Feb. 1. The group also
plans to run the ad in Thursday's Des Moines Register in Iowa, which is holding
its presidential caucuses on Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   The ad will also be in the Albany (N.Y.) Times Union on Thursday, group
officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   "We hope people pay attention to it," said Hunter, who lives in Syracuse.
"We hope George W. Bush pays attention to it."
</P>
<P>
	   Hunter said his group is conservative in philosophy and is not aligned with
a political party. He refused to disclose its sources of money or how much it
planned to spend on the anti-Pataki ads.
</P>
<P>
	   Pataki is considered a long-shot to be tapped by Bush as a running mate.
Pataki and most of the rest of the New York Republican Party organization have
endorsed Bush for president.
</P>
<P>
	   Scott McClellan, a spokesman for the Bush campaign, said it is "way too
premature" to be discussing Bush's vice presidential selection.
</P>
<P>
	   "Gov. Bush is focused on earning the presidential nomination," McClellan
said. "Gov. Pataki is a good friend, a strong supporter and Gov. Bush
appreciates his serving as his state campaign chair in New York."
</P>
<P>
	   Pataki spokeswoman and political adviser Zenia Mucha called the ad "silly"
and "not even accurate."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-20-00 0035 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
