<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hillary Clinton faces questions on personal life, marriage  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) - On a day when she hoped the talk would center on
such things as her plans for announcing her Senate candidacy, Hillary Rodham
Clinton instead found herself being questioned about her marital fidelity.
<P>
	   For a second straight day, the first lady fielded questions Wednesday about
her personal life, and reluctantly answered them.
</P>
<P>
	   She told a radio talk show host she had never been unfaithful to her husband
and denied rumors she had an affair with former White House Deputy Counsel Vince
Foster, who committed suicide.
</P>
<P>
	   She also told the interviewer what she thought of such inquiries.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think those questions are out of bounds," she told WGR-FM morning host
Tom Bauerle in Buffalo during a campaign swing through New York's second largest
city.
</P>
<P>
	   Bauerle had prefaced his questions by telling the first lady, "You're going
to hate me for this."
</P>
<P>
	   "I do hate you for that," Mrs. Clinton told him.
</P>
<P>
	   Bauerle wasn't done.
</P>
<P>
	   "Have you ever used pot or cocaine?" he asked.
</P>
<P>
	   "Tom, what did you have breakfast for this morning?" Mrs. Clinton responded.
"No."
</P>
<P>
	   Asked later whether questions about her personal life were fair, she said:
"I don't know that it's fair or unfair. It is on some peoples' minds, but most
of what people talk to me about is the state of their families and their jobs
and their schools and that's what I'm going to be talking about."
</P>
<P>
	   But a short while later, at a senior citizens community center in the
Buffalo suburb of Cheektowaga, Mrs. Clinton said she had been hearing from
people in the audience about the personal questions she had been asked.
</P>
<P>
	   Taking a microphone, she told the several hundred people that "sometimes in
public life people ask inappropriate, off-the-wall kinds of questions, don't
they? But I want you to know none of that is going to deter me from coming back
time after time to western New York and being part of building a better future
here."
</P>
<P>
	   A day earlier, Mrs. Clinton had told an inquiring television interviewer
that she planned to "spend the rest of my life" with Bill Clinton, the president
whose affair with a White House intern led to his impeachment and a failed vote
in the Senate last year to remove him from office.
</P>
<P>
	   That seemed to set the stage for Wednesday's new round of questions by the
media about her personal life as she prepares for a campaign that is expected to
pit her against New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
	   After her interview with Bauerle, Mrs. Clinton was on WKBW-TV's "AM Buffalo
Show" where she defended the choices she has made in her marriage.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think anybody who's ever been married knows that you have ups and downs
and there are high points and low points," she said.
</P>
<P>
	   "I know people are interested, but this is something that - I'm going to
have to live my own way and make my own decisions about," she said.
</P>
<P>
	   On the subject she DID want to talk about, Mrs. Clinton told reporters she
would formally announce her candidacy in Westchester County on Feb. 6. Mrs.
Clinton recently moved in to a $1.7 million house she and President Clinton
purchased in the county just north of New York City.
</P>
<P>
	   After her announcement, Mrs. Clinton said she would embark on a tour of the
state, but that given the season it would not be a reprise of the bus tour that
kicked off her husband's 1992 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think it'll be more a van-and-Suburban-and-four-wheel-drive tour, because
I want to go throughout the state," she said.
</P>
<P>
	   Aides said they expected the tour to last about a week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
