<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 00:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A hard sell: arguing that $40 an hour is grossly unfair  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Here is the challenge Chief Judge Judith Kaye is
taking on in 2000: convincing people that paying someone $40 an hour is, as she
puts it, "absolutely ludicrous" and "totally unrealistic."
<P>
	   She doesn't mean ludicrously too much, she means ludicrously too little.
Kaye wants to substantially raise the amount earned by lawyers assigned by
courts to represent indigent defendants.
</P>
<P>
	   Trying to convince taxpayers that more of their money should go to
"underpaid" lawyers - especially to represent possible criminals - is about as
easy a sell as ... say hawking suntan lotion in January in Syracuse or selling
Tennessee Titans jerseys at a Buffalo Bills game.
</P>
<P>
	   Currently, "assigned" counsels in New York get $40 an hour for in-court work
and $25 an hour for out-of-court work. Those pay levels have been unchanged
since 1986. Kaye wants the fees to go up to $75 an hour for felony and Family
Court cases and $60 an hour for nonfelony cases.
</P>
<P>
	   She said it would cost about $71.8 million a year to pay for the higher
assigned counsel fees. Court administrators are starting a program they think
could ultimately generate that kind of money - hiring private collection
agencies to go after court-imposed fines and surcharges which now are not being
paid.
</P>
<P>
	   This is not a matter of the state's legal system looking out for its own,
Kaye insists. She said assigned counsels are a bulwark of the justice process
because they guarantee that the poorest defendants still get adequate
representation in court. The entire legal system suffers if any class of
defendants are disenfranchised because of money, the chief judge argued.
</P>
<P>
	   But with the "low" $40 and $25 fee levels, the pools of lawyers willing to
be assigned have shrunk and the whole assigned counsel system is in "crisis,"
according to the chief judge. Lawyers with too little experience are handling
too many cases as assigned counsels, she said.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1989 in the judicial system's Eastern Department - encompassing most of
eastern New York north of New York City - 940 lawyers were taking court
assignments in criminal cases. Today, only about 300 attorneys are doing so,
court administrators say.
</P>
<P>
	   While the pool of available lawyers has been shrinking, the number of cases
in criminal and Family Courts have been skyrocketing.
</P>
<P>
	   The state Office of Court Administration released a report this month
designed to bolster Kaye's argument for boosting the lawyers' fees.
</P>
<P>
	   It found that only New Jersey, with a $30-an-hour in-court and $25-an-hour
out-of-court scale, pays assigned counsels less. Massachusetts' payment
schedule, more complicated than New York's, is roughly equivalent.
</P>
<P>
	   Some of the states New Yorkers like to think of as poorer and more backward
than New York allot their assigned counsels more, including Arkansas (an average
of $80 to $85 an hour), Georgia (up to $60 an hour) and Alabama (up to $50 an
hour).
</P>
<P>
	   Other court-appointed experts in New York get much more for their time than
assigned lawyers, the report noted. They include psychologists ($90 an hour),
psychiatrists ($125 an hour) and physicians ($200 an hour).
</P>
<P>
	   As persuasive as Kaye's argument for giving assigned counsels higher fees
is, she is laboring against both perception and reality in her campaign to get
the governor and Legislature to approve higher fees.
</P>
<P>
	   Her State of the Judiciary address this month noted that the reputations of
the legal and judicial systems are in need of burnishing. Lawyers rarely finish
high in polls of professionals held in high esteem.
</P>
<P>
	   "We have to make sure that the public understands that courts provide more
than just prime time plotlines," she said. "Courts protect our fundamental
liberties. And lawyers aren't just fodder for punch lines. Lawyers help keep
this society orderly and free, a model for the world."
</P>
<P>
	   The reality of the working lives of New Yorkers is that the state's per
capita income is about $30,000. That translates to a per-hour wage of $14 for a
40-hour week. That makes $40 an hour seem pretty generous, especially if the
taxpayers making $14 an hour are footing the bill.
</P>
<P>
	   That's apparently the mathematics Gov. George Pataki is looking at. He says
he does "not intend" to agree to higher assigned counsel rates. State Assembly
Speaker Sheldon Silver, on the other hand, said the rates are too low and wants
to see them go up.
</P>
<P>
	   To be fair, $40 an hour is poor compensation in the realm of the legal
profession, where a good defense lawyer in upstate New York can command
$200-$250 an hour in a criminal case from well-heeled clients. Top-notch
defenders in New York City, where a lawyer's overhead costs are higher, charge
even more.
</P>
<P>
	   With that in mind, the state Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers has a
different opinion about the fee schedule. It said $30 or $45 an hour for
assigned counsels is "abysmally" low, and $60 or $75 isn't that much better.
</P>
<P>
	   Its president-elect, Kathryn Kase, is urging Kaye to push for $100 an hour.
</P>
<P>
	   ----
</P>
<P>
	   Joel Stashenko is Capitol Editor for The Associated Press in Albany. He can
be reached at P.O. Box 7165, Albany, N.Y., 12224.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-20-00 0037 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000120.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 00:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Group calls on Bush not to pick pro-casino Pataki as VP  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - George Bush should not pick George Pataki as a
running mate because the New York governor has authorized Indian casinos and
wants to legalize non-Indian casinos as well, a group is contending.
<P>
	   The organization, the New York Institute for Law in Society, took out a
full-page advertisement in Wednesday's Manchester (N.H.) Union Leader newspaper
urging Bush not to select Pataki.
</P>
<P>
	   The Union Leader will be the first of several newspapers to run the ad as
the Republican presidential primaries near, according to the group.
</P>
<P>
	   The ad is designed as an open letter to Texas Gov. Bush, the frontrunner to
capture the Republican nomination for president in 2000. It urges Bush to
"review" Pataki's record on casinos before considering him as a vice
presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
	   "The 2000 Republican National ticket cannot have a candidate who supports
the proliferation of casino gambling," the organization said.
</P>
<P>
	   A leader of the Rome, N.Y.-based group, Tom Hunter, said it believes Pataki
has illegally entered into a compact which is allowing Mohawk Indians to operate
a casino on their land near the United States-Canadian border. The group is
arguing - along with other gambling foes and Democratic state legislators - that
Pataki needed the approval of the Legislature before the state could enter into
any gaming compacts with tribes.
</P>
<P>
	   Indians are also seeking to open other casinos in New York, and the Pataki
administration is involved in wide-ranging discussions with New York tribes
about casinos, Indian land claims and other issues.
</P>
<P>
	   Pataki has said he does not like casinos, but believes that since two Indian
casinos are already operating, the state should allow non-Indian casinos to open
in some areas of New York. That way, the state can profit from the gambling
revenues, he said. The Legislature has refused to go along with his casino
legislation.
</P>
<P>
	   Hunter said the group may take out the ad again in New Hampshire, where the
first-in-the-nation presidential primary will be held Feb. 1. The group also
plans to run the ad in Thursday's Des Moines Register in Iowa, which is holding
its presidential caucuses on Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   The ad will also be in the Albany (N.Y.) Times Union on Thursday, group
officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   "We hope people pay attention to it," said Hunter, who lives in Syracuse.
"We hope George W. Bush pays attention to it."
</P>
<P>
	   Hunter said his group is conservative in philosophy and is not aligned with
a political party. He refused to disclose its sources of money or how much it
planned to spend on the anti-Pataki ads.
</P>
<P>
	   Pataki is considered a long-shot to be tapped by Bush as a running mate.
Pataki and most of the rest of the New York Republican Party organization have
endorsed Bush for president.
</P>
<P>
	   Scott McClellan, a spokesman for the Bush campaign, said it is "way too
premature" to be discussing Bush's vice presidential selection.
</P>
<P>
	   "Gov. Bush is focused on earning the presidential nomination," McClellan
said. "Gov. Pataki is a good friend, a strong supporter and Gov. Bush
appreciates his serving as his state campaign chair in New York."
</P>
<P>
	   Pataki spokeswoman and political adviser Zenia Mucha called the ad "silly"
and "not even accurate."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-20-00 0037 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000120.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
