<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    Thursday, Jan. 20, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mideast Peace Deadline May Be Missed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration acknowledged Wednesday that
Israel and the Palestinians may miss a mid-February deadline for concluding the
outline of a final settlement of their long dispute. With Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat due to call at the White House on Thursday, State Department
spokesman James P. Rubin said if Israel and the Palestinians delayed there would
be no framework agreement by Feb. 13 or a formal settlement by the fall, as
planned. "It's our view that the parties have some tough decisions to make," he
said. These include whether the Palestinians are to have a state, whether
Jerusalem is to be shared by Israel with Arafat and how much more land Israel
will turn over to his Authority.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
WTO Chief Calls for Reassessment
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The World Trade Organization needs to think about
doing things "differently" in the wake of talks in Seattle that ground to a halt
in the wake of anti-WTO protests, the organization's director-general said
Wednesday. There would be no "short-term fix" to the problems highlighted at
Seattle, said Mike Moore after addressing a U.N. senior management meeting
chaired by Secretary-General Kofi Annan. In the days following the Nov. 29
opening of the WTO's meeting in Seattle, an estimated 45,000 people took to the
streets to rally against the trade organization's policies.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Report: Hunger Persists in America
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   BOSTON (AP) -- In these times of low unemployment and overnight stock market
fortunes, 30 million Americans worry about where they will get their next meals,
according to a new study. The number of Americans who go hungry has held steady
for the last four years, despite unprecedented economic growth, the Center on
Hunger and Poverty at Tufts University found. The Tufts study is billed as the
most comprehensive analysis of domestic hunger since welfare was overhauled in
1996. Researchers pulled together federal and state estimates on hunger, along
with reports from food banks and shelters.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.N. Urges Enlarged Presence in Congo
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The U.N. chief on Wednesday recommended a dramatic
increase in the small U.N. contingent in Congo to better monitor a shaky
cease-fire and pave the way for an eventual U.N. peacekeeping force.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan urged the Security Council deploy a total of 5,537
troops, up from the current 90 military liaison officers authorized. The total
would include 500 military observers and 3,400 soldiers to provide security.
Also included are two marine units to make use of Congo's inland waterway system
and logistical, medical and communications officers.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Researchers Warn About La Nina
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Unusual weather driven by La Nina cooling in the Pacific
Ocean may be part of a larger, longer-lasting climate shift, researchers said
Wednesday after analyzing new satellite data. If the interpretation is correct,
the Southern states, as well as the Southwest, could be in for 20 years or more
of mild and relatively dry winters while the Pacific Northwest and the East
could get socked by strong winter storms. The Pacific Ocean's surface water
temperature is a dominant force behind storm intensity as well as the path of
the jet stream.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Touts $110B Health Plan
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton Wednesday unveiled a whopping $110
billion package of health insurance initiatives for his final year in office,
asking the Republican-dominated Congress to approve the largest investment in
health care since Medicare was created in 1965. Less expensive versions of the
programs died last year, in part because of the president's own veto of the
Republicans' $792 billion tax-cutting plan. "These proposals are a significant
investment in the health of Americans, another step toward giving every American
access to quality health care," the president said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Rise in Early Trading
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks rose moderately Thursday. The Nikkei gained
147.42 points to 19,045.17 in early trading. In New York on Wednesday, the Dow
Jones industrial average fell 71.36 points to close at 11,489.36.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Blazers Defeat Spurs 105-95
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- Rasheed Wallace scored 22 points and helped end Tim
Duncan's streak of 61 straight double-figure scoring games as the Portland
Trailblazers beat the San Antonio Spurs 105-95 Wednesday night. It was the first
meeting between the teams since the Spurs swept the Blazers 4-0 in the Western
Conference finals last season on their way to the NBA title. If the Blazers
wanted to make a statement against the defending champs, it came across loud and
clear. Bouncing back from its first two-game losing streak of the season,
Portland never trailed and held a double-figure lead most of the second half.
</P>
<P>
	   AP NewsBrief by ELIZABETH A. KENNEDY
</P>
