<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Olympic Snub Miffs Sprinter Bailey  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TORONTO (AP) -- If sprinter Donovan Bailey wants to race at the 2000 Sydney
Olympics, he's going to have to earn the chance.
</P>
<P>
	The Canadian Olympic Association on Wednesday released a list of athletes who
already have achieved the selection standard for the Summer Games, and Bailey
was not among them.
</P>
<P>
	That means, despite winning the gold medal at the previous Olympics in Atlanta
in 1996, Bailey has to run the 100 meters in 10.23 seconds or better by Aug. 13
or miss out on the Games.
</P>
<P>
	Bailey, 32, suffered a rupture of his Achilles tendon in September 1998 and
returned to competitive track on June 12, 1999.
</P>
<P>
	While he was healthy for most of last season, he was never in top race shape,
and his best time was 10.19. Because the time was wind-aided, however, it was
not considered an official time and does not count toward team qualification.
</P>
<P>
	Athletics Canada president John Thresher said it would be ``an interesting
idea'' for the COA to consider pre-selecting defending Olympic champions to the
team without forcing them to make domestic standards. But Thresher said he is
confident Bailey will achieve the standard this season without much difficulty.
</P>
<P>
	``It would (have been nice),'' Bailey said when asked if he should have been
pre-selected to the team. ``But I can't worry about that. I have got to do what
I've got to do and that is get ready to compete.
</P>
<P>
	``I am not running for accolades, but a little bit of respect would be nice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
