<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Disclosures Barred in Diallo Case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- A jury will not be allowed to hear that three of the
four New York City police officers accused of fatally shooting an African
immigrant were involved in past shootings.
</P>
<P>
	   Justice Joseph C. Teresi also rejected a motion filed by eight news
organizations seeking to open all hearings and papers to the press.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It would be horrific to have similar circumstances concerning publicity
occur again,'' he wrote in Wednesday's decision. An appeals court moved the
trial to Albany because of pretrial publicity.
</P>
<P>
	   Officers Sean Carroll, Edward McMellon, Richard Murphy and Kenneth Boss were
indicted on second-degree murder charges in March after they fired 41 bullets at
Diallo while searching a neighborhood for a rape suspect. Defense attorneys say
the officers mistakenly believed Diallo was reaching for a gun.
</P>
<P>
	   According to reports, a grand jury cleared Boss of wrongdoing after he shot
and killed an armed man in 1997. In 1998, a suspect shot at Carroll and Carroll
fired back, but missed. McMellon wounded an armed man in 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   Jury selection is set to begin Jan. 31.
</P>
</TEXT>
