<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.M. OKs Foreign-Language Jurors  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA FE, N.M. (AP) -- The state Supreme Court has upheld a ruling that
people cannot be disqualified from serving as jurors because they don't speak
English.
</P>
<P>
	   The court unanimously denied a request from Dona Ana County District
Attorney Susana Martinez to overturn a ruling by a judge in Las Cruces. That
judge had ruled that non-English-speaking people could not be kept off juries
and required the court to provide interpreters to accompany jurors who do not
speak English.
</P>
<P>
	   In Wednesday's high court ruling, Chief Justice Pamela Minzner quoted the
state Constitution, which says residents cannot be restricted from sitting on
juries on account of an inability to speak, read or write English or Spanish.
</P>
<P>
	   Melissa Reeves, an attorney for the state, said statewide procedures will be
set up for non-English-speaking jurors.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is the ruling we expected,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
	   The Dona Ana County district attorney's office had argued against allowing
non-English-speaking jurors, warning that inexact translations could cause
problems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
