<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 01:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Union Membership Rises in U.S.  </HEADLINE>
   By TOM VERDIN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Claudia Johnson divides her working career into two
phases: pre-union and afterward.
</P>
<P>
	   She is one of more than 70,000 Los Angeles County home care workers who
unionized last year, helping propel union membership nationwide to its largest
increase in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
	   Nationwide, the number of union members was 16.5 million in 1999, an
increase of 265,000 from the year before, the Labor Department's Bureau of Labor
Statistics reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Labor leaders estimated that at least 600,000 workers joined up in 1999,
although the net gain was 265,000. And while the country added 2.7 million jobs
last year, the overall percentage of workers who carry a union card remained at
13.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Still, one particularly bright spot for labor leaders was the number of
workers who organized in fields not traditionally associated with unions,
including doctors and the Los Angeles home care aides.
</P>
<P>
	   Before voting to join the Service Employees International Union last
February, home care workers were subjected to a variety of poor working
conditions, said Johnson, 65, who has bathed, fed, medicated and cleaned up for
elderly or disabled clients for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
	   Workers' checks would sometimes arrive months late, they had to work when
sick because there was no one to cover for them and many worked overtime for
which they were never paid, she said.
</P>
<P>
	   The union negotiated an 8 percent raise, implemented a screening process for
applicants and instituted a number of work rules that have better defined the
job.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think it made us feel better about the job we do,'' Johnson said. ``A
lot of people want to get into it now because of the union.''
</P>
<P>
	   Labor leaders are hoping for more of the same in other fields. They said the
growth in union numbers should translate into more political clout for organized
labor in this year's elections.
</P>
<P>
	   ``In the year 2000, you're going to see the largest and most significant
activity that grassroots workers have exercised in any political election,''
said AFL-CIO President John J. Sweeney, whose organization has endorsed Vice
President Al Gore for president.
</P>
<P>
	   Expected to add to that clout are the 112,493 new members working in the
private sector that unions added to their rolls in 1999.
</P>
<P>
	   Traditionally, government employees and contractors have been the stronghold
of the labor movement. While that remains the case, union organizers note that
this year's gain in the private sector reverses a membership decline in that
area that had been going on since 1978.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The private sector growth is a clear sign that our efforts to think
strategically and creatively are beginning to bear fruit,'' said Kirk Adams, the
AFL-CIO's organizing director.
</P>
<P>
	   The novel approach has been to spread the union gospel through a variety of
occupations, not just the jobs that require hard hats. For example, in the last
year, 45,000 doctors joined unions.
</P>
<P>
	   Some high-tech and communications workers also are beginning to explore
unions at computer giant Microsoft, Internet retailer Amazon.com, computer maker
IBM and telecommunications giant AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
	   Still, the Labor Department reports that 37 percent of government workers,
including local police and firefighters are union members, compared with only
about 9 percent of private sector employees.
</P>
<P>
	   It is too early for unions to declare a high-tech victory, said economist
Ken Goldstein of the Conference Board, a business-sponsored study group in New
York.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Unless they can start to organize the office, days like this are going to
be few and far between,'' he said. ``For all the good news this is from their
point of view, this is a quite limited and perhaps a quite temporary
celebration.''
</P>
<P>
	   Adams said that for unions to continue to grow in a rapidly expanding
economy they must add between 500,000 and a million workers a year -- not a
small hurdle because so many union jobs are lost to attrition. Labor leaders
estimated that at least 600,000 workers joined up in 1999, although the net gain
was 265,000.
</P>
<P>
	   And while the country added 2.7 million jobs last year, the overall
percentage of workers who carry a union card remained at 13.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Unions now are trying to win over future workers before they hit the job
market. For example, Sweeney on Wednesday was headed to Dartmouth College in New
Hampshire to woo students.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We're turning the corner, but we're not at our destination yet,'' Sweeney
said. ``Our challenge for the future is to remain focused and to broaden our
efforts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-20-00 0115 </TRAILER>
