<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 01:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German FM Poised for Top IMF Post  </HEADLINE>
    By HANS GREIMEL Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- German officials have renewed their campaign to
promote German Deputy Finance Minister Caio Koch-Weser as the next head of the
International Monetary Fund, creating a stir as finance ministers from the
world's seven richest nations head to Tokyo for a weekend meeting.
</P>
<P>
	   The Brazilian-born German is viewed by supporters as a balanced
representative of the developing countries, which get help from the
international fund -- and the rich, Western nations, which are its largest
contributors.
</P>
<P>
	   Picking a successor to current head Michel Camdessus is not officially on
the Group of Seven agenda, but there will be plenty of talk in the hallways when
the finance ministers meet Saturday, given Camdessus' scheduled exit next month.
</P>
<P>
	   With both France and the United States cool on Koch-Weser for lacking a
high-profile and hard-core financial background, German Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder has intensified the campaign to put his candidate at the helm of the
182-nation organization based in Washington.
</P>
<P>
	   Ahead of the G7 finance meeting, Schroeder sent letters to the 24 countries
that make up the IMF's executive committee promoting Koch-Weser as a competent
adviser and good negotiator. Schroeder's chief foreign policy adviser, Michael
Steiner, summoned ambassadors of 42 countries to further pitch the Koch-Weser
candidacy on Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Schroeder put the push in high gear after France indicated last week it was
promoting former Prime Minister Laurent Fabius. But France has already chosen
three of the last four IMF heads, including Camdessus, and Fabius described
speculation that he was a candidate "flattering" but untrue.
</P>
<P>
	   Others vying for the job -- which has always been held by a European --
include Italian Treasury Director Mario Draghi and two Brits -- British
Chancellor of the Exchequer Gordon Brown and Andrew Crockett, who heads the Bank
of International Settlements in Basel, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
	   Japan also is promoting former vice finance minister for international
affairs, Eisuke Sakakibara -- known as "Mr. Yen" for his influence on currency
markets.
</P>
<P>
	   A German has never held the job, and Koch-Weser -- who has 26 years of
international experience at the World Bank -- would be a natural choice, his
supporters say.
</P>
<P>
	   "Germany is growing in influence and it is playing a more important role in
the international forum, so I think it would be very healthy for the world, if
you could find Germans like Koch-Weser to play a bigger role," said Peter Eigen,
a former World Bank colleague who now leads Transparency International, a
Berlin-based group dedicated to fighting political corruption.
</P>
<P>
	   Koch-Weser rose quickly through the ranks at the World Bank, serving first
as an economist and then as a health projects officer for the organization,
which works closely with the IMF to finance development projects, mostly in
poorer countries.
</P>
<P>
	   He also created and administered a joint IMF-World Bank project in Ghana
that retrained workers in the bloated public sector for private sector jobs, and
worked on an anti-corruption campaign to ensure bank funds actually reached
their intended recipients.
</P>
<P>
	   He had been promoted to managing director at the bank when Germany's Finance
Ministry recruited him in April to strengthen Schroeder's Cabinet after
then-Finance Minister Oskar Lafontaine resigned in a political spat.
</P>
<P>
	   Eigen said Koch-Weser's strength is being able to build consensus without
twisting arms -- a key to dealing with some of the critical issues the IMF now
faces, including the integration of Russia and Africa into the world economy, as
well as bringing China into the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
	   But Koch-Weser also has no experience as a top finance minister or central
bank governor, and that makes him a less attractive candidate to IMF members who
value a foundation in economics and finance.
</P>
<P>
	   That will play a major role as pressure mounts for the IMF to restructure
itself -- particularly in the United States, which has criticized the fund for
its loans to Russia and its handling of the Asian crisis.
</P>
<P>
	   There are also political obstacles to his candidacy. Japan is the IMF's
second-largest financial contributor after the United States, and has repeatedly
demanded a bigger voice in the organization. Already several major Asian
nations, as well as Russia, have openly supported Sakakibara's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
	   At the same time, the United States has given Koch-Weser a lukewarm
reception -- partly from an interest in keeping the spot open for U.S. Treasury
Secretary Lawrence Summers, who could lose his job after the upcoming
presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
	   In the meantime, Camdessus' deputy, Stanley Fischer, is expected to fill in
for at least part of his boss' remaining two-year term.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-20-00 0122 </TRAILER>
