<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Korean Peninsula Nukes Opposed  </HEADLINE>
   By SANG-HUN CHOE Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- In a rare joint stand, China and South Korea
warned today that proliferation of nuclear and other weapons of mass destruction
on the Korean Peninsula would touch off an arms race in the region.
</P>
<P>
	   The two former adversaries took that view when their defense chiefs met and
reviewed security on the peninsula, the world's last Cold War frontier, South
Korean officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The two defense ministers voiced their opposition to proliferation of
weapons of mass destruction on the Korean Peninsula, such as nuclear and
biological and chemical weapons,'' South Korean Defense Ministry spokesman Yoon
Il-young said.
</P>
<P>
	   Chinese Defense Minister Chi Haotian flew into Seoul on Wednesday for a
five-day visit and met President Kim Dae-jung. The first visit to Seoul by a
Chinese defense chief, it was seen by South Korea as a diplomatic coup over its
rival North Korea.
</P>
<P>
	   In today's meeting with his South Korean counterpart, Cho Sung-tae, Chi
urged the two Koreas not to develop weapons of mass destruction, saying
stability on the divided peninsula is vital to regional peace, ministry
officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   Chi's remarks were in line with Beijing's policy -- but South Korean
officials saw them as directed more at Pyongyang, a longtime China ally, than
Seoul.
</P>
<P>
	   North Korea has frozen its suspect nuclear weapons program under a 1994
accord with the United States. Its missile, chemical and biological warfare
capabilities have raised a new spate of alarm in the region.
</P>
<P>
	   South Korea's 2000 defense white paper, released in December, said North
Korea has boosted its stockpile of chemical weapons fivefold over the years to
5,000 tons. The North is also believed to have stockpiled anthrax and nine other
types of biological weapons, it said.
</P>
<P>
	   South Korea says it has no weapons of mass destruction on its soil, but some
U.S. experts believe the Seoul government possesses chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
	   Chi's trip signals closer ties between China and South Korea. While wanting
more investment and trade with the South, Beijing so far has tried to keep its
military contacts to a minimum to avoid offending North Korea. China fought on
North Korea's side during the 1950-53 Korean War and has since remained the
closest ally of the isolated communist country.
</P>
<P>
	   During today's meeting, South Korea's Cho proposed that his country and
China exchange visits of military officers, port calls by navy ships and open a
regular dialogue between the two defense ministries, ministry officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   Chi's response was not immediately known.
</P>
<P>
	   China opened diplomatic relations with South Korea in 1992. China is
currently South Korea's third-largest trading partner, while South Korea is
China's fifth largest.
</P>
<P>
	   Besides South Korea, Chi's visit is part of a tour of stops in Britain,
Russia and Mongolia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-20-00 0129 </TRAILER>
