<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 01:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Italian Premier Craxi Dies  </HEADLINE>
   By FRANCES D'EMILIO Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ROME (AP) -- Bettino Craxi, a Socialist who defied Washington and stood up
to Italy's powerful communists during a record term as premier, died in Tunisia,
where he fled to avoid a prison sentence for corruption convictions. He was 65.
</P>
<P>
	   Craxi died Wednesday of a heart attack at his seaside villa in Hammamet,
said his lawyer, Giannino Giuso.
</P>
<P>
	   Craxi had suffered for years from heart problems and other complications of
diabetes. In November, a Milan court ruled he could return to Italy for bypass
surgery on condition he serve his corruption sentence under house arrest. Craxi
refused.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'd only return as a free man. Any different way, I won't return, nor
alive nor dead,'' Craxi said in an interview with RAI Italian state TV.
</P>
<P>
	   His daughter, Stefania, expressed bitterness Wednesday over what she said
was her father's abandonment by his country and many former political allies.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They killed him,'' she said, referring to some of Italy's prosecutors and
politicians and ``all the friends who turned their backs on him.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``He died like a dog,'' Stefania said, speaking in an interview with RAI
from her father's villa.
</P>
<P>
	   Craxi was Italy's longest-serving premier of the postwar years, holding two
back-to-back terms from August 1983 to March 1987, a remarkable feat in a
country of ``revolving door'' governments.
</P>
<P>
	   He stood up to the United States in 1985, refusing to hand over the
Palestinian commandos who hijacked the Achille Lauro cruise ship and killed an
elderly American passenger, Leon Klinghoffer.
</P>
<P>
	   But Craxi also defied Italian communists -- the largest communist party in
the West and a big-vote getter in Italian politics -- by allowing NATO
nuclear-tipped missiles to be installed in Sicily.
</P>
<P>
	   Craxi was delighted by his political staying power. He once recalled his
reception by other European leaders at a summit in Germany in 1985. ``The other
members looked at me, seemingly relieved -- as if to say, `Oh, we know him, it's
the same guy we saw at the last meeting,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The best vacation is power,'' Craxi once said. Those words came back to
haunt him when his Socialists, along with the Christian Democrats they ruled
with in several coalition governments, were disgraced by the inquiries begun by
Milan's ``Clean Hands'' prosecutors in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
	   They eventually uncovered a well-oiled system in which businessmen filled
party coffers or politicians' pockets with hundreds of millions of dollars in
exchange for deals with the sprawling state economy.
</P>
<P>
	   Throughout the scandal, Craxi maintained he was an innocent victim of a
vendetta by jealous politicians.
</P>
<P>
	   He fled Italy in 1994, and a year later a Milan court declared him a
fugitive from justice. Two convictions have been upheld by Italy's highest
criminal appeals court, with sentences of 5 1/2 and 4 1/2 years in corruption
cases. He was absolved in three other cases.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He's not a saint but a politician who did some good for Italians. That's
why he was persecuted by his enemies,'' said Rocco Buttiglione, a former
Christian Democrat.
</P>
<P>
	   Born Benedetto Craxi in Milan on Feb. 24, 1934, the future premier was the
son of a Sicilian lawyer who left the island to migrate north. Craxi dropped out
of the University of Milan for the world of politics.
</P>
<P>
	   He was first elected to Parliament in 1968. A decade later, as Socialists
became the key to forming a government without the communists, Craxi worked to
move his party away from the communists and became its leader in 1981.
</P>
<P>
	   Craxi's daughter, Stefania, said he would be buried in Tunisia.
</P>
<P>
	   Besides his daughter, survivors include his wife, Anna, and son, Bobo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-20-00 0138 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000120.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 01:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jury selection begins in second Louima case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - A federal judge began the tedious process of choosing a
jury for the second trial in the Abner Louima police-torture case by selecting
four potential jurors out of a pool of 500.
<P>
	   A teacher who served in the Marines and a Bell Atlantic employee of
Vietnamese descent survived the initial cut Wednesday, saying nothing in their
views or experience would prevent them from being able to reach a fair verdict.
</P>
<P>
	   Asked about the so-called "blue wall of silence" among police officers, the
silver-haired ex-Marine said, "I think that such behavior occurs in all
professions to some extent."
</P>
<P>
	   He said he believes "cops operate under duress, and not all handle that
duress well."
</P>
<P>
	   Former officer Charles Schwarz, 35, and officers Thomas Wiese, 37, and
Thomas Bruder, 34, are accused of conspiring to obstruct justice by concealing
Schwarz's alleged role in the brutal precinct-house attack on Louima, a Haitian
immigrant, following his arrest on a minor charge in 1997.
</P>
<P>
	   Former officer Justin Volpe is serving a 30-year term after pleading guilty
to violating Louima's civil rights. Schwarz was convicted and faces a life
sentence, but Volpe now claims Schwarz was not involved.
</P>
<P>
	   The officers, all of whom are white, face five years in prison on the
conspiracy charge. Louima is black.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. District Judge Eugene Nickerson wants to pare a jury pool of more than
500 to 75, then pick a panel from that smaller group by Jan. 31. The task is
complicated by widespread publicity and tensions generated by the racially
explosive case.
</P>
<P>
	   By day's end, four prospective jurors, three men and one woman, were
retained and three other men were dismissed.
</P>
<P>
	   Nickerson quizzed the candidates closely about their answers to a written
questionnaire, especially what they knew of the case and whether they had ever
been exposed to racism. Most said they had been.
</P>
<P>
	   The teacher said his son had undergone therapy after suffering "harassment"
by a group of Haitian and Hispanic youths, but said that would not affect his
own ability to reach an honest verdict.
</P>
<P>
	   "There are always going to be some people who are prejudiced to some extent
... I try to look at who that person is rather than the ethnic or racial
background," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Under persistent questioning by Nickerson, the man said he believed police
might be justified in using "more force than necessary" if their lives are in
danger.
</P>
<P>
	   Another prospective panelist, a retired engineer, also said the "blue wall
of silence" exists.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think it probably happens in some cases, but not in all cases," said the
man, who was excused.
</P>
<P>
	   A defense systems programmer, 60 years old and white, said he had not been
subjected to racism but has known people who were bigoted.
</P>
<P>
	   "There are always bigoted people - there's a lot of that in the world," he
said.
</P>
<P>
	   That would-be juror also said he had "no respect" for black activist the
Rev. Al Sharpton, who led a series of anti-police marches protesting the Louima
attack. "I don't believe he helps his people at all," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   He also questioned Schwarz's conviction, since " the man who committed the
crime said he wasn't there."
</P>
<P>
	   Schwarz, seated at the defense table, did not visibly react.
</P>
<P>
	   Schwarz was convicted last year of violating Louima's civil rights by
holding him down while Volpe sodomized him with a broken broom stick. Volpe said
later that Wiese, not Schwarz, was the second officer present in the bathroom in
Brooklyn's 70th Precinct.
</P>
<P>
	   Stuart London and Joseph Tacopina, attorneys for Bruder and Wiese,
respectively, say their clients contend that Schwarz was never in the bathroom.
</P>
</TEXT>
