<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 01:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    Thursday, Jan. 20, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Israel, Palestinians May Miss Deadline
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration acknowledged Wednesday that
Israel and the Palestinians may miss a mid-February deadline for concluding the
outline of a final settlement of their long dispute. With Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat due to call at the White House on Thursday, State Department
spokesman James P. Rubin said if Israel and the Palestinians delayed there would
be no framework agreement by Feb. 13 or a formal settlement by the fall, as
planned. "It's our view that the parties have some tough decisions to make," he
said. These include whether the Palestinians are to have a state, whether
Jerusalem is to be shared by Israel with Arafat and how much more land Israel
will turn over to his Authority.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fatal Dormitory Fire Under Investigation
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SOUTH ORANGE, N.J. (AP) -- The cause of the fire that killed three people at
a Seton Hall University dormitory early Wednesday is under investigation. The
fire broke out as hundreds slept, sending terrified students crawling in pajamas
through smoke into the freezing cold. Sixty-two people were injured, one of them
suffering third-degree burns over most of his body. Two of the three male
students killed were found in the lounge and the other was found in a bedroom
nearby. The victims, all 18, were identified by the Essex County medical
examiner's office as Frank S. Caltabilota, John N. Giunta and Aaron C. Karol.
The office did not release their home towns, but friends and relatives said all
were from New Jersey.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
WTO Chief Calls for Reassessment
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The World Trade Organization needs to think about
doing things "differently" in the wake of talks in Seattle that ground to a halt
in the wake of anti-WTO protests, the organization's director-general said
Wednesday. There would be no "short-term fix" to the problems highlighted at
Seattle, said Mike Moore after addressing a U.N. senior management meeting
chaired by Secretary-General Kofi Annan. In the days following the Nov. 29
opening of the WTO's meeting in Seattle, an estimated 45,000 people took to the
streets to rally against the trade organization's policies.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
China, S.Korea Take Stand on Nukes
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- In a rare joint stand, China and South Korea
warned Thursday that proliferation of nuclear and other weapons of mass
destruction on the Korean Peninsula would touch off an arms race in the region.
The two former adversaries took that view when their defense chiefs met and
reviewed security on the peninsula, the world's last Cold War frontier, South
Korean officials said. "The two defense ministers voiced their opposition to
proliferation of weapons of mass destruction on the Korean Peninsula, such as
nuclear and biological and chemical weapons," South Korean Defense Ministry
spokesman Yoon Il-young said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Reform Party Looks To Make Amends
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Reform Party faction leaders are planning a face-to-face
meeting next month to settle disputes that are threatening the party's survival
and its influence on the presidential race. But peace may not be at hand, key
leaders said. "A small group of approximately 20 people could, because of their
position (as Reform Party leaders), literally destroy the party," National
Chairman Jack Gargan said Wednesday from Florida, referring to supporters of
party founder Ross Perot. "If we could get rid of those 20 people, that would
solve everything."
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
New Dietary Standards Target Fat, Alcohol
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Nutrition experts rewriting the nation's dietary
guidelines will likely specify for the first time who might benefit from
moderate consumption of alcohol: middle-aged men and women. The proposed new
guidelines, expected to be made public soon by an 11-member advisory committee,
also will tell Americans to cut down on foods rich in saturated fats such as
meat and dairy products, according to a working draft of the standards. They
will include a change in wording intended to make it easier for consumers to
adhere to the maximum fat intake -- renaming the maximum as "moderate" in fat,
instead of "low in fat, according to a working draft of the new standards.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Close Higher
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- The Nikkei Stock Average closed at 19,008.01 points on the
Tokyo Stock Exchange Thursday, up 110.26 points from Wednesday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Lakers Defeat Cavaliers 95-86
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Shaquille O'Neal scored eight of his 27 points in the
fourth quarter and also had 23 rebounds Wednesday night as the Los Angeles
Lakers rallied for a 95-86 victory over the Cleveland Cavaliers. The Lakers,
whose 33-7 record is the NBA's best, came back from a 15-point deficit in the
third period to win for the 18th time in 20 games, and 25th in 28 over the last
two months.
</P>
<P>
	   AP NewsBrief by ELIZABETH A. KENNEDY
</P>
</TEXT>
