<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 02:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge bars disclosure of Diallo cops' backgrounds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The jury in the trial of four officers accused of
murdering Amadou Diallo will not learn that three of the officers had been
involved in prior shootings, a judge has ruled.
<P>
	   The decision was one of several pretrial rulings by Justice Joseph C. Teresi
issued after a hearing in Albany on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Teresi also ordered prosecutors to turn over more evidence to the defense
and rejected a prosecution motion asking him to limit testimony by defense
expert witnesses.
</P>
<P>
	   At the same time, Teresi, who took over the case after it was moved to
Albany from the Bronx, decided that the new evidence and background information
would not be made public.
</P>
<P>
	   Plainclothes officers Sean Carroll, Edward McMellon, Richard Murphy and
Kenneth Boss were indicted on second-degree murder charges in March after they
fired 41 bullets at Diallo while searching a Bronx neighborhood for violent
criminals.
</P>
<P>
	   Diallo, struck 19 times, was dead at the scene. Attorneys for the officers
have claimed their clients mistakenly believed the street vendor, a West African
immigrant, was reaching for a gun.
</P>
<P>
	   An appeals court moved the trial upstate after accepting defense lawyers'
claims that pretrial publicity had made it impossible to seat an impartial jury
in the Bronx. The shooting involving white officers and a black victim touched
off weeks of protests alleging brutality against minorities.
</P>
<P>
	   A motion filed by eight news organizations had asked the judge to open all
hearings and papers to the press. But Teresi argued that full disclosure could
taint the jury.
</P>
<P>
	   "It would be horrific to have similar circumstances concerning publicity
occur again," he wrote.
</P>
<P>
	   According to past reports, Boss shot and killed a man armed with a shotgun
in Brooklyn in 1997, but a grand jury cleared him of wrongdoing. Three civilian
complaints alleging he used excessive force were all found to be
unsubstantiated.
</P>
<P>
	   Carroll had three unsubstantiated complaints alleging inappropriate use of
force. In August 1998, a suspect in the Bronx shot at him and Carroll fired
back, but missed.
</P>
<P>
	   McMellon wounded an armed man in Brooklyn in 1998. He has been accused five
times of using excessive force, abuse of authority or racial insensitivity, but
none of the complaints has been substantiated.
</P>
<P>
	   Murphy had no prior shooting incidents or civilian complaints.
</P>
<P>
	   Teresi argued that "past occurrences" involving the defendants were
"irrelevant and would prejudice the rights of the subject defendants."
</P>
<P>
	   McMellon's attorney, Stephen Worth, said he was confident the defendants,
who were not in court, would get a fair trial.
</P>
<P>
	   "Our officers shot Amadou Diallo - there's never been a question about
that," he said. "The question is under what circumstances. That's what this
trial is about."
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors declined comment.
</P>
<P>
	   The rulings clear the way for the defense to call two police training and
tactics experts and a psychologist as expert witnesses to try to convince the
jury the officers followed proper procedure. A prosecution motion had warned
that the witnesses may "be asked to offer opinions on ultimate matters which
would invade the province of the jury."
</P>
<P>
	   Jury selection is set to begin Jan. 31; the trial is expected to last up to
six weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
