<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 02:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three students dead, 62 injured in college dorm fire  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   SOUTH ORANGE, N.J. (AP) - The fire alarm blared through the dark
dormitory and most students turned over and went back to sleep, thinking it was
like all the others.
<P>
	   "I thought it was a joke," said Pete Tornatore, 18.
</P>
<P>
	   Instead of a prank, Seton Hall University freshmen woke Wednesday to a smoky
fire that swept through their dormitory, killing three classmates, injuring 62
and sending hundreds of students crawling or jumping out windows into the
predawn cold.
</P>
<P>
	   "It was panic. Everybody was just, "Go, go, go."' said Nicole McFarlane, 19,
of Summit, one of more than 600 students who fled the six-story Boland Hall.
</P>
<P>
	   Six students were critically burned, including one who suffered third-degree
burns over most of his body.
</P>
<P>
	   The cause of the fire, which began in and was largely contained to a
third-floor lounge, was under investigation. Students said that people
frequently smoked illegally in the lounge, but fire officials have ruled out
careless smoking or an electrical problem as the cause, The Star-Ledger of
Newark reported today, citing unspecified sources close to the investigation.
</P>
<P>
	   Instead, investigators are seeking information on three young men whom a
resident adviser had asked to leave the building less than an hour before the
fire broke out, the newspaper reported. Basketball fans had swarmed over the
campus after Seton Hall upset nationally ranked Big East conference rival St.
John's, 78-70, in East Rutherford Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
	   Essex County Prosecutor Donald Campolo declined to comment on what may have
caused the fire.
</P>
<P>
	   "It will be a painstaking investigation," Campolo said.
</P>
<P>
	   The 48-year-old dormitory was equipped with smoke alarms and 55 fire
extinguishers that had been recently inspected, but did not have a sprinkler
system because it was built before 1984 regulations requiring them, Campolo
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Firehoses had been disconnected last week and piled in the first floor for
removal because the equipment was obsolete, Seton Hall spokeswoman Lisa Grider
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Killed were Frank S. Caltabilota of West Long Branch, John N. Giunta of
Vineland and Aaron C. Karol of Green Brook. All were 18-year-old freshmen. Two
were found in the lounge and the third was found in a nearby bedroom, Campolo
said.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're pretty devastated," said Karol's father, Joseph, on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The fire stunned the 10,000-student, Roman Catholic university 15 miles from
New York City, bringing hundreds to a prayer service Wednesday night led by
Newark Archbishop Theodore McCarrick.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're glad we're people of faith," McCarrick said. "The mystery of God's
work is always a great mystery."
</P>
<P>
	   Many of the students thought the 4:30 a.m. fire alarm was another in a
string of 18 false alarms that have rung in the building since September. The
university had offered a reward for help finding a prankster.
</P>
<P>
	   But students soon heard screams for help, smelled choking smoke and saw
flames creep under the door.
</P>
<P>
	   "I opened the door just to check," said Yatin Patel. "All the ceiling tiles
were coming down. I saw a ceiling tile fall on someone."
</P>
<P>
	   He put a wet towel under his door, kicked out his window screens and threw
mattresses to the ground in case he would have to jump. Firefighters soon came
and got him and his roommate, who crawled holding on to each other's legs down
the corridor to a stairwell.
</P>
<P>
	   Nicholas Donato, 19, of Sparta, broke his wrist and ankle after leaping from
his third-floor bedroom.
</P>
<P>
	   "He said the smoke was so intense," said Anthony Donato, Nicholas' father.
"He knew where the exit was, and he could not find it."
</P>
<P>
	   Across the street, Mike Williams woke to frantic students banging on his
door, pleading for help. He went to his back yard, got his ladder, and helped
pull 14 students out of the window before firefighters arrived.
</P>
<P>
	   Several students were hanging out their windows, preparing to jump, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   "They were like, 'Please help us. Somebody save us,"' said Williams.
</P>
<P>
	   After stumbling out into the subfreezing cold, the soot-covered students
milled about the student center, some barefoot, others covering their pajamas
with blankets.
</P>
<P>
	   Lisa Sepulveda, an 18-year-old student from New York City, saw one man,
shirtless and burned, moaning as they fled the freshman dorm: "He looked like he
had painted his entire body. It was purple and blue and orange."
</P>
<P>
	   Classes for the university's 10,000 students were canceled for the week and
sports events were postponed through today.
</P>
<P>
	   The injured included two firefighters and two police officers, and injuries
ranged from smoke inhalation to severe burns. The majority had been treated and
released by Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Hani Mansour, chief of St. Barnabas Medical Center's burn unit, said three
18-year-old males were in the most serious condition with deep burns plus smoke
and heat damage to their throats and lungs.
</P>
<P>
	   "They are on a breathing machine, and they are very heavily sedated,"
Mansour said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
