<HEADLINE> Union Dockworkers Protest in S.C.  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) -- Police used dogs to disperse hundreds of dock
workers who pelted police with rocks as a labor dispute boiled over Wednesday
night. Several protesters were hurt.
</P>
<P>
	   As many as 600 International Longshoremen's Association workers were at the
city docks protesting the use of nonunion labor to unload a Nordana Line
freighter.
</P>
<P>
	   They arrived at midnight, hurling rocks and chanting ``ILA, ILA.'' News
photographers and television cameramen were struck with debris and beaten by
protesters before the violence ended two hours later.
</P>
<P>
	   The dogs were brought in as workers began to tear down spotlights police had
set up. Several protesters were hurt, but the extent of their injuries wasn't
immediately known. Police cars moved through the crowd and officers fired a
smoke grenade. One worker was hit by a police car.
</P>
<P>
	   By 1 a.m. Thursday, police began moving the protesters back toward the union
hall. Several protesters were arrested and the crowd was under control by 2
a.m., local media reported.
</P>
<P>
	   Police from across the state had been on the scene since Tuesday afternoon
in anticipation of the protest.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If you're training for some type of terrorist attack, I can understand
this response,'' Kenneth Riley Jr., president of ILA Local 1422, said earlier in
the day. ``But you're not dealing with a group of thugs here. These guys are
hardworking, good citizens of the city.''
</P>
<P>
	   But when the crowd got out of hand, Riley was unable to calm protesters. He
was escorted away from the scene by other ILA members.
</P>
<P>
	   The Nordana freighter Skodsborg docked Wednesday evening and was being
unloaded. It carried various types of cargo, including containers, said State
Ports Authority spokesman Byron Miller.
</P>
<P>
	   Nordana has refused to comment and no one at the company returned a phone
message left Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
