<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 02:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Candidate Surrogates Flood Iowa  </HEADLINE>
   By MIKE GLOVER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Bill Bradley sighed as he thought back to the early
days when he planned the logistics of his bid for the Democratic presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Iowa is a bigger state than I thought, in terms of media markets and in
terms of distance and in terms of the need to meet with people on a more
intimate basis,'' he said, explaining the reality that almost all politicians
who come here bemoan.
</P>
<P>
	   While Iowa is small in population, its sprawling 55,875 square miles make it
challenging to get around. It's an eight-hour drive from Burlington in the
southeast to Sioux City on the Nebraska border, and a six-hour trek, west to
east, from Council Bluffs to Davenport.
</P>
<P>
	   That means even the most industrious of candidates often need someone to fly
the flag on their behalf when they can't do it themselves. Hence, the stand-ins.
</P>
<P>
	   Even New Hampshire, far smaller than Iowa at 8,969 square miles, presents
some of the same challenges, with borders that extend from Massachusetts north
to Canada, interrupted by the White Mountains and forests in the North Country.
</P>
<P>
	   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the front-runner for the GOP presidential
nomination, left New Hampshire on Wednesday to concentrate on Iowa in advance of
Monday's caucuses. But not to neglect New Hampshire in the meantime, he was
being replaced by another campaign asset: his mother, popular former first lady
Barbara Bush.
</P>
<P>
	   Brother Jeb, the Florida governor, visited last weekend, and two other
brothers and sister Doro also plan trips before the Feb. 1 New Hampshire
primary.
</P>
<P>
	   In fact, with all of the presidential candidates campaigning today in Iowa,
surrogates were left to carry their messages across New Hampshire. Bradley has
former basketball greats Bill Russell, Dave DeBusschere, Tiny Archibald and K.C.
Jones. Commerce Secretary William Daley planned to stump for Vice President Al
Gore.
</P>
<P>
	   In Iowa, House Democratic Leader Richard Gephardt, a stand-in for Gore,
said: ``I have some friends in this state, from being here a lot. I think I've
helped in the early stages in convincing them to be for Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
	   In fact, Gephardt won the caucuses in 1988, has maintained a loyal band of
followers and has very close ties with organized labor. He met quietly Wednesday
with a handful of labor activists and inspected a voter turnout operation
humming in the union hall.
</P>
<P>
	   Nebraska Sen. Bob Kerrey has been active on Bradley's behalf, bringing a
special appeal to the table. Since Omaha's television market covers the western
part of Iowa, Kerrey is very well known in that part of the state.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There are so many surrogates out here that I'm getting outnumbered,'' he
chuckled.
</P>
<P>
	   Some surrogates can help translate support into votes.
</P>
<P>
	   Wayne Ford, the only African-American in the Iowa Legislature, backed Gore
on Wednesday. Less than 2 percent of Iowa's population is black, but Ford is an
important leader in that community. Gore campaign manager Donna Brazile made a
point of being on hand with Ford to stress the importance of turning out the
black vote.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's a small base but it could put us over the top,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
	   Television is part of the mix here, too, and a lot of stand-ins cut
commercials for their candidates. But Iowa activists prefer their politicians in
the flesh.
</P>
<P>
	   If they absolutely, positively can't be there, however, a well-known
stand-in helps.
</P>
<P>
	   There is even a more pragmatic reason to bring in a celebrity, said
Republican activist Steve Roberts. Any activists who want to see a politician
will have had countless chances to do so by now. Celebrities might give them a
reason to go get another look and, in Bradley's case, the former pro basketball
colleagues who appear for, and with him, are a hit.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The fact that you can go see Bill Bradley with Bill Russell, someone who
has some glamor, helps build a crowd,'' Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
	   The effort is bipartisan. Bush recently brought in his father, the former
president, to rev up his front-running campaign. ``You can't do it alone,'' the
elder Bush said.
</P>
<P>
	   In fact, one of the better scenes on the campaign trail is of the diminutive
Republican Gary Bauer next to his much taller, star stand-in, retired football
player Reggie White.
</P>
<P>
	   Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah once trumped that by bringing in Utah Jazz
basketball star Karl Malone.
</P>
<P>
	   Other surrogates bring a specific area of expertise to the campaign.
Bradley's aides were touting the endorsement Wednesday of Oregon Gov. John
Kitzhaber, who said he signed on because of Bradley's health care plan and can
help sell that package.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think I have some credibility and expertise on that issue,'' said
Kitzhaber, a physician. ``I'm willing to travel and do whatever to get the word
out.''
</P>
<P>
	   Another piece of Iowa geography requires that candidates get help. With its
population of more than 2.8 million spread evenly across the state, Kerrey said
it's not possible for a candidate to just drop in on a couple of metropolitan
areas and touch base with voters.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   EDITOR'S NOTE: Glen Johnson contributed to this report from New Hampshire.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-20-00 0247 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000120.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 02:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Defends Tibetan Policies  </HEADLINE>
   By DAVID BRISCOE Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- China's vice chairman for Tibet says a revered teen-age
monk who fled to India a few days ago would be welcomed back, but the Chinese
government will continue to control ordination of key Buddhist religious
figures.
</P>
<P>
	   At a rare news conference called by the Chinese Embassy, Sun Qi Wen
dismissed concerns that the departure of the Karmapa Lama, who arrived in
Dharamsala Jan. 7, might hurt Chinese relations with India. The 14-year-old monk
has met with the Dalai Lama, the exiled Tibetan political and religious leader
whose government in exile is based in Dharamsala.
</P>
<P>
	   Sun also denied any connection between the young monk's departure and
Beijing's official recognition of another child Buddhist leader, the Reting
Lama, on Sunday. He rejected suggestions that China was trying to increase its
control over Tibet by sanctioning young monks who eventually would identify a
new Dalai Lama to lead Tibetan Buddhists.
</P>
<P>
	   The office of the Dalai Lama has rejected the ordination of a new Reting,
saying the Reting Lama has not yet been reborn. Tibetan Buddhists believe high
lamas are reborn over and over to help mankind. Their incarnations are
identified by other monks through mystical clues.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There is no direct connection between the incarnation of the Reting Lama
and the Karmapa Lama's departure,'' Sun said.
</P>
<P>
	   Both the Dalai Lama and the government had recognized the Karmapa as a true
reincarnation.
</P>
<P>
	   The two young monks hold different positions. Some of the Karmapa's
supporters said he may have left because the government was denying him promised
access to key teachers and advisers.
</P>
<P>
	   Sun said China's atheist regime allows citizens to believe or not believe in
religion as they please and is merely following ``historical convention'' in
requiring government endorsement for Tibetan religious leaders.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Any installation not ratified by the central government is considered
illegal,'' he said, reflecting growing Chinese efforts to control religious
practices across the country.
</P>
<P>
	   Avoiding any criticism of the Karmapa for his escape to India, Sun repeated
government claims that the Karmapa left a letter which declared he would not
betray the monastery, the country or its leaders and was traveling to India to
recover sacred artifacts essential to his office.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We believe the Karmapa will keep his promise,'' Sun said.
</P>
<P>
	   In denying the Karmapa's departure would have any impact on China's
relations with India, Sun said the Karmapa is ``only a child'' and could not
affect the two country's ties. Chinese officials have avoided any request that
India refuse the youth sanctuary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-20-00 0247 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000120.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 02:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Business Organizing for Republicans  </HEADLINE>
   By JONATHAN D. SALANT Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Just as labor unions let their members know which
lawmakers are friendly to their issues, a coalition of business groups is urging
corporate executives to do the same thing with workers.
</P>
<P>
	   The willingness of executives to go along will be important to business'
ability to turn out its vote this fall. Project 2000, a business coalition that
includes such powerhouse lobbying groups as the U.S. Chamber of Commerce and
National Restaurant Association, hopes that this grassroots effort will help
elect pro-business candidates in tight congressional races and keep Republicans
in control of Congress.
</P>
<P>
	   Their model is organized labor, which, though outspent by business 11 to 1,
helped their Democratic allies shrink the Republican edge in the House in 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We're not reinventing this wheel,'' said Dave Gribbin, vice president for
government affairs for the Halliburton Co. and chairman of Project 2000. ``Labor
has figured out where elections are won. They're increasingly won on the street,
in terms of grassroots get-out-the-vote activity.''
</P>
<P>
	   Project 2000 will concentrate its resources on a small number of Senate and
House races. The business coalition will select the races to target based on
such factors as how much money the challenger has raised and whether
pro-Democratic labor and trial lawyer groups are involved in the race,
participation that would make the coalition more likely to focus on the race.
</P>
<P>
	   The efforts are expected to buoy Republican candidates, who usually score
higher on corporate scorecards than Democrats do. For example, House Speaker
Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., had a 100 percent pro-business voting record in 1999,
according to Project 2000. House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri, who
would become speaker if the Democrats win the majority, scored zero.
</P>
<P>
	   Under federal law, company executives can't use the corporate treasury to
run a campaign urging their workers to support a particular candidate. But they
can spend company money on an educational campaign, letting the workers know
which candidates vote the way business would like them to, and which ones do
not. Unions do the same thing with their members.
</P>
<P>
	   Corporate executives can also use company funds to run voter registration
and get-out-the-vote campaigns, inserting flyers in paycheck envelopes or
mailing forms to every employee's home, for example.
</P>
<P>
	   To make it easier for corporate executives to farm the grassroots, Project
2000 has put all of the necessary equipment on a Web site.
</P>
<P>
	   Company executives also can print out a scorecard detailing how their local
lawmaker voted on issues important to the company. They can add their corporate
logo and a personal message and send it to every worker.
</P>
<P>
	   They can register their employees to vote and send mailings or make phone
calls designed to get them to the polls, where, armed with the voting record of
their lawmaker, they can decide which way to vote on Election Day.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is pure democracy, educating voters with respect to their choices,''
Gribbin said. ``The important followup is then to encourage them to go out and
vote.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's necessary to have PACs, it's necessary to spend soft money, it's
necessary to have issue ads, but if you do all of that and don't do this last
piece, the chances are you will not succeed.''
</P>
<P>
	   The hope is that the employees will agree with their bosses that a candidate
who is good for business is good for them.
</P>
<P>
	   Union officials doubt that the workers will toe the company line.
</P>
<P>
	   ``You can't jury-rig a relationship,'' said Steve Rosenthal, the AFL-CIO's
political director. ``I don't think that just sending something to an employee
saying, 'Your boss is for this candidate, therefore you should be for him,' is
going to translate into support for that candidate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-20-00 0249 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000120.0070 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 02:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Missile Debate Escalates  </HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT BURNS AP Military Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The failure of a prototype missile interceptor to hit its
target 140 miles above the Pacific Ocean apparently can be traced to the
breakdown of heat-seeking devices aboard the interceptor.
</P>
<P>
	   That is the preliminary assessment of Pentagon and industry technical
experts who are studying what went wrong in the $100 million test Tuesday night
in which the interceptor launched correctly, received in-flight course
correction information as planned, but then missed the mock warhead it was
supposed to smash into and destroy.
</P>
<P>
	   Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said Wednesday ``there will be a lot of
data crunching over the next week or so'' to reach a full understanding of why
the interceptor went off course at nearly the last moment.
</P>
<P>
	   The apparent malfunction was in two devices aboard the interceptor which
sense temperature differences in order to ``see'' the intended target, according
to a senior military officer who discussed the preliminary assessment on
condition that he not be identified. It is not yet known why the sensors failed.
</P>
<P>
	   The military officer who briefed reporters Wednesday did not suggest that
the failure was a major technological setback.
</P>
<P>
	   Cheryl Irwin, a Pentagon spokeswoman, said the interceptor was ``extremely
close'' to hitting its target but missed at the last moment.
</P>
<P>
	   For all but the last six seconds of the interceptor's approximately eight
minute flight from a U.S. Army range on Kwajalein Atoll in the Pacific the
indications were that the interceptor would hit its target, the officer said.
The malfunctioning of the heat-seeking devices, called infrared sensors, meant
the interceptor could not ``see'' the target well enough to steer itself into
the target's path.
</P>
<P>
	   Private experts had said before the test that whatever the outcome, the
missile defense debate would continue to rage.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Critics will say it proves the system is not ready, and supporters will
leap on it as proof that the program needs more money,'' said Loren Thompson,
head of national security programs at the Lexington Institute, a think tank.
</P>
<P>
	   In fact, both of those assertions are true.
</P>
<P>
	   The failure of the Raytheon Corp.-built interceptor to hit its target -- a
mock warhead launched into space from Vandenberg Air Force Base, Calif. --
demonstrates what the Pentagon already knew: More testing is needed, the project
is bound to encounter setbacks, and its eventual success is far from assured.
</P>
<P>
	   As missile defense doubter Sen. Byron Dorgan, D-N.D., put it, ``Obviously
this is a setback for the program. It demonstrates that the technology does not
exist yet to give anybody any confidence that this is going to work.''
</P>
<P>
	   Nevertheless, the Clinton administration intends to ask Congress to add $2.2
billion to next year's budget to pay for more testing and to expand the number
of interceptors that would be fielded. So far, the administration estimates that
building the missile defense system will cost $12.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   That leaves at least two critical questions yet to be answered:
</P>
<P>
	   --Can the Pentagon build a national missile defense that can be counted on
to work in the event of an actual missile attack?
</P>
<P>
	   --Is there enough of a threat of attack -- whether from North Korea or any
other country -- to justify the cost, both in national treasury and diplomatic
complications with Russia and China, which oppose the project and assert that
building it will trigger a new and dangerous arms race? Many critics say no.
</P>
<P>
	   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, said Wednesday she remained optimistic
that reliable missile defenses can be built.
</P>
<P>
	   ``A mix of advances and setbacks mark all technological undertakings of this
size, and our commitment to defend the nation from ballistic missile attack
should not be determined by a single test,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
	   President Clinton is scheduled to make a formal decision by late summer on
whether to go ahead with deploying a system designed to protect all 50 U.S.
states against a limited ballistic missile attack.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-20-00 0249 </TRAILER>
