<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 02:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Don Knotts Gets Hollywood Star  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Don Knotts' newest star didn't come from the Mayberry
sheriff's department.
</P>
<P>
	   Knotts, a five-time Emmy winner for his portrayal of bumbling Deputy Barney
Fife on "The Andy Griffith Show," was honored Wednesday with a star on the
Hollywood Walk of Fame.
</P>
<P>
	   Knotts, 75, also appeared in 19 movies including "The Incredible Mr. Limpet"
and "The Reluctant Astronaut" and was the host of his own television variety
series.
</P>
<P>
	   "I can't believe I have my own star. I'm gonna come down here every morning
and shine that sucker up," Knotts said at a ceremony attended by Griffith, Louis
Nye, Gary Owens and John Ritter, a co-star in the "Three's Company" TV series.
</P>
<P>
	   Knotts, a native of Morgantown, W.Va., has star No. 2,152 on the Walk of
Fame.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
