<DOCNO> APW20000120.0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 02:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Perlman To Be Guest Conductor  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    DETROIT (AP) -- One of classical music's biggest stars, violinist Itzhak
Perlman, will be the Detroit Symphony Orchestra's first principal guest
conductor.
</P>
<P>
	   For three weeks a year starting in the 2001-2002 season, Perlman, 54, will
conduct concerts, participate in the orchestra's education programs, and work
with the symphony's youth orchestra and the Detroit High School for the Fine and
Performing Arts.
</P>
<P>
	   "I felt such a great rapport with the musicians of the orchestra," Perlman
said Wednesday. "I was quite flabbergasted by this offer."
</P>
<P>
	   The Israeli-born Perlman, who walks with crutches and plays and conducts
while seated because of a childhood bout with polio, has performed with the
Detroit Symphony Orchestra more than 30 times since 1964. He made his debut on
the podium last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
