<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    Thursday, Jan. 20, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Renewing Plan for Education
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton is going to push again this year for a
tax credit that's designed to make college education more affordable, officials
familiar with his proposal say. First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton and Sen.
Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., with whom Mrs. Clinton would serve alongside were she
to win her Senate bid in New York, were joining the president in making the
announcement Thursday at the White House. The centerpiece of the education plan
is a renewal of Clinton's proposed "lifelong learning tax credit," which died in
Congress last year, according to officials who spoke only on condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Report: Smoking, Electricity Ruled Out in Fire
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SOUTH ORANGE, N.J. (AP) -- The cause of the fire that killed three people at
a Seton Hall University dormitory early Wednesday is under investigation. Essex
County Prosecutor Donald C. Campolo declined comment Wednesday on a possible
cause. The Star-Ledger of Newark, citing unidentified sources close to the
investigation, reported Thursday that fire officials have ruled out careless
smoking or an electrical problem as the cause. Investigators are seeking
information on three young men whom a resident adviser had asked to leave the
building less than an hour before the fire broke out, the newspaper reported.
The 48-year-old building was equipped with smoke alarms and extinguishers but
did not have a sprinkler system because it was built before they were required,
Campolo said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mideast Peace May Be Stalled
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- With Mideast peacemaking in slow-motion, President
Clinton says he is taking on the task of nudging Syria and Israel along, and
that neither side is giving up despite the suspension of talks this week.
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat has a scheduled White House meeting Thursday
with Clinton as the administration acknowledged Israel and the Palestinians may
miss a mid-February deadline for concluding the outline of a final settlement of
their long dispute. State Department spokesman James P. Rubin said Wednesday if
Israel and the Palestinians delayed there would be no framework agreement by
Feb. 13 or a formal settlement by the fall, as planned.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
S.C. Dockworkers Protest Turns Violent
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) -- Police used dogs to disperse hundreds of dock
workers who pelted police with rocks as a labor dispute boiled over Wednesday
night. Several protesters were hurt. As many as 600 International Longshoremen's
Association workers were at the city docks protesting the use of nonunion labor
to unload a Nordana Line freighter. They arrived at midnight, hurling rocks and
chanting "ILA, ILA." News photographers and television cameramen were struck
with debris and beaten by protesters before the violence ended two hours later.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Oregon, Cuban Students Debate
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   HAVANA (AP) -- Oregon and Cuban high school students formally debated
international relations, agreeing that baseball contacts should continue between
the two countries and that the U.S. trade embargo should be lifted. Authorities
barred most of the foreign press from covering Wednesday's exchange, but a
reporter from The (Portland) Oregonian was allowed into the hall for part of the
debate sponsored by the Union of Young Communists at the Lenin Technical School
on the outskirts of Havana. Despite protests in both the United States and Cuba
over Elian Gonzalez, the 6-year-old boy's case was not a topic of Wednesday's
debate, at least not for the brief time that the Oregonian reporter was allowed
to watch.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
China, S.Korea Take Stand on Nukes
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- In a rare joint stand, China and South Korea
warned Thursday that proliferation of nuclear and other weapons of mass
destruction on the Korean Peninsula would touch off an arms race in the region.
The two former adversaries took that view when their defense chiefs met and
reviewed security on the peninsula, the world's last Cold War frontier, South
Korean officials said. "The two defense ministers voiced their opposition to
proliferation of weapons of mass destruction on the Korean Peninsula, such as
nuclear and biological and chemical weapons," South Korean Defense Ministry
spokesman Yoon Il-young said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Close Higher
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- The Nikkei Stock Average closed at 19,008.01 points on the
Tokyo Stock Exchange Thursday, up 110.26 points from Wednesday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Lakers Defeat Cavaliers 95-86
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Shaquille O'Neal scored eight of his 27 points in the
fourth quarter and also had 23 rebounds Wednesday night as the Los Angeles
Lakers rallied for a 95-86 victory over the Cleveland Cavaliers. The Lakers,
whose 33-7 record is the NBA's best, came back from a 15-point deficit in the
third period to win for the 18th time in 20 games, and 25th in 28 over the last
two months.
</P>
<P>
	   AP NewsBrief by ELIZABETH A. KENNEDY
</P>
</TEXT>
