<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000120.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 03:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Alstott Enjoys More Work for Bucs  </HEADLINE>
    By FRED GOODALL AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- Mike Alstott isn't disappointed he didn't rush for 1,000
yards. It means more to him to be playing on a team with a chance to go to the
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
	   The Tampa Bay Buccaneers will play for the NFC championship on Sunday, and
the 260-pound fullback figures to be a big part of the game plan against the St.
Louis Rams.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is why I'm here. I don't feel pressure. I feel determination. I feel
hunger. I feel motivation," the three-time All-Pro said. "Man, who wouldn't want
to be in my shoes right now."
</P>
<P>
	   Alstott rushed for 949 yards and scored nine touchdowns -- both career highs
-- this season, thriving on the increased workload he took on after speedy
sidekick Warrick Dunn got off to a slow start.
</P>
<P>
	   Although Dunn paced the team with 64 pass receptions, he only gained 616
yards on the ground after leading the Bucs in rushing the previous two seasons.
Meanwhile, Alstott joined Hall of Famer Lee Roy Selmon as the only players in
franchise history to be selected All-Pro three consecutive seasons.
</P>
<P>
	   "Every year has been different. There have been different roles," said
Alstott, who feels he's not only improved as a runner, but as a receiver and
blocker, too.
</P>
<P>
	   "I've come a long way, learning from other athletes, other celebrities
throughout the league, watching a lot of tape and just realizing how fortunate,
how lucky, I am."
</P>
<P>
	   Although he was held to 24 yards on 15 carries in last week's 14-13 playoff
victory over Washington, Alstott had two runs that were crucial to Tampa Bay's
comeback from a 13-point deficit.
</P>
<P>
	   One typified the Bucs' season -- a year in which the team has had a knack
for doing whatever it takes to win.
</P>
<P>
	   The fourth-year pro took a handoff from Shaun King and started right, only
to be met head on by would-be tacklers. Spinning out of their grasp, he tried
the middle, where two more Redskins got their hands on him, but couldn't bring
him down.
</P>
<P>
	   Finally, Alstott whirled to his left, broke an arm tackle and rumbled around
end to finish a 2-yard touchdown run that trimmed Washington's third-quarter
lead to 13-7.
</P>
<P>
	   "He's a fine, fine player. Anything he does doesn't surprise me," Rams coach
Dick Vermeil said.
</P>
<P>
	   "He's a big, strong guy, and you get tired of running into him. He's a great
ricochet runner. He bounces off people. You don't normally knock him down with
one person."
</P>
<P>
	   The TD got Tampa Bay back in the game. Alstott delivered again midway
through the fourth quarter, gaining 5 yards on fourth-and-1 from the Washington
8 to keep the go-ahead drive alive.
</P>
<P>
	   To beat St. Louis, the Bucs will have to solve the NFL's best run defense.
The Rams yielded just 74.3 yards per game and haven't allowed an opposing runner
to rush for 100 yards in 19 games, including last week's playoff victory over
Minnesota. That's the longest streak in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
	   "That's kind of the well-kept secret about them. They're a very good
defensive football team. Their offense is so explosive, that gets the
notoriety," Bucs coach Tony Dungy said.
</P>
<P>
	   Part of St. Louis' success can attributed to the Rams forcing opponents to
abandon the run in an effort to keep pace with their high-scoring offense.
</P>
<P>
	   "That always help you play defense, when you get ahead," Dungy said. "But
that's not the whole thing of it. They play well."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-20-00 0302 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000120.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 03:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Titans Take 'No Name' Approach  </HEADLINE>
    By TERESA M. WALKER AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Reporters crowd around Tennessee Titans rookie star
Jevon Kearse, and veteran safety Blaine Bishop draws attention as a three-time
Pro Bowl player. The rest of the Titans' defenders usually stand by and watch.
</P>
<P>
	   Nobody is complaining.
</P>
<P>
	   "Of course Jevon and Blaine are probably the best two players on our
defense," second-year cornerback Samari Rolle said on Wednesday. "They deserve
all the credit they get. ... We don't have any guys that are jealous or envious
over anyone. That's fine."
</P>
<P>
	   Defensive end Kenny Holmes, the team's No. 1 draft pick in 1997, said
everyone seems to think the rest of the unit is a bunch of nobodies.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're going to play along with that. We're nobodies with one good defensive
player in Jevon, so we're going to play along with that until you see us down in
Atlanta," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Atlanta -- and the Super Bowl -- will be the destination of the Titans if
they beat the Jaguars on Sunday in Jacksonville for the AFC championship.
</P>
<P>
	   Kearse is a popular attraction as the first rookie to lead a conference in
sacks, with his rookie record of 14 1/2. He earned All-Pro honors and became the
first rookie end named an AFC Pro Bowl starter.
</P>
<P>
	   He also has gotten considerable credit for the Titans' much-improved pass
rush. He had more sacks by himself than the defensive line had in 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   It hasn't been a solo effort. The Titans finished with a club-record 54
sacks during the regular season, and the relentless rush has allowed the
linebackers and defensive backs to be much more aggressive. The result has been
37 turnovers, a big improvement from 19 last season.
</P>
<P>
	   Jaguars linebacker Kevin Hardy considers himself a football fan and enjoys
watching the Titans defense.
</P>
<P>
	   "Their defense is probably the real reason they're where they are right now.
Not to take anything away from their offense, but their defense has been playing
tremendous," Hardy said.
</P>
<P>
	   The Titans finished the regular season ranked just 17th in the league in
total defense and 25th against the pass.
</P>
<P>
	   But Jacksonville coach Tom Coughlin said rankings can't sum up just what the
Titans do defensively. He called the unit outstanding and pointed to how poorly
Buffalo and Indianapolis fared in losing to the Titans in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
	   Tennessee allowed Bills quarterback Rob Johnson and Colts quarterback Peyton
Manning to complete just 44 percent of their passes, none for touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
	   "They're playing super football without a doubt," Coughlin said.
</P>
<P>
	   The defense's leader is Bishop. He was designated the team's franchise
player before the 1997 season and is a three-time Pro Bowler. Fisher thinks
Bishop may have played the best game of his career in the Titans' 19-16
divisional victory over the Colts. Bishop was credited with 11 total tackles and
defended two passes.
</P>
<P>
	   "His play has been huge for them," Hardy said.
</P>
<P>
	   The Titans also have built a stingy secondary through the draft the last
three seasons. Cornerback Denard Walker is the veteran and Rolle, who took over
right corner just before the season, shut down star receivers.
</P>
<P>
	   Dainon Sidney and rookie Donald Mitchell pitch in on passing downs.
</P>
<P>
	   All four of Rolle's career interceptions came against Jacksonville this
season, and the Jaguars managed only one touchdown pass in two losses to the
Titans.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'd give them half of what I make because those guys will cover anybody,"
Holmes said. "I'll put our four corners against anybody in the NFL. (When) we
bring four corners on the field, I know I have plenty of time to rush because
those guys cover like blankets."
</P>
<P>
	   The Titans feel they have just one area to improve -- catching the ball
instead of breaking up passes.
</P>
<P>
	   "We need to get our hands on more interceptions," free safety Marcus
Robertson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
