<HEADLINE> Duval at 59 With 2 Hole Remaining  </HEADLINE>
    By KEN PETERS AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PALM DESERT, Calif. (AP) -- PGA West looked different to David Duval.
</P>
<P>
	   "This course seemed like they added a few holes. I don't remember it being
this hard," he said, shaking his head and smiling.
</P>
<P>
	   Duval, who matched golf's magic number a year ago with a closing round of 59
to win the Bob Hope Classic, this time reached 59 considerably earlier -- with
his putt for par on his 16th hole at the same PGA West Palmer course.
</P>
<P>
	   He finished the opening round of the Hope with a 4-under 68, good enough to
keep him within five shots of leader David Toms, but a far cry from his 13-under
round of 1999.
</P>
<P>
	   There were early indications that another 59 wasn't in the cards.
</P>
<P>
	   Duval got off to a quick start on the final day last year, with birdies on
the first three holes.
</P>
<P>
	   After just six pars during his record-tying round, he capped his day with a
6-foot putt for an eagle on the par-5 No. 18 for a record-tying 59. Only two
other players in PGA Tour history, Al Geiberger and Chip Beck, have gone so low.
</P>
<P>
	   This year, Duval missed a 12-foot birdie try on his first hole, parred the
next hole, then went 1-over with a bogey on his third.
</P>
<P>
	   The gallery following him, several hundred people at the start, had dwindled
to less than 100 by the time he got his first birdie, on the seventh hole.
</P>
<P>
	   But Duval came up big on No. 18 again. He and his playing partners, who
included New York Yankees ace Roger Clemens, started the round on the 10th tee,
so the 18th was actually their ninth hole.
</P>
<P>
	   After drilling his tee shot down the center of the fairway, Duval nestled a
long iron shot within 20 feet of the pin, then rolled in the putt for eagle as
the fans in stands around the green erupted in cheers.
</P>
<P>
	   "It just happened there again," Duval said of his dramatics at No. 18. "I
hit some good shots."
</P>
<P>
	   He was steady off the tee Wednesday and he hit his irons well enough to give
him numerous birdie opportunities. But he failed to cash in, just missing a
string of birdie putts from within 20 feet or closer.
</P>
<P>
	   "I missed a few putts I should have made. I shot a pretty good score. I
don't know what anyone else did here, but I think I played pretty well," he
said.
</P>
<P>
	   "I would imagine a 68 puts me at least in the top half of the people who
played here. That's a pretty good score considering this is one of the harder
courses they use."
</P>
<P>
	   Duval finished the round with four birdies, the eagle and two bogeys.
</P>
<P>
	   He was content with his position after the first day of the tournament,
which uses four different courses that vary in the degree of difficulty.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think I had a 70 in the first round last year," he said. "The thing about
this tournament is you never really know, the players or the people who are
reporting it, who is really leading until after Saturday."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
