<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Energy Dept. Finds Racial Profiling  </HEADLINE>
   By H. JOSEF HEBERT Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Months of anxiety and controversy among Asian-American
scientists over allegations of Chinese espionage is having an impact on the
government's ability to attract top-notch scientists, Energy Secretary Bill
Richardson says.
</P>
<P>
	   Richardson released the findings Wednesday of a six-month investigation that
found evidence of racial profiling and an ``atmosphere of distrust and
suspicion'' toward Asian-Americans at the nuclear weapons research labs after
the firing of a Taiwan-born scientist for security violations last March.
</P>
<P>
	   The scientist, Wen Ho Lee, in December was arrested and charged with
mishandling and improper copying of top-secret nuclear weapons computer tapes
and is in jail without bail, awaiting trial. He has denied giving secrets to
China or anyone else, and has not been charged with espionage.
</P>
<P>
	   Despite directives last summer from Richardson against racial profiling,
managers and supervisors at the weapons labs -- Sandia, Los Alamos and Lawrence
Livermore -- and other Energy Department facilities have questioned ``the
loyalty and patriotism of some employees based upon racial factors,'' the report
said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``While specific incidents and examples of racial profiling may differ from
site to site, the general concerns and issues were virtually identical
department-wide,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
	   And the 19-member task force found widespread concern among Asian-American
scientists over the potential of a ``brain drain'' as the most qualified
scholars choose to go to universities and a friendlier, more open work
environment.
</P>
<P>
	   There is no room for racial profiling, insisted Richardson, promising to
stamp it out. He said the fallout could be long lasting.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This perceived hostile work environment ... can foment a dangerous `brain
drain' where we lose our best scientists, hobbling our research quality, leading
edge science and ultimately our national security,'' the secretary warned.
</P>
<P>
	   Already, he added, ``we are not having as much success in recruiting
topflight scientists.''
</P>
<P>
	   Asian-American scientists told task force members that the ``hostile work
environment'' was jeopardizing their opportunities for promotion and scientific
development. Scientists told of supervisors who made clear they didn't want
Asian-Americans on a project for fear their presence would attract unwanted
attention, task force members said.
</P>
<P>
	   Yvonne Lee, a member of the U.S. Civil Rights Commission and a task force
member, said the group, while visiting nine facilities, found ``a general sense
of fear'' among Asian-Americans of being unfairly targeted.
</P>
<P>
	   Task force members cited as examples a practice by the FBI to call on
Asian-American scientists simply because of their race, and counterintelligence
briefers joking about the large number of Chinese restaurants in town. They're
needed, the briefers would joke, ``for spying, of course,'' task force
investigators were told.
</P>
<P>
	   While calling such comments ``insensitive and inappropriate,'' Richardson
said no specific case of racial profiling has been proven. Still, he said, the
perception and mistrust that has developed among Asian-American scientists was
troubling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-20-00 0311 </TRAILER>
