<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Warner's a Stock Boy's Dream  </HEADLINE>
    By ED SCHUYLER JR. AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   Kurt Warner fades back, a can of beans in his hand, and looks for the
receiver sprinting between the cheese table and the meat freezer.
</P>
<P>
	   Before he hurls the beans and risks smashing a display case of gourmet
foods, he wakes up. It's not Kurt Warner at all, it's just a supermarket stock
boy, or, if you prefer, stock person.
</P>
<P>
	   Stocking shelves at night in a supermarket was what Warner was doing in 1994
in Cedar Rapids, Iowa. On Jan. 30 -- it says here -- he will be playing in the
Super Bowl as quarterback for the St. Louis Rams and telling a huge television
audience that he's going to an amusement park.
</P>
<P>
	   Kurt Warner is a flesh-and-blood dream realized.
</P>
<P>
	   To get to the Super Bowl indoors at Atlanta, Warner and the Rams will beat
the Tampa Bay Buccaneers indoors at St. Louis on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
	   The Bucs' quarterback is rookie Shaun King, who is 5-1 as a starter since he
replaced the injured Trent Dilfer. One of the wins was the 14-13 playoff verdict
over the Washington Redskins.
</P>
<P>
	   So a rookie and a former arena player are the quarterbacks in the National
Conference championship game.
</P>
<P>
	   After years of reading and listening to analysts, some of us thought being a
successful NFL quarterback was like becoming a neurosurgeon. It required years
of dedicated study.
</P>
<P>
	   "It was typical Kurt Warner," Rams wide receiver Az-Zahir Hakim said after
Warner completed 27 of 33 passes for 391 yards and five touchdowns in the 49-37
playoff victory over the Minnesota Vikings. He threw 41 TD passes in the regular
season.
</P>
<P>
	   Warner really is a typical case -- an unheralded college player who didn't
dazzle the all-knowing scouts and computers.
</P>
<P>
	   "You can't help but think there are guys that got passed over that maybe
could have had great careers had they gotten the opportunity," Warner has said.
Many players who were in Warner's situation can't hang around long enough to get
a chance at the NFL.
</P>
<P>
	   Fate smiled on Warner after having kept a straight face for quite awhile. He
came out of Northern Iowa to fail in tryouts with five NFL teams. Then after
stocking shelves for six months in 1994, he played for three years with the Iowa
Barnstormers in the Arena Football League and then one season with the Amsterdam
Admirals of NFL Europe.
</P>
<P>
	   Warner was the Rams' third-string quarterback two seasons ago, moved to No.
2 this past preseason and became No. 1 for the regular season when Trent Green
injured a knee.
</P>
<P>
	   Now he's an NFL MVP and about to be the winning quarterback in the Super
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
	   On Sunday, the Bucs defense will keep it close, but three Rams touchdowns
will be enough to win and send them to a Super Bowl victory over the Tennessee
Titans, who will beat the Jacksonville Jaguars for the third straight time in
the American Conference title game at Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
	   The Titans will be at a disadvantage because the Super Bowl will be played
on artificial turf in the Georgia Dome, and they won't be able to draw up any
schoolyard plays in the dirt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-20-00 0319 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
