<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Close Higher  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks closed higher today, boosted by a rise in the
technology-rich Nasdaq on Wall Street. The dollar edged lower against the yen.
</P>
<P>
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average closed up 110.26 points, or
0.58 percent, to 19,008.01. On Wednesday, the average finished down 298.82
points, or 1.56 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   The dollar bought 105.34 yen at 5 p.m. (3 a.m. EST), down 0.18 yen from late
Wednesday and below its late New York level of 105.36 yen. During the day, it
traded between 105.17 yen and 105.39 yen.
</P>
<P>
	   On the stock market, prices rose on buying of several blue chips as
investors were encouraged by a new record close on the Nasdaq Composite Index in
New York.
</P>
<P>
	   The Nasdaq index ended Wednesday at 4,151.27, its first closing record high
since Jan. 3. The Dow Jones industrial average, however, fell 71.36 points, or
0.6 percent, to close at 11,489.36.
</P>
<P>
	   The Tokyo market was being led by strong gains in several blue-chip stocks,
with Sony, Toyota Motor and Matsushita Electric Industrial all posting rises
today.
</P>
<P>
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the first
section was up 1.83 points, or 0.11 percent, to 1,633.11. The TOPIX closed down
34.56 points, or 2.07 percent, the day before.
</P>
<P>
	   Volume on the first section was estimated at 600.75 million shares, up from
561.40 million shares Wednesday. Rising shares outnumbered decliners 710 to 511,
while 120 closed unchanged.
</P>
<P>
	   In currency dealings, the greenback moved in a narrow range in quiet trading
ahead of the meeting of Group of Seven finance ministers and central bank
governors in Tokyo on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   The dollar fell to a low of 105.15 yen, but rebounded to 105.37 yen in early
Asian trading on bids from some U.S. and Japanese investors ahead of the G-7
meeting, traders said. Some investors expect the group to publicly express
concern about the strong yen.
</P>
<P>
	   Japanese officials have said the yen's rapid rise will hurt Japanese exports
and profits, slowing down the nation's economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
	   In other currencies, the euro was traded at 106.64 yen, down from 107.06 yen
late Wednesday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
	   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose to 1.7750
percent from Wednesday's finish of 1.7550 percent. Its price fell 0.17 point to
100.21.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
