<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Researchers Test 'Marijuana Patch'  </HEADLINE>
    By MICHAEL GORMLEY Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Scientists are planning research on whether a
"marijuana patch" similar to the patches that help smokers kick the habit could
help ease the suffering of cancer patients.
</P>
<P>
	   The American Cancer Society is funding a three-year, $361,000 grant for
research at the Albany College of Pharmacy. A formal announcement was planned
for today.
</P>
<P>
	   The marijuana patch could ease the pain, nausea and vomiting that
chemotherapy patients can suffer, said Gail Tyner-Taylor of the American Cancer
Society of New York and New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
	   No such patch exists now, but Dr. Audra Stinchcomb, an assistant professor
who researches medications transmitted through the skin, will explore whether it
is feasible.
</P>
<P>
	   The concept is similar to nicotine patches used as a way to deliver
controlled doses of nicotine to help people quit smoking tobacco.
</P>
<P>
	   The patch could provide an alternative to smoking marijuana for medical
purposes, which has been approved in some states but remains a controversial
issue nationwide.
</P>
<P>
	   Advocates for the use of medical marijuana, however, criticized the patch
concept as another in a long line of less-effective alternatives to smoking the
drug.
</P>
<P>
	   "The American Cancer Society has always been on record against people
smoking tobacco and marijuana," said Allen St. Pierre, executive director of the
National Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Laws in Washington, D.C. "This
is a way to assuage opponents."
</P>
<P>
	   Previous research included pills, suppositories, eye and ear drops and even
talk of creating a marijuana vapor, St. Pierre said. Smoking, however, is a
faster way to get the drug into the system, an important factor in controlling
nausea.
</P>
<P>
	   The National Institutes of Health and an affiliate of the National Academy
of Sciences have concluded that the active ingredients in marijuana can ease the
pain, nausea and vomiting of cancer and AIDS.
</P>
<P>
	   A half-dozen states have offered ballot measures to legalize marijuana as
medication, but the drug is banned by federal law and doctors hesitate to
prescribe it, even in states that legalized its medical use.
</P>
<P>
	   The Justice Department is challenging voter-approved laws in Alaska,
Arizona, California, Oregon and Washington. Maine voters approved a medical
marijuana law last year and the law went into effect last month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-20-00 0631 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000120.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 07:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin Grammys Awarded to L.A.  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) -- The first Latin Grammys will be awarded in Los
Angeles because the first choice, Miami, refused to permit Cuban performers,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   Gloria Estefan and other stars attended Wednesday's announcement at the
headquarters of the Latin Academy of Recording Arts &AMP; Sciences.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think we are still on the ground floor of the emergence of Latin music in
America, and I look forward to our contribution to the popularity of this
wonderful music," said Michael Greene, president of the National Academy of
Recording Arts and Sciences, which helped organize the Latin recording academy.
</P>
<P>
	   NARAS awards the traditional Grammys, which includes seven in Latin music
categories. Those Grammys, led by Carlos Santana's 10 nominations, will be
handed out next month.
</P>
<P>
	   The Latin Grammys will have 40 categories covering Spanish and Portuguese
music -- "everything from salsa to merengue" -- and will be open to musicians
anywhere on the planet, Greene said.
</P>
<P>
	   The Sept. 15 awards ceremony will air on CBS. No site was announced.
</P>
<P>
	   Miami was dumped because an ordinance prohibits the surrounding county from
doing business with any entity doing business with Cuba, Green said. That would
have prevented use of a needed arena and barred Cuban musicians from performing.
</P>
<P>
	   "Dade County continues to be held hostage by the Cuban expatriates down
there," Greene said. "It's regrettable, because Miami is such an international
Latino city."
</P>
<P>
	   Officials in South Florida lamented the loss of the awards show.
</P>
<P>
	   "There is only one connection between Fidel Castro and the Latin Grammys and
that is the ordinance in Dade County. Because of that South Florida just lost
$40 million dollars," said Nicki Grossman, president of the Fort Lauderdale
Visitors &AMP; Conventions Bureau.
</P>
<P>
	   Broward County officials made a strong bid to lure the awards show and Miami
Beach offered to support Grammy-related events, but Miami-Dade Mayor Alex
Penelas refused to join in the effort.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is an opportunity lost for the area," said Miami Beach Mayor Neisen
Kasdin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-20-00 0736 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000120.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 07:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Poised for Top IMF Post  </HEADLINE>
    By HANS GREIMEL Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- German officials have renewed their campaign to
promote German Deputy Finance Minister Caio Koch-Weser as the next head of the
International Monetary Fund, creating a stir as finance ministers from the
world's seven richest nations head to Tokyo for a weekend meeting.
</P>
<P>
	   The Brazilian-born German is viewed by supporters as a balanced
representative of the developing countries, which get help from the
international fund -- and the rich, Western nations, which are its largest
contributors.
</P>
<P>
	   Picking a successor to current head Michel Camdessus is not officially on
the Group of Seven agenda, but there will be plenty of talk in the hallways when
the finance ministers meet Saturday, given Camdessus' scheduled exit next month.
</P>
<P>
	   With both France and the United States cool on Koch-Weser for lacking a
high-profile and hard-core financial background, German Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder has intensified the campaign to put his candidate at the helm of the
182-nation organization based in Washington.
</P>
<P>
	   Ahead of the G7 finance meeting, Schroeder sent letters to the 40 countries
promoting Koch-Weser as a competent adviser and good negotiator. And Schroeder's
chief foreign policy adviser, Michael Steiner, summoned ambassadors of those
countries on Monday to further pitch the Koch-Weser candidacy.
</P>
<P>
	   "We expect to get a clear message at Tokyo that Koch-Weser will be the
European candidate," said Schroeder spokesman Bela Anda. "The signals we've been
getting are quite positive."
</P>
<P>
	   Schroeder put the push in high gear after France indicated last week it was
promoting former Prime Minister Laurent Fabius. But France has already chosen
three of the last four IMF heads, including Camdessus, and Fabius described
speculation that he was a candidate "flattering" but untrue.
</P>
<P>
	   Others vying for the job -- which has always been held by a European --
include Italian Treasury Director Mario Draghi and two Brits -- British
Chancellor of the Exchequer Gordon Brown and Andrew Crockett, who heads the Bank
of International Settlements in Basel, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
	   Japan also is promoting former vice finance minister for international
affairs, Eisuke Sakakibara -- known as "Mr. Yen" for his influence on currency
markets.
</P>
<P>
	   A German has never held the job, and Koch-Weser -- who has 26 years of
international experience at the World Bank -- would be a natural choice, his
supporters say.
</P>
<P>
	   "Germany is growing in influence and it is playing a more important role in
the international forum, so I think it would be very healthy for the world, if
you could find Germans like Koch-Weser to play a bigger role," said Peter Eigen,
a former World Bank colleague who now leads Transparency International, a
Berlin-based group dedicated to fighting political corruption.
</P>
<P>
	   Koch-Weser rose quickly through the ranks at the World Bank, serving first
as an economist and then as a health projects officer for the organization,
which works closely with the IMF to finance development projects, mostly in
poorer countries.
</P>
<P>
	   He had been promoted to managing director at the bank when Germany's Finance
Ministry recruited him in April to strengthen Schroeder's Cabinet after
then-Finance Minister Oskar Lafontaine resigned in a political spat.
</P>
<P>
	   Eigen said Koch-Weser's strength is being able to build consensus without
twisting arms -- a key to dealing with some of the critical issues the IMF now
faces, including the integration of Russia and Africa into the world economy, as
well as bringing China into the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
	   But Koch-Weser also has no experience as a top finance minister or central
bank governor, and that makes him a less attractive candidate to IMF members who
value a foundation in economics and finance.
</P>
<P>
	   That will play a major role as pressure mounts for the IMF to restructure
itself -- particularly in the United States, which has criticized the fund for
its loans to Russia and its handling of the Asian crisis.
</P>
<P>
	   There are also political obstacles to his candidacy. Japan is the IMF's
second-largest financial contributor after the United States, and has repeatedly
demanded a bigger voice in the organization. Already several major Asian
nations, as well as Russia, have openly supported Sakakibara's candidacy.
</P>
<P>
	   At the same time, the United States has given Koch-Weser a lukewarm
reception -- partly from an interest in keeping the spot open for U.S. Treasury
Secretary Lawrence Summers, who could lose his job after the upcoming
presidential elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-20-00 0737 </TRAILER>
