<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 07:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Plan Wedding Without Depleting Cash  </HEADLINE>
    By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- When it comes time for planning their weddings, many
couples find themselves torn between their dream day and the reality of what it
all will cost. Plenty of pre-wedding angst comes from trying to create a
beautiful, elegant affair without running up debt that outlasts the memories.
</P>
<P>
	   Buying a wedding -- which, basically, is what you're doing -- is like any
other purchase in that the more informed you are, the more likely you are to be
happy with what you get and how much you pay for it.
</P>
<P>
	   Many bridal consultants -- as well as brides and other veterans of wedding
planning -- say that when it comes to saving on a wedding, the more time you
give yourself to find a location, food, music, clothes, etc., the better. Less
time pressure means you're more likely to make decisions you'll be satisfied
with and that will save you money (think of it in terms of last-minute Christmas
shopping, when you spent more than you intended because you were up against the
wall).
</P>
<P>
	   Some books on weddings advise couples to give themselves a year or more. It
is quite possible to put on a lovely wedding in a few months' time without
spending beyond your budget, said Kathy Bateman, a wedding coordinator in York,
Pa., but "the longer you have to plan, the more options you have."
</P>
<P>
	   Ms. Bateman says that no matter what the time frame is, the first question
for a couple to consider is "What do you want?" In other words, what kind of
wedding -- big, small, traditional, out-of-town? After that comes the critical
"What is your budget?" and then, "What is the most important part of this to
you? What things are you willing to give up? What things are you not willing to
give up?"
</P>
<P>
	   For example, if having great music, or food, or a drop-dead dress is
important, those are the areas where you'll want to spend more. If you don't
care about having the biggest limo, or you don't need the most expensive
invitations, don't put your money there.
</P>
<P>
	   Jeanne Crudup, a wedding consultant with D'Elegance in Citrus Heights,
Calif., tells her clients, "If you have a figure in mind, you're more apt to
stay within it." Then, as you're planning, don't let your feelings rule, and
allow yourself to spend on something that in the end you might not care about.
</P>
<P>
	   "Weddings are so emotionally driven," Ms. Crudup said. "A month after the
event, you'll say, 'I was so stupid! Why did I do so-and-so?"'
</P>
<P>
	   Many brides look to magazines and books and now the Internet for ideas. But
while these sources will give you an idea of the possibilities, they may not
necessarily help you save money.
</P>
<P>
	   Moreover, some couples choose retailers that offer one-stop shopping --
clothing, photography, flowers, limousines, invitations, wedding party gifts and
more under one roof. Or, Internet equivalents, sites that link a variety of
retailers, photographers and other services. This may be the most convenient
route, but it might exclude some options that are either cheaper or more to your
taste.
</P>
<P>
	   Going to a wedding consultant is an expense, but both Ms. Bateman and Ms.
Crudup say seeking professional advice can help save money. Consultants should
be able to work within a couple's budget and suggest less expensive wedding
suppliers. They can also suggest ways to pare costs.
</P>
<P>
	   For instance, Ms. Crudup suggested that couples who are creative or who have
creative friends can save money on floral decorations by not buying them from
retail florists. Instead, go to a craft store or wholesale florist and make the
centerpieces yourself; you can save hundreds of dollars.
</P>
<P>
	   When you're buying invitations, instead of getting expensive ones from a
stationery store, try a mail-order catalog or online supplier that charges less
(and be honest, will it really matter if you don't get top-of-the-line engraved
invitations?).
</P>
<P>
	   Even something as big as a reception can be done more cheaply simply by
booking a catering hall on a Friday night or on a Sunday. Most people want to
get married on Saturday, but doing so drives up not just the cost of the
caterer, but probably the pay for musicians, disc jockeys and limo drivers.
</P>
<P>
	   Along that line, Ms. Crudup has a warning for couples planning to marry this
year or next. Because of the millennium, "places are going to be charging
through the roof." She noted that many popular catering halls are largely booked
for 2000.
</P>
<P>
	   You might not want to postpone your wedding, waiting for prices to drop, but
keep in mind you may be paying more just for a particular date.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-20-00 0747 </TRAILER>
