<HEADLINE> Asian Markets Close Mostly Higher  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian stock markets closed mostly higher Thursday as
investors shrugged off fears of a possible rise in U.S. interest rates.
</P>
<P>
	   Tokyo stocks rose on the back of a rise in the technology-rich Nasdaq
Composite Index overnight on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average closed up 110.26 points, or
0.58 percent, to 19,008.01. On Wednesday, the average had dropped 1.56 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Gains were led by several blue-chips such as Sony, Toyota Motor Corp. and
Matsushita Electric Industrial.
</P>
<P>
	   The Nasdaq on Wednesday gained 0.50 percent to its highest close since Jan.
3.
</P>
<P>
	   In currency trading, the U.S. dollar rose against the Japanese yen. The
dollar bought 105.34 yen in late trading, down 0.18 yen from late Wednesday and
below its late New York level of 105.36 yen overnight.
</P>
<P>
	   The dollar fell ahead of the meeting of Group of Seven finance ministers and
central bank governors in Tokyo on Saturday. The group was expected to express
concern about the strong yen.
</P>
<P>
	   Hong Kong stocks bucked the regional trend, closing moderately lower as
investors cashed in their gains amid lackluster trading.
</P>
<P>
	   The blue-chip Hang Seng Index shed 60.03 points, or 0.40 percent, to
15,215.31. On Wednesday, the index had plunged 3.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Hong Kong shares were "more expensive than other Southeast Asian countries,"
and therefore fell more sharply on fears over U.S. interest rates, said Dennis
Leung of J and A Securities.
</P>
<P>
	   ELSEWHERE
</P>
<P>
	   BANGKOK: Shares rose despite losses in the banking sector. The SET index
rose 0.31 points, or 0.1 percent, to 486.64.
</P>
<P>
	   KUALA LUMPUR: Shares surged 1.9 percent on buying from local and retail
investors. The Composite Index rose 950.86 points to 17.48.
</P>
<P>
	   MANILA: Shares rose amid allegations that President Joseph Estrada had
ordered a stop to an investigation into alleged illegal trades. The PSE Index
rose 4.84 points, or 0.23 percent to 2,053.37.
</P>
<P>
	   JAKARTA: Shares rose 2.2 percent on gains in selected blue chips and
positive news from the International Monetary Fund. The JSX Composite index rose
14.158 points to 670.153.
</P>
<P>
	   TAIPEI: Shares fell on lackluster market sentiment. The Weighted Price Index
slipped 14.49 points, or 0.20 percent, to 9,136.95.
</P>
<P>
	   SEOUL: Shares rose on buying by local institutional investors and gains in
the futures market. The Kospi rose 7.12 points, or 0.8 percent, to 945.90.
</P>
<P>
	   SYDNEY: Shares rose on buying in major resource and media stocks. The All
Ordinaries Index rose 31.70 points, or 1 percent, to 3,137.10.
</P>
<P>
	   SINGAPORE: Shares surged 2.7 percent on strong export trade data released
Thursday. The STI rose 60.66 points to 2,315.53.
</P>
<P>
	   WELLINGTON: Shares fell 1.7 percent on heavy offshore selling in local
stocks. The NZSE-40 Capital Index fell 37.00 points to 2,086.80.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
