<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mazda Turns to Internet Sales  </HEADLINE>
    By YURI KAGEYAMA Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- Having returned to profitability, Mazda Motor Corp. will now
go on the offensive by using the Internet to sell cars in Japan, the automaker's
new president said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Mazda has achieved a remarkable recovery through cost-cutting and
streamlining its lineup over the last four years, since Ford Motor Co. increased
its investment to a 33.4 percent controlling stake in the Hiroshima-based
automaker.
</P>
<P>
	   It posted a profit last fiscal year for the first time in six years, and the
earnings were its highest since 1985. Mazda has recently increased market share
not only at home but also in the United States, Canada and Europe.
</P>
<P>
	   It posted a net profit of 13.2 billion yen, or $125 million, in the first
half of this fiscal year ending in September, in contrast to a loss of 4.4
billion yen the previous year.
</P>
<P>
	   "So the trend is good," said Mark Fields, who was named president last
month.
</P>
<P>
	   Fields has drawn media attention here because at 38 he is the youngest
person to head a major automaker in Japan, a culture long dominated by the rule
of seniority.
</P>
<P>
	   "We can't shrink our way to greatness. We need to grow our business as
well," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   As part of its latest initiative, Mazda has begun a Web site to sell its
remodeled Demio, a popular compact sports-utility vehicle, and hopes to use the
Internet to sell more models.
</P>
<P>
	   The Internet is "going to redefine what it takes to be competitive," Fields
said. "It's not something we can sit back and wait for the best answer. We've
got to get on it now, and we've got to experiment."
</P>
<P>
	   The two presidents before him, both executives sent by Ford, had helped
stabilize Mazda, Fields said, adding that now his job is to go on the offensive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
