<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 9:10 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thursday, Jan. 20, 2000
</P>
<P>
	   GM Earnings Fall 32 Percent
</P>
<P>
	   DETROIT (AP) -- General Motors Corp. saw its earnings fall to
$1.1 billion in the fourth quarter, a decline of 32 percent, due to
reduced U.S. truck sales and losses at its Hughes electronics unit.
The world's largest automaker said it earned $1.86 a share,
compared to $2.48 a share last year, when the company reported
record quarterly earnings. The results beat Wall Street
expectations. Revenues totaled $46.3 billion, compared to $44.6
billion in the same quarter in 1998. For the year, GM earned $5.6
billion, or $8.53 a share, up 83 percent over 1998's
strike-affected earnings of $3 billion, or $4.32 a share. Revenues
totaled $176.5 billion, up 13.6 percent from $155 billion a year
ago. The results do not include income from Delphi Automotive
Systems, which was spun off from GM in 1999.
</P>
<P>
	   Mazda Turns to Internet Sales
</P>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- Having returned to profitability, Mazda Motor Corp.
will now go on the offensive by using the Internet to sell cars in
Japan, the automaker's new president said today. Mazda has achieved
a remarkable recovery through cost-cutting and streamlining its
lineup over the last four years, since Ford Motor Co. increased its
investment to a 33.4 percent controlling stake in the
Hiroshima-based automaker. It posted a profit last fiscal year for
the first time in six years, and the earnings were its highest
since 1985. Mazda has recently increased market share not only at
home but also in the United States, Canada and Europe.
</P>
<P>
	   Trade Deficit Hits Another Record
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- America's trade deficit widened to a record
$26.5 billion in November as a flood of foreign cars and consumer
goods pushed imports to an all-time high. The Commerce Department
reported today that the deficit in trade in goods and services was
up 3.7 percent from the October imbalance of $25.6 billion.
Imports, which have been strong all year, climbed 1.4 percent to a
record $109.4 billion, reflecting robust U.S. demand for foreign
cars, business equipment, consumer goods ranging from clothing to
household appliances and a rising oil import bill.
</P>
<P>
	   Jobless Claims Fall by 39,000
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- New claims for unemployment insurance fell by
39,000 to 272,000 last week, the Labor Department announced this
morning. It was the biggest drop since late July. The decline left
claims at a level indicating that employers continue to scramble to
find scarce workers to fill job openings.
</P>
<P>
	   German Party Official in Suspected Suicide
</P>
<P>
	   BERLIN (AP) -- An official handling finances for Germany's
Christian Democrats committed suicide today in the midst of the
campaign funding scandal shaking the party, German television
reported. The floor leader of the Christian Democrats' Bavarian
wing, Michael Glos, identified the official as Wolfgang Huellen,
head of the party's financial and budget section in parliament. A
senior party official, Joachim Hoerster, confirmed the official's
death to reporters, but sought to counter speculation it was
related to the scandal.
</P>
<P>
	   Union Dockworkers Protest in S.C.
</P>
<P>
	   CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) -- Hundreds of angry dockworkers clashed
with police early today after a Danish company used nonunion
workers to unload one of its cargo ships. Police used dogs and at
least one smoke grenade to break up the crowd. At least six people
were treated and released from hospitals. Several people were seen
taken away in police wagons but officials could not immediately
give detail on arrests. Police closed off several blocks leading to
the terminal following the incident. There were no protesters left
at the site by 7 a.m.
</P>
<P>
	   AOL Earnings More Than Double
</P>
<P>
	   SPRINGFIELD, Va. (AP) -- America Online, which agreed to buy
media leader Time Warner last week, reported sharply higher
earnings yesterday on greater revenues from advertising and
e-commerce. AOL earned $224 million, or 9 cents a share, in the
quarter ended Dec. 31, more than double the $86 million, or 4 cents
a share, in the same period a year ago. The figures from both
periods exclude one-time gains and losses. Total revenues rose to
$1.6 billion, or 41 percent over last year's second quarter.
Revenues from advertising and commerce reached $437 million, an
increase of 79 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Apple Posts 9th Consecutive Profit
</P>
<P>
	   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Apple Computer posted its ninth consecutive
quarterly profit as consumers continued to flock to its curvy and
colorful iMacs and iBooks. Apple reported yesterday that net income
for the three months ended Jan. 1, its first fiscal quarter, rose
to $183 million, or $1.03 a share. In the same period a year ago,
Apple earned $152 million, or 95 cents a share. Excluding a
one-time gain of $101 million from an investment and $6 million for
restructuring costs, Apple earned $178 million, or $1 a share.
Apple's operating profit easily topped Wall Street forecasts of 90
cents a share, according to a survey of analysts by First
Call/Thomson Financial, and even beat unofficial ``whisper''
estimates of 97 cents that circulated before the report.
</P>
<P>
	   IBM Reports 11 Percent Profit Drop
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- IBM reported a 11 percent drop in fourth-quarter
profit yesterday, hurt by slower demand for the company's powerful
business computers. But aggressive cost-cutting helped IBM's profit
easily exceed Wall Street forecasts. IBM warned last quarter that
customers were delaying purchases of its powerful network and
database servers due to uncertainty over the Y2K bug. IBM noted
Wednesday that lingering concern will continue to take its toll on
sales in the current quarter.
</P>
<P>
	   Chase Profits Jump 45 Percent
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Chase Manhattan Corp. reported profits surged
more than 45 percent in the fourth quarter, blowing past analysts'
estimates, as the nation's third-largest bank posted huge gains
from its investments in Internet startups. Chase had operating
profits of $1.68 billion, or $1.97 a share, for the quarter ended
Dec. 31, far above Wall Street's forecast of $1.32 a share,
according to First Call/Thomson Financial. Including a one-time
gain, Chase posted net income of $1.69 billion, or $1.98 a share,
in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
	   Asian Markets Close Mostly Higher
</P>
<P>
	   HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian stock markets closed mostly higher today
as investors shrugged off fears of a possible rise in U.S. interest
rates. Tokyo stocks rose on the back of a rise in the Nasdaq
Composite Index overnight on Wall Street. The 225-issue Nikkei
Stock Average closed up 110.26 points, or 0.58 percent, to
19,008.01. Gains were led by several blue-chips such as Sony,
Toyota Motor Corp. and Matsushita Electric Industrial. Hong Kong
stocks bucked the regional trend, closing moderately lower as
investors cashed in their gains amid lackluster trading. The Hang
Seng Index shed 60.03 points, or 0.40 percent, to 15,215.31.
</P>
<P>
	   Nasdaq at Record-High Close
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Nasdaq composite index rose to a new record
Wednesday even as investors punished Microsoft for a profit report
that met published estimates but failed to impress some Wall Street
analysts. The Nasdaq Composite Index rose 20.48 to 4,151.29, its
first new record since it closed at 4,131.15 on Jan. 3. The Dow
Jones industrial average fell 71.36 to 11,489.36, a decline that
came almost entirely from Microsoft. Microsoft fell 8 5/16 from its
4 p.m. price Tuesday to 107. Late Tuesday, the company said it
earned $2.44 billion, or 44 cents per share, in its fiscal second
quarter, compared to the 42 cents predicted by analysts surveyed by
First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
