<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 09:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Deficit Hits Another Record  </HEADLINE>
    By JEANNINE AVERSA Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- America's trade deficit widened to a record $26.5 billion
in November as a flood of foreign cars and consumer goods pushed imports to an
all-time high.
</P>
<P>
	   The Commerce Department reported today that the deficit in trade in goods
and services was up 3.7 percent from the October imbalance of $25.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   Imports, which have been strong all year, climbed 1.4 percent to a record
$109.4 billion, reflecting robust U.S. demand for foreign cars, business
equipment, consumer goods ranging from clothing to household appliances and a
rising oil import bill.
</P>
<P>
	   "The good times keep rolling for U.S. consumers. Cheaper-priced imports help
keep inflation at bay and satisfy Americans' insatiable demand for goods," said
Mike Fenollosa, an economist with John Hancock.
</P>
<P>
	   Exports, however, also rose a brisk 0.7 percent to a record $82.9 billion as
demand for U.S. products from overseas economies picked up after being severely
depressed from the Asian financial crisis. Sales of telecommunications
equipment, semiconductors, TV sets and VCRs, and industrial supplies all rose.
</P>
<P>
	   "The pickup in exports is positive because it helps pay for our import bill
and it helps U.S. manufacturers," Fenollosa said.
</P>
<P>
	   The bond markets had little reaction to the trade report. Yields on 30-year
Treasury bonds had already climbed back to match Tuesday's 2 1/2-year high of
6.75 percent. Yields continued to hover around that level after the report, up
from late Wednesday's 6.71 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Through the first 11 months of 1999, the U.S. trade deficit was running at
an annual rate of $266.8 billion, far surpassing last year's record deficit of
$164.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   The trade deficit has set a new monthly record eight out of 11 months in
1999 as America's performance on trade has continued to suffer from the
lingering effects of a global financial crisis that depressed U.S. exports and
contributed to a flood of cheaper-priced imports into the country.
</P>
<P>
	   The trade imbalance is the one blot on an otherwise superior economic
performance that has pushed America's unemployment rate down to a 30-year low of
4.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   In a second report today, the number of Americans filing new claims for
unemployment benefits last week fell sharply by an unexpected 39,000 to 272,000,
the biggest drop since late July. The decline left claims at a level indicating
that employers continue to scramble to find scarce workers to fill job openings.
</P>
<P>
	   Critics of President Clinton's trade policies have seized on the soaring
deficits to support their argument that the administration's pursuit of big
market-opening trade deals is not working.
</P>
<P>
	   In December, the 135-nation World Trade Organization meeting in Seattle
failed to launch a new round of global trade talks. U.S. Trade Representative
Charlene Barshefsky on Wednesday offered a pessimistic assessment of the chances
for getting those negotiations started any time soon, given the wide differences
that remain over what should be on the agenda.
</P>
<P>
	   The administration also faces a major fight in Congress to win approval for
a trade agreement clearing the way for China to become a member of the WTO.
Clinton convened a Cabinet meeting Wednesday to review administration goals for
his final year in office, particularly the strategy for winning congressional
approval of normal trade relations with China.
</P>
<P>
	   The November trade report showed that the U.S. deficit with China narrowed
by 9.2 percent to $6.5 billion. The politically sensitive deficit with Japan
also narrowed by 11.3 percent to $6.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
	   However, America's deficit with Germany soared by 29.4 percent to a record
$3 billion in November as imports from that country jumped to an all-time high.
</P>
<P>
	   American's foreign oil bill rose 0.9 percent to $7 billion in November as
crude oil prices hit their highest level since January 1997. Since November,
prices have soared to nearly $30 -- the highest level since January 1991, before
the Gulf War.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-20-00 0923 </TRAILER>
