<DOCNO> APW20000120.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 09:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chicago Board of Trade May Split  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    CHICAGO (AP) -- The Chicago Board of Trade's directors have reportedly
approved a plan to divide the world's oldest futures market into two for-profit
companies.
</P>
<P>
	   One venture would handle electronic markets, while the other would run the
traditional trading floors and pits, the Chicago Sun-Times and the Chicago
Tribune reported today. The companies would have separate boards, management and
strategies and compete for orders.
</P>
<P>
	   Board Chairman David Brennan was expected to announce the decision, made at
a special board meeting Wednesday night, to exchange members today. Two-thirds
of the more than 3,600 members would have to approve the plan to make it
official.
</P>
<P>
	   Under the plan, members who own the CBOT would get interest in shares of the
new company, which is being called "eBOT." Future plans might also include an
initial public stock offering, both newspapers reported, citing sources familiar
with the plan who declined to be identified.
</P>
<P>
	   The 152-year-old Board of Trade has been developing the more streamlined and
agile structure for months to help cope with increasing competitive pressure
from electronic trading networks. Last June, board members approved an alliance
with rival exchange, Frankfurt-based Eurex.
</P>
<P>
	   Because many details are unresolved, some members said the split could take
up to a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
