<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 10:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Up 31.65; Nasdaq Up 56.41  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks opened higher today as robust corporate earnings
reports from several technology companies boosted the Nasdaq further into record
territory.
</P>
<P>
	   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average was up 31.65 at 11,521.01.
</P>
<P>
	   The Nasdaq composite index was up 56.41 at 4,207.70, extending the closing
record of 11,489.36 reached Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Broader stock indicators were also higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index
was up 7.43 at 1,463.33.
</P>
<P>
	   Investors once again poured money into shares of large technology companies,
several of which reported better than expected earnings late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   IBM, which sent a chill through the technology sector last fall when it said
sales had slumped due to worries about the Year 2000 computer bug, easily beat
Wall Street's profit forecasts. While company officials warned that lingering
concerns will continue to take a toll on sales in the current quarter, they
encouraged analysts to leave their profit forecasts for 2000 intact.
</P>
<P>
	   IBM stock soared 7 1/2 to 123 today.
</P>
<P>
	   On the Nasdaq, Apple Computer rose 9 11/16 to 116 1/4. Apple said late
Wednesday it earned $183 million, or $1.03 a share, in its most recent quarter.
Strong sales of its iMac computer helped Apple coast past published estimates of
90 cents per share and past the "whisper number" of 97 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
	   America Online, which has seen its stock price tumble since the company
announced its intentions to merge with Time Warner, slipped 5/16 to 63 3/4. AOL
said late Wednesday it earned $224 million, or 9 cents a share, in the quarter
ended Dec. 31, more than double the $86 million, or 4 cents a share, in the same
period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
	   Analysts had expected AOL to earn 8 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
	   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 6-to-5 margin on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 142.9 million shares, ahead of Wednesday's
early pace.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 4.70 to 524.72.
</P>
<P>
	   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.6 percent. In afternoon
trading, Germany's DAX index was up 0.6 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 was down
0.9 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up 1.1 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-20-00 1026 </TRAILER>
