<DOCNO> APW20000120.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 10:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Helms To Visit U.N., Talk About Dues  </HEADLINE>
   By TOM RAUM Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Sen. Jesse Helms, one of the harshest congressional
critics of the United Nations, is offering the world body a truce.
</P>
<P>
	   But he's mixing his overture with a pitch for structural change and a
smaller U.S. share of the peacekeeping burden.
</P>
<P>
	   The conservative chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, who in
the past has ridiculed U.N. leaders as ``dysfunctional'' and ``cry babies,'' is
ready to plead for better relations, a spokesman says.
</P>
<P>
	   But at the same time, Helms, R-N.C., plans to tell the Security Council
exactly what he expects in return for a congressional agreement to pay nearly $1
billion in back dues owed by the United States.
</P>
<P>
	   Helms was to address the Security Council today, becoming the first U.S.
legislator to do so. He was invited to speak by the current council chairman,
U.S. Ambassador Richard Holbrooke. ``It's his day,'' Holbrooke told reporters as
Helms arrived at U.N. headquarters today.
</P>
<P>
	   Helms plans to ``express his hope for new, better relations with the United
Nations,'' said Marc Thiessen, Helms' spokesman. But Thiessen also said Helms
would assert his view that reforms are needed at the world organization and that
it must know its limitations.
</P>
<P>
	   Among other criticisms, Helms has taken issue with Secretary General Kofi
Annan's calls for increased ``global engagement.''
</P>
<P>
	   Holbrooke said Wednesday that Helms' visit ``has to help. It has to reduce
misunderstandings. It has to increase understanding here in the U.N. of the
Helms-Biden benchmarks and I hope it will be a two-way street.''
</P>
<P>
	   On Friday, other members of the Foreign Relations Committee will join Helms
for a meeting with Annan, lunch at U.N. headquarters, and a committee hearing at
a nearby office building that will look into recent developments at the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We in the Congress don't do nearly enough of this sort of thing,'' said
committee member Sen. Chuck Hagel, R-Neb.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It will be a good exchange in general areas. We'll get into things like
Iraq, peacekeeping in the Balkans. We want to hear a little more about Africa,''
Hagel said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
	   Hagel said that ``you always run the risk'' that some committee members
might use the session as a platform for hurling new invectives at the United
Nations. But, he said, ``I think it's critically important for us to get out of
Washington, to get where the world is real.''
</P>
<P>
	   In late 1999, Congress voted to pay $926 million in U.N. arrears over three
years, ending years of debate on unrelated issues like international abortion
programs that had held up the payments.
</P>
<P>
	   But the legislation also included about two dozen conditions, which must be
met for all the money to be released. One of the conditions is that the United
Nations maintain a zero-growth budget. Other conditions call for a reduction in
the U.S. share of the U.N. peacekeeping budget from the current 31 percent to 25
percent; and in the regular budget from 25 percent to 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   The United States now must try to persuade the other 187 U.N. members to go
along with these demands.
</P>
<P>
	   The leadoff witness at Friday's hearing will be Holbrooke. After a rocky
confirmation process last year that wound up with Holbrooke's winning Helms'
support, Holbrooke invited Helms to bring his committee to New York to observe
the organization in action.
</P>
<P>
	   The Security Council first planned to accept Helms' testimony behind closed
doors. But at the urging of Helms and Holbrooke, the panel agreed to open the
session.
</P>
<P>
	   Helms arrived in New York on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition to public appearances, Helms and committee members have various
private meetings over the next two days scheduled with Holbrooke and other U.N.
officials, said Holbrooke spokeswoman Mary Ellen Glynn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-20-00 1039 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000120.0125 </DOCNO>
