<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Helms Seeks U.N. Reforms  </HEADLINE>
   By TOM RAUM Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Sen. Jesse Helms, one of the harshest congressional
critics of the United Nations, offered ``my hand of friendship'' today to the
world body but coupled his overture with sharp warning that the organization not
overstep its bounds.
</P>
<P>
	   ``A United Nations that seeks to impose its presumed authority on the
American people without their consent begs for confrontation, and I want to be
candid, eventual U.S. withdrawal,'' Helms said in prepared remarks.
</P>
<P>
	   Helms, chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, accused the
188-member U.N. General Assembly of an anti-American bias in many of its
activities and said that Americans ``have grown increasingly frustrated with
what they feel is a lack of gratitude.''
</P>
<P>
	   Still, Helms, R-N.C., said he hoped that relations would improve between the
world body and the Republican-led U.S. Congress.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It is not my intent to offend you, and I hope I will not,'' Helms said.
``It is my intent to extend to you my hand of friendship and convey the hope
that in the days to come ... we can join in a mutual respect.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-20-00 1104 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000120.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 11:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Russia Discuss Arms Cuts  </HEADLINE>
   By ALEXANDER G. HIGGINS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   GENEVA (AP) -- U.S. and Russian officials tried today to break a logjam over
nuclear arms cuts and missile defense, while the world's main disarmament forum
appeared to be waiting for developments from those talks.
</P>
<P>
	   John Holum, the Clinton administration's top disarmament specialist, met
with his Russian counterpart in Geneva, also the site of the 66-nation
Conference on Disarmament.
</P>
<P>
	   Many ambassadors to the conference said they expected an address from Holum,
but an aide said no speech was planned. A limited session heard only Ireland's
concerns that the conference get global disarmament talks moving or risk
countries building their own nuclear arsenals.
</P>
<P>
	   But Holum and Yuri Kapralov, head of the Russian Foreign Ministry's arms
control department, stayed well away. Aides said they were holding discussions
elsewhere in the city.
</P>
<P>
	   At issue are attempts to get the Russian parliament to approve the START II
treaty so the countries can move on to START III.
</P>
<P>
	   Adding to the sensitivity of the talks is Washington's desire to reopen the
1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty so it can develop a limited nuclear defense.
</P>
<P>
	   The United States says such a system is needed to defend against attacks
from rogue nations and poses no threat to Russia. Moscow says it would upset the
strategic balance and launch a new arms race.
</P>
<P>
	   The Holum-Kapralov session is the latest high-level U.S.-Russian meeting to
follow up on former President Boris Yeltsin's agreement with President Clinton
to at least discuss ABM modifications.
</P>
<P>
	   Despite the failure of a prototype U.S. missile interceptor to hit its
target above the Pacific Ocean this week, diplomats were concerned that the U.S.
efforts were part of the unraveling of world disarmament efforts.
</P>
<P>
	   Irish Ambassador Anne Anderson described the ABM treaty as ``under
challenge'' and noted that U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan described it as ``a
cornerstone of strategic stability.''
</P>
<P>
	   The acting head of the delegation from China said his nation still fears the
impact the U.S. plans could have on the global network of arms agreements.
</P>
<P>
	   China joined with Russia in a joint statement last May to say deployment of
a missile defense system would violate ``a fundamental obligation under the ABM
treaty not to deploy ABM systems for the defense of national territory.''
</P>
<P>
	   Ambassador Li Changhe told the conference then that U.S. plans would
``trigger a new round of the arms race.'' Russian Ambassador Vasily S. Sidorov
said it would upset ``the whole system of international treaties in the
disarmament field.''
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. and Russian diplomats refused to say if the talks were making progress.
</P>
<P>
	   START II, which would halve U.S. and Russian nuclear arsenals to 3,000-3,500
warheads each, was signed in 1993 and ratified by the U.S. Senate in 1996.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The START process has stalled,'' Annan said in a plea read Tuesday at the
opening of the conference that participants put ``a real sense of urgency'' into
efforts to break the stalemate.
</P>
<P>
	   The deadlock is ``part of a wider and disturbing stagnation in the overall
disarmament and nonproliferation agenda,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
	   The Conference on Disarmament, meanwhile, was meeting for the first time
since the U.S. Senate rejected in October the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty the
forum negotiated in 1996.
</P>
<P>
	   That treaty also lacks ratification from such declared or ``threshold''
nuclear countries as China, Russia, India, Pakistan and Israel. Of the nuclear
powers, only France and Britain have ratified it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-20-00 1109 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000120.0129 </DOCNO>
