<DOCNO> APW20000120.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 11:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Helms Seeks U.N. Reforms  </HEADLINE>
   By TOM RAUM Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Sen. Jesse Helms, one of the harshest critics of the
United Nations, extended a ``hand of friendship'' to the world body today but
mixed the overture with a warning to the organization to trim its bureaucracy
and not overstep its authority.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The American people ... have grown increasingly frustrated with what they
feel is a lack of gratitude,'' Helms, R-N.C., said in the first address of a
U.S. lawmaker to the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
	   He said the United Nations must trim its spending and not draw the United
States into ``entangling alliances.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``A United Nations that seeks to impose its presumed authority on the
American people without their consent begs for confrontation, and I want to be
candid, eventual U.S. withdrawal,'' Helms said.
</P>
<P>
	   Helms, chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, accused the
188-member U.N. General Assembly of an anti-American bias in many of its
activities.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I have received literally thousands of letters from Americans all across
the country expressing their deep frustration with this institution,'' Helms
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Still, Helms, said he hoped that relations would improve between the world
body and the Republican-led U.S. Congress.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It is not my intent to offend you, and I hope I will not,'' Helms said.
``It is my intent to extend to you my hand of friendship and convey the hope
that in the days to come ... we can join in a mutual respect.''
</P>
<P>
	   Helms, who in the past has ridiculed U.N. leaders as ``dysfunctional'' and
``cry babies,'' sought to mix a stern lecture with folksy charm, saying he hoped
``you have a translator here who can speak Southern.''
</P>
<P>
	   He called for ``a pattern of understanding and friendship'' between U.N.
delegates and Americans.
</P>
<P>
	   Helms sat in a seat at the top of the horseshoe-shaped Security Council
table, mostly reading his remarks from a loose-leaf notebook, sometimes banging
his hands on the table to emphasize a point. Council members looked on with
little apparent emotion as he spoke.
</P>
<P>
	   The Security Council has 15 members, including the permanent five which have
veto power: the United States, Russia, China, France and Britain.
</P>
<P>
	   Helms told the council exactly what he expects in return for a congressional
agreement to pay nearly $1 billion in back dues owed by the United States.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The money we spend on the U.N. is not charity,'' Helms said. ``To the
contrary, it is an investment -- an investment from which the American people
rightly expect a return.''
</P>
<P>
	   Helms was invited to speak by the current council chairman, U.S. Ambassador
Richard Holbrooke.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's his day,'' Holbrooke told reporters as Helms arrived at U.N.
headquarters. Holbrooke introduced Helms to the council, calling it a ``historic
occasion'' and crediting Helms' support for his own confirmation by the U.S.
Senate last year, after months of delay.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I want to welcome you to this historic room, where wars have been avoided
at times and at other times the Security Council has failed to prevent wars,''
Holbrooke told Helms.
</P>
<P>
	   But Helms said the Security Council had a ``mixed record'' in recent
conflicts.
</P>
<P>
	   He said it ``performed admirably'' in ending Iraqi aggression against Kuwait
in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
	   ``In the more recent case of Kosovo, it was paralyzed. The U.N. peacekeeping
mission in Bosnia was a disaster, and its failure to protect the Bosnian people
from Serb genocide is well documented,'' Helms said.
</P>
<P>
	   Among other criticisms, Helms has taken issue with Secretary General Kofi
Annan's calls for increased ``global engagement.''
</P>
<P>
	   The United Nations ``must respect national sovereignty'' and not seek ``to
impose its utopian vision of international law on Americans,'' Helms said.
</P>
<P>
	   On Friday, other members of the Foreign Relations Committee will join Helms
for a meeting with Annan, lunch at U.N. headquarters, and a committee hearing at
a nearby office building that will look into recent developments at the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We in the Congress don't do nearly enough of this sort of thing,'' said
committee member Sen. Chuck Hagel, R-Neb.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It will be a good exchange in general areas. We'll get into things like
Iraq, peacekeeping in the Balkans. We want to hear a little more about Africa,''
Hagel said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
	   Hagel said that ``you always run the risk'' that some committee members
might use the session as a platform for hurling new invectives at the United
Nations. But, he said, ``I think it's critically important for us to get out of
Washington, to get where the world is real.''
</P>
<P>
	   In late 1999, Congress voted to pay $926 million in U.N. arrears over three
years, ending years of debate on unrelated issues like international abortion
programs that had held up the payments.
</P>
<P>
	   But the legislation also included about two dozen conditions, which must be
met for all the money to be released. One of the conditions is that the United
Nations maintain a zero-growth budget. Other conditions call for a reduction in
the U.S. share of the U.N. peacekeeping budget from the current 31 percent to 25
percent; and in the regular budget from 25 percent to 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   The United States now must try to persuade the other 187 U.N. members to go
along with these demands.
</P>
<P>
	   Helms told the Security Council he knew ``some don't like reforms dictated
to them by the United States.''
</P>
<P>
	   Still, he said, ``If we are to have a new beginning, we must endeavor to
understand each other better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-20-00 1154 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
