<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that are moving substantially or trading heavily
today on the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq Stock Market.
</P>
<P>
	   IBM's fourth-quarter profit tumbled 11 percent as the company struggled with
customers' worries over the Year 2000 computer bug. But profits still beat Wall
Street forecasts, and IBM officials encouraged analysts to leave their forecasts
for 2000 intact.
</P>
<P>
	   The bookseller expects fourth-quarter earnings to top estimates due to
strong sales at its superstores. Barnes &AMP; Noble said it expects to report $1.38
a share in profits, above analysts' estimates of $1.21 a share.
</P>
<P>
	   Cascade Investment LLC, an investment vehicle for Microsoft Corp. chairman
Bill Gates, has claimed a 5.01 percent stake in Avista. Gates disclosed in a
filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission that he holds 1.79 million
shares in Avista, a Spokane, Wash., energy company.
</P>
<P>
	   Tobacco company Swedish Match AB plans to buy 64 percent of the shares in
General Cigar Holding, a U.S. company which sells cigar brands including
Macanudo and Cohiba. Last spring, Swedish Match bought General Cigar's mass
market operations.
</P>
<P>
	   The company expects to drastically miss earnings estimates for the fourth
quarter. Sunterra said it expects to report operating income of 1 cent to 8
cents per share, well below First Call/Thomson Financial estimates of 42 cents a
share. Sunterra develops and operates time-share vacation resorts.
</P>
<P>
	   The company said its auditors have required it to adopt more conservative
accounting practices, which forced it to restate third-quarter results. Legato
also missed estimates for its fourth quarter. The company makes backup and
recovery software.
</P>
<P>
	   The nation's largest maker of lasers used in vision-correcting surgery said
demand for procedures using its surgical laser did not grow in the fourth
quarter. Visx met earnings forecasts of 38 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
	   The company said its experimental cancer drug, Endostatin, is faring well in
an initial round of safety studies. EntreMed also preparing to start testing two
new compounds in humans some time this quarter.
</P>
</TEXT>
