<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DeLay Opens New GOP Drive  </HEADLINE>
   By ALAN FRAM Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- House Majority Whip Tom DeLay implored conservatives
Thursday to back the Republican drive to capture the White House and hold the
party's congressional majority this November, saying the GOP is defending ``the
great principles that have always defined America.''
</P>
<P>
	   In a 21-minute speech brimming with attacks on President Clinton and
liberals, DeLay sought to rally conservatives who in recent years have despaired
over GOP compromises on spending and other issues. DeLay, R-Texas, has become
one of the conservative movement's closest allies in Congress.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Our cause -- the defense of our values -- has never changed,'' DeLay said
in remarks at the conservative Heritage Foundation. ``We lack only a united
conservative front that can guide a cause to victory. And that means a
Republican president working with a Republican Congress.''
</P>
<P>
	   Many Republicans have said poor turnout by dispirited conservatives cost the
GOP several House seats in the 1998 elections. The GOP's hold on the 435-member
House is now so slim that a net Democratic gain of five seats would give them
control of the chamber. Republicans consider a big conservative turnout crucial
to their electoral prospects in this fall's voting.
</P>
<P>
	   ``So you can understand my frustration when some of our friends in the
conservative movement allow the perfect to be the enemy of the good,'' DeLay
said. ``All conservatives want to do more, but achieving more will require an
expanded Republican majority.''
</P>
<P>
	   In his speech and in remarks afterward to reporters, DeLay suggested that
the GOP's congressional agenda should be pushed rightward this year. Such a
strategy could conflict with that of GOP presidential front-runner George W.
Bush, who has been trying to give himself a softer edge than congressional
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
	   DeLay told reporters that his fellow Republicans should ``stand up for what
you believe in and not run from the onslaught that is to come'' if measures are
vetoed.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's time to rediscover our world view and apply it to everything we're
passing in the House,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   DeLay mentioned few specific proposals. But he said a GOP drive aimed at
``rediscovering our values'' would include supporting ``faith-based
institutions,'' attacking violence and obscenity, reducing taxes and regulations
that he said hurt families, supporting the military and a foreign policy that
supports religious and political freedom.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We will be the foot soldiers in what, I believe, will someday be
recognized as the effort that not only contained, but rolled back the attack on
the great principles that have always defined America,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Erik Smith, spokesman for the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee,
said that with GOP incumbents vacating House seats in several moderate, suburban
districts, a conservative shift by the Republican Party would help Democrats.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Following Tom DeLay's path to the far right is what's going to lose the
House'' for Republicans, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
	   DeLay, long one of Clinton's most unrelenting critics, said the White House
``has moved through the cherished institutions of our nation like a threshing
machine.'' He cited the administration's decision to return 6-year-old Elian
Gonzalez to his father in Cuba as evidence of the need to introduce ``moral
principle'' to politics.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We cannot make great progress with a chief executive who believes that it
can, under any circumstances, be in a child's best interests to live under
Castro's communism,'' DeLay said.
</P>
<P>
	   He also credited congressional Republicans with opposing ``a culture of
fashionable nihilism'' led by abortion-rights supporters and activist judges.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We have been alone in mounting a broad challenge to a liberalism designed
in elite universities and marketed by the entertainment moguls who employ their
graduates,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   DeLay's remarks came a week before Clinton is scheduled to deliver his State
of the Union address. With Congress not commencing this year's session until
next week, Republicans have been hoping to gain attention with speeches by DeLay
and other congressional leaders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
