<HEADLINE> Cohen Backs Swede for Iraq Agency  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Defense Secretary William Cohen flew to New York on
Thursday to meet with United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan and express
the Clinton administration's support for Annan's candidate to head a new U.N.
weapons inspection agency for Iraq.
</P>
<P>
	   Annan wants Sweden's ambassador to Washington, Rolf Ekeus, to head the
inspection agency but Russia, China and France blocked the choice in the U.N.
Security Council on Tuesday. Security Council members decided to continue
consultations, and U.N. Ambassador Richard Holbrooke said Ekeus remained a
candidate.
</P>
<P>
	   Ekeus headed an earlier U.N. effort to account for Iraq's weapons of mass
destruction before he became Sweden's ambassador to Washington. There have been
no U.N. weapons inspections in Iraq since December 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   Cohen's spokesman, Kenneth Bacon, said the defense secretary also would
discuss African security issues with Annan, as well as meet with Holbrooke.
Cohen is planning a trip to Africa in February.
</P>
</TEXT>
