<HEADLINE> Dow Down 119.68; Nasdaq Up 27.99  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue-chip stocks fell steeply today, while robust corporate
earnings reports from several technology companies boosted the Nasdaq further
into record territory.
</P>
<P>
	   In afternoon trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was
down 119.68 at 11,369.68. Its loss stemmed largely from Alcoa.
</P>
<P>
	   The Nasdaq composite index was up 27.99 at 4,179.28, moving past the closing
record of 4,151.29 reached Wednesday. In earlier trading, the
technology-dominated index rose as much as 73 points.
</P>
<P>
	   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was
down 10.37 at 1,445.53.
</P>
<P>
	   Alcoa dropped 4 7/16 to 73 11/16 as the company announced plans to restart
primary aluminum production to meet growing global demand. The announcement
caused aluminum prices to drop. A steady rise in aluminum prices last year
helped Alcoa turn in the highest returns of any Dow component stock.
</P>
<P>
	   Consumer products companies also fared poorly today. Procter &AMP; Gamble fell 1
3/4 to 110 1/8 and 3M fell 4 to 94 13/16.
</P>
<P>
	   Investors once again poured money into shares of large technology companies,
several of which reported better than expected earnings late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   "The earnings reports bolstered the positive outlook about technology and
its prospects for growth," said Paul Cherney, market analyst at Standard &AMP;
Poor's.
</P>
<P>
	   IBM, which sent a chill through the technology sector last fall when it said
sales had slumped due to worries about the Year 2000 computer bug, easily beat
Wall Street's profit forecasts. While company officials warned that lingering
concerns will continue to take a toll on sales in the current quarter, they
encouraged analysts to leave their profit forecasts for 2000 intact.
</P>
<P>
	   IBM stock rose 6 5/16 to 121 13/16 today.
</P>
<P>
	   On the Nasdaq, Apple Computer soared 11 1/2 to 118 1/16. Apple said late
Wednesday it earned $183 million, or $1.03 a share, in its most recent quarter.
Strong sales of its iMac computer helped Apple coast past published estimates of
90 cents per share and past the "whisper number" of 97 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
	   America Online, which has seen its stock price tumble since the company
announced its intentions to merge with Time Warner, edged up  1/2 to 64 9/16.
AOL said late Wednesday it earned $224 million, or 9 cents a share, in the
quarter ended Dec. 31, more than double the $86 million, or 4 cents a share, in
the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
	   Analysts had expected AOL to earn 8 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
	   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by an 8-to-5 margin on the New York
Stock Exchange, where volume came to 896.00 million shares, ahead of Wednesday's
pace.
</P>
<P>
	   Trading was fairly volatile a day ahead of Friday's "double witching"
session, when quarterly stock and index options expire, forcing traders to
adjust their portfolios. These quarterly deadlines tend to increase volume and
volatility.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 5.11 to 525.13. The index,
which lagged through much of 1999, has surged so far this year and has set new
closing records in the past three sessions on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're getting some measurable outperformance from the small companies,"
Cherney said. "Investors appear unwilling to put all their eggs in one basket,"
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
