<HEADLINE> Navy chooses Camden over Bayonne as permanent home of USS New  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   WASHINGTON (AP) - The U.S. Navy has chosen the Camden, N.J., waterfront
as the permanent home for the retired battleship USS New Jersey, members of
Congress said Thursday.
<P>
	   The decision, which the Navy is expected to officially announce shortly,
will deliver a huge victory to South Jersey advocates who said the ship belongs
close to its place of birth, the Philadelphia Navy Yard.
</P>
<P>
	   The Navy decision goes against the recommendation of the state's Battleship
New Jersey Commission, which by a majority vote endorsed placing the battleship
at a pier in Bayonne, N.J., across the harbor from New York City.
</P>
<P>
	   Bayonne and Camden both advanced detailed arguments about why they would
they would be the best place for a floating museum.
</P>
<P>
	   Bayonne boosters cited the city's proximity to New York and other population
centers of northern New Jersey. The case for Camden included the ship's ties to
the Philadelphia shipyard, where it was built in 1942, and the idea that the
Delaware River's freshwater would be kinder to the ship's massive hull.
</P>
<P>
	   The highly decorated New Jersey, one of only four battleships left in the
world, cruised the seas through 40 years and four wars. Launched during World
War II, it employed its immense guns in Korea, Vietnam and off the coast of
Lebanon in 1983.
</P>
<P>
	   "This will be a great thing for the area, a great thing for the area's
veterans and a great thing for Camden," said Rep. Jim Saxton, R-Mount Holly, who
helped lead the Camden push.
</P>
<P>
	   Saxton said Camden proved the more economically viable location, in part
because Bayonne would have had to compete against an existing floating military
museum, the aircraft carrier USS Intrepid, located across New York Harbor.
</P>
<P>
	   State Assemblyman Joe Azzolina, chairman of the state battleship commission,
promised to implement the Navy's decision even though it went against his
long-held belief that the ship should go to the former Military Ocean Terminal
in Bayonne.
</P>
<P>
	   "Congratulations to Camden!" he wrote in pen on the bottom of a press
release.
</P>
<P>
	   The battleship currently sits at the Philadelphia Naval Business Center,
formerly the Philadelphia Naval Shipyard. It was towed there from Bremerton,
Wash., last year on a 5,800-mile trip that included its 10th - and final -
passage through the Panama Canal.
</P>
<P>
	   The battle for the battleship opened a long-standing political rift between
North Jersey versus South Jersey.
</P>
<P>
	   Eight northern New Jersey congressman advocated Bayonne, while three
southern New Jersey congressman endorsed Camden.
</P>
<P>
	   South Jersey advocates also secured endorsements from congressmen
representing parts of Pennsylvania, Delaware and Maryland, as well as members of
New York's delegation, who worried that a battleship museum in North Jersey
would compete for tourist dollars with the Intrepid, docked off Manhattan's West
Side.
</P>
<P>
	   Also weighing in for Camden was Andrew Cuomo, secretary of Housing and Urban
Development, who said a floating battleship museum would support federal efforts
to make the city an economic empowerment zone.
</P>
<P>
	   Closely divided, New Jersey's battleship commission voted in 1998 to berth
the warship in Bayonne. But several members supporting Bayonne did so with the
caveat that the ship should move to Liberty State Park in Jersey City if it is
ever renovated to accommodate such a huge vessel.
</P>
<P>
	   Jersey City officials subsequently agreed not to compete with Bayonne before
the Navy's ship-donation program. But Camden did file its own application.
</P>
<P>
	   Gov. Christie Whitman originally said she would abide by the advice of the
commission. But then she proclaimed herself neutral, pledging $6 million in
state money to restore the ship to museum readiness, wherever it ended up.
</P>
<P>
	   Economics, not just pride, was at issue. Bayonne and Camden are both aging
cities that would welcome the boost of tourism dollars. Also, since the federal
government cannot subsidize a donated warship, a failed museum in either
location could force taxpayers to cover its expense.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition to the $6 million from the state, an estimated $15 million more
is needed from various public and private organizations to prepare the
battleship as a tourist attraction. Bayonne and Camden supporters all agreed
that the museum, once open, will have operating costs of about $3 million per
year.
</P>
<P>
	   The Naval Sea Systems Command, the Navy branch that runs the ship donation
program, kept its deliberations tightly private. Both proposals - Camden's was
estimated to reach 1,700 pages - were not available to the public.
</P>
<P>
	   Early Thursday afternoon, South Jersey congressmen lobbying on behalf of
Camden scheduled a 3:15 p.m. press conference at the Philadelphia shipyard,
knowing a decision was coming, believing it was in their favor, but not entirely
sure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
