<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pataki suggests higher license fees for barbers, cosmeticians  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Steve Starr pays more attention to his own budget
than he does Gov. George Pataki's executive budget. But this time, the Army
veteran and barber is going to be watching to see what kind of cutting state
legislators do.
<P>
	   An increase in examination and license renewal fees for barbers,
cosmetologists and nail specialists is among the proposed $28 million in fee
increases proposed in Pataki's executive budget for fiscal 2000-01.
</P>
<P>
	   "I don't like it at all," said Starr, who cuts hair at Siena Unisex Hair
Styles in Colonie, a suburb of the state capital. "But it's something we have to
do to keep our licenses. Sometimes you have to do things you don't like."
</P>
<P>
	   Barbers aren't the only ones who'll see their costs grow if Pataki's
proposals are adopted by the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
	   Other fee increases include an average 20 percent increase in hunting and
fishing licenses, increases in license fees for real estate brokers and agents,
notary publics, as well as security guards and an extension on a fee for
fishermen who harvest clams and quahogs.
</P>
<P>
	   The cost of crime will also go up, with the fees charged to crooks doubling
in some case.
</P>
<P>
	   In all, fees make up roughly $800 million of Pataki's $77 billion budget
this time around, Pataki budget spokesman Kevin Quinn said.
</P>
<P>
	   In comparison, fees made up about $756 million in Pataki's $72.7 billion
spending plan last year. Fees went up $37.9 million during that budget.
</P>
<P>
	   Quinn points out that Pataki has been cutting taxes in all of his budgets,
including a proposed $2.3 billion in this year's proposed plan. He also said all
the fee increases will benefit the people who are paying them, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The increases for hunting and fishing licenses would go to the state's
Conservation Fund, which pays for about half of the state's fish and wildlife
programs. "Without this increase, the state would have to cut back on its
hunting and fishing programs," said Brian O'Connor, spokesman for the Department
of Environmental Conservation.
</P>
<P>
	   The increases for barbers, cosmetologists, security guards and real estate
brokers will go to improving the computers at the Department of State, which
will eventually allow online licensing for those professions, Quinn said.
</P>
<P>
	   If approved, new barbers, cosmetologists and nail specialists would see a
$10 increase in the examination fee to $25 from $15 and experienced ones would
see a $10 increase for licensing renewals to $30 from $20.
</P>
<P>
	   Many of those fees haven't been increased in years, Quinn said.
</P>
<P>
	   Don't worry about the price of haircuts or a pedicure going up, though.
"It's only a one-time fee," Starr said. "It shouldn't affect the prices at all."
</P>
<P>
	   Other proposed increases include:
</P>
<P>
	   - Doubling the Crime Victim Assistance Fund fee charged to criminals to $10
from the previous $5. The mandatory crime surcharges also are going up: to $50
from $40 for criminal violations, to $110 from $85 for misdemeanors and to $200
from $150 for felonies. All those fees go to the Crime Victim Assistance Fund,
Quinn said.
</P>
<P>
	   - Extending the fee for fishermen who take clams and quahogs from New York
waters. The 15-cent-per-bushel clam surcharge and 10-cent-per-bushel quahog
surcharge was supposed to expire in January 2001 but the money is needed to fund
marine research, Quinn said.
</P>
<P>
	   - A new fee on public water systems to fund monitoring and testing public
waters. Public water systems that have less than 1,000 connections will have to
pay $100 annually, while larger systems will have to pay $3 per connection.
</P>
<P>
	   "This will dramatically improve the quality of drinking water around the
state," said John Signor, spokesman for the state Health Department. "This will
help prevent a repeat of the tragic events that happened at the Washington
County fairgrounds."
</P>
<P>
	   State officials blamed water contaminated by cow manure at the annual fair
for the deaths of a child and an elderly man in September. About 1,000 people
were sickened with the E. coli bacteria.
</P>
<P>
	   Lawmakers already are lining up to fight some of Pataki's proposed
increases, however. The Legislature will be holding hearings on Pataki's
executive budget for the next few weeks before taking up the budget later this
year. The next state fiscal year begins on April 1.
</P>
<P>
	   State Assembly Majority Leader Michael Bragman, who has opposed sportsman
fee increases, wants Pataki to wait until after an audit of the state
Conservation Fund is completed before asking for an increase in hunting and
fishing fees.
</P>
<P>
	   "Only this independent evaluation will provide the data the Legislature will
need to responsibly address fee increases," Bragman said.
</P>
<P>
	   "I have maintained for more than a year ... the need for a resident fee
increase has not yet been demonstrated or justified."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
