<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 16:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Whitman seeks probe of auto emissions memos  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Gov. Christie Whitman Thursday directed the
Attorney General's Office to investigate why a state subcontractor's concerns
about the new auto emissions test system weren't brought to the state's
attention.
<P>
	   In memos written in the months preceding the mid-December startup of the
enhanced test, subcontractor Sierra Research of Pasadena, Calif., warned that
Parsons Infrastructure and Technology Group's testing equipment was vulnerable
to freezing temperatures and that Parsons' workers were not adequately trained -
issues that later led to long lines and frayed nerves at New Jersey's inspection
stations.
</P>
<P>
	   "Disclosure of this information should have been automatic, not optional,"
the governor said at a hastily arranged news conference Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   "I want a panel to tell me what happened and why it happened. I don't care
where the investigation leads," she said. "I've heard nothing, seen nothing that
indicates anything criminal here."
</P>
<P>
	   Whitman directed Attorney General John J. Farmer Jr. to convene a special
panel, to include members of the public, to investigate Sierra's claims and why
they were not disclosed to state officials who awarded the testing bid to
Parsons.
</P>
<P>
	   Parsons' system has been in disarray since the state's private vendor
launched the enhanced safety and emissions test on Dec. 13.
</P>
<P>
	   The new test, which is aimed at meeting Clean Air Act mandates, is up to
five times longer than the old inspection process, and a series of computer
glitches, equipment problems and staffing woes conspired to force long lines and
hours-long waiting times at many of the state's 32 centralized inspection
stations. In some cases, cold weather forced equipment to fail.
</P>
<P>
	   The Whitman administration in 1998 signed Parsons to a seven-year, $400
million contract that drew controversy. Parsons was the only vendor to bid for
the job.
</P>
<P>
	   Whitman has grown increasingly angry at Parsons, and state officials say
they intend to remove $580,000 from a scheduled Feb. 10 state payment to the
firm because the long waiting times violate the contract.
</P>
<P>
	   Parsons officials say the impostion of sanctions by the Whitman
administration is "premature," and that some of the long lines were actually
caused by late software changes ordered by the state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
