<DOCNO> APW20000120.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Down 130.06; New Nasdaq High  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue-chip stocks fell steeply today amid worries that
rising interest rates will ultimately cut into corporate earnings, while signs
of strong growth from leading technology companies boosted the Nasdaq further
into record territory.
</P>
<P>
	   According to preliminary calculations, the Dow Jones industrial average fell
138.06 to close at 11,351.30. The blue-chip index pitched wildly today, rising
as much as 68 points in early trading and plunging as much as 214 at midday.
</P>
<P>
	   The Nasdaq composite index rose, extending the record high reached just
Wednesday. Broader stock indicators were mixed.
</P>
<P>
	   Stocks rose at the opening bell after IBM, which sent a chill through the
technology sector last fall when it said sales had slumped due to worries about
the Year 2000 computer bug, easily beat Wall Street's profit forecasts.
</P>
<P>
	   While company officials warned that lingering concerns will continue to take
a toll on sales in the current quarter, they encouraged analysts to leave their
profit forecasts for 2000 intact. IBM stock rose today.
</P>
<P>
	   Alcoa dropped as the company announced plans to restart primary aluminum
production to meet growing global demand. The announcement sparked fears that
aluminum prices will drop, hurting Alcoa's bottom line. A steady rise in
aluminum prices last year helped Alcoa turn in the highest returns of any Dow
component stock.
</P>
<P>
	   Consumer products companies also fared poorly today. Procter &AMP; Gamble and 3M
fell.
</P>
<P>
	   Analysts said lingering worries that the Federal Reserve will raise interest
rates this year are affecting blue-chip stocks much more sharply than
high-flying technology companies. Higher rates can cut into corporate profits by
making it more expensive to borrow money.
</P>
<P>
	   "Investors seem to feel that as long as the technology companies are
projected to grow 40 or 50 percent per year, who cares about interest rates?"
said A.C. Moore, chief investment strategist for Dunvegan Associates in Santa
Barbara, Calif. "More mature companies can't possibly grow at that rate."
</P>
<P>
	   Indeed, investors rewarded several technology leaders for their strong
growth today.
</P>
<P>
	   On the Nasdaq, Apple Computer soared. Apple said late Wednesday it earned
$183 million, or $1.03 a share, in its most recent quarter. Strong sales of its
iMac computer helped Apple coast past published estimates of 90 cents per share
and past the "whisper number" of 97 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
	   "The earnings reports bolstered the positive outlook about technology and
its prospects for growth," said Paul Cherney, market analyst at Standard &AMP;
Poor's.
</P>
<P>
	   Engage Technologies rose sharply after buying two online advertising
businesses from its parent company, CMGI Inc.
</P>
<P>
	   Not every technology leader was rewarded for strong profits. America Online,
which has seen its stock price tumble since the company announced its intentions
to merge with Time Warner, fell slightly. AOL said late Wednesday it earned $224
million, or 9 cents a share, in the quarter ended Dec. 31, more than double the
$86 million, or 4 cents a share, in the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
	   Analysts had expected AOL to earn 8 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
	   Trading was fairly volatile a day ahead of Friday's "double witching"
session, when quarterly stock and index options expire, forcing traders to
adjust their portfolios. These quarterly deadlines tend to increase volume and
volatility.
</P>
<P>
	   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose to a new record. The index,
which lagged through much of 1999, has surged so far this year and has set new
closing records in four consecutive sessions.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're getting some measurable outperformance from the small companies,"
Cherney said. "Investors appear unwilling to put all their eggs in one basket,"
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-20-00 1626 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
