<DOCNO> APW20000120.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Discusses Spiritual Anchor  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sharing a rare insight into how he has dealt with the
emotional fallout of the impeachment scandal, President Clinton said he has
sought a ``spiritual anchor'' and to forgive those he feels had wronged him.
</P>
<P>
	   ``What I have gained more than anything else is a certain humility in
recognizing how important forgiveness is, but how it doesn't count and it can't
count unless you can give it as well as ask for it,'' the president said in an
interview with the Christian Science Monitor.
</P>
<P>
	   In the interview, which was conducted on Tuesday in Boston but released by
the White House on Thursday, Clinton was asked about his own ``spiritual
growth'' over the last 18 months.
</P>
<P>
	   While he never mentioned the impeachment directly, he has said he was
seeking spiritual counseling following the revelations about his relationship
with former intern Monica Lewinksy and the ensuing impeachment fight.
</P>
<P>
	   The president indicated that one of his personal challenges has been
abandoning resentment over the investigation into the matter. Clinton was
impeached by the House, but the Senate declined to vote him out of office.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The thing that I have really had to work on is trying to gain some
spiritual anchor that will enable me to give up resentments and disappointment
and anger,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton remarked that he had sought advice from former South African
President Nelson Mandela about how Mandela had learned to forgive those who had
jailed him under his country's system of Apartheid.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I've really tried to deal with this in a very serious way and I think I've
learned quite a lot about myself in the process,'' Clinton said. ``And it's an
ongoing effort.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-20-00 1632 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
