<DOCNO> APW20000120.0171 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former NJ sporting head, Whitman fundraiser acquitted  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - A judge Thursday threw out charges against Michael
Francis, ending a trial in which the former head of the New Jersey Sports and
Exposition Authority and Gov. Christie Whitman's ex-chief fundraiser was charged
with trying to force an Atlantic City mall to hire his cleaning company.
<P>
	   Judge Andrew J. Smithson, who earlier dismissed eight criminal counts
against Francis, tossed out the remaining two that were before the Mercer County
jury. Two other charges that were not part of the trial remain lodged against
Francis.
</P>
<P>
	   State prosecutors alleged Francis, Whitman's top money man for her
successful 1993 gubernatorial campaign, threatened the Ocean One Mall with labor
unrest if it did not award his Planned Building Services with a $500,000
cleaning contract.
</P>
<P>
	   The defense responded that there was no evidence that Francis did anything
other than promote his company. His statements that there would be no labor
problems were meant to reassure the mall owners, not threaten or pressure them,
the defense said.
</P>
<P>
	   The judge took the unusual step of stopping the trial before the jury could
consider the charges
</P>
<P>
	   "I truly do not find in this case a scintilla of evidence for the jury to
consider," the judge said. "There's certainly smoke in this case, but I didn't
find any fire. I don't even find a spark."
</P>
<P>
	   "Frankly, I did not want to put Michael Francis through the agony of having
to wait for the jury to reach a verdict," the judge said.
</P>
<P>
	   A spokesman for Attorney General John J. Farmer Jr. said prosecutors were
considering their options, including whether to pursue the remaining two charges
against Francis.
</P>
<P>
	   "We are disappointed that the judge did not permit the case to go to the
jury," said spokesman Chuck Davis. "We'll review the judge's decision and how it
relates to those two charges and then make a decision."
</P>
<P>
	   Whitman, noting the charges that remain against her former fundraiser,
declined comment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Francis could not be reached for comment. But his defense attorney Michael
Chertoff said his client is "elated" at the judge's decision.
</P>
<P>
	   Chertoff, a former U.S. Attorney for New Jersey, said it is highly unusual
for a judge to halt a trial midstream.
</P>
<P>
	   "It suggests the state's case as presented was far short," he said. "The
judge vindicating Michael ... totally undercuts the original charge."
</P>
<P>
	   Based on Smithson's ruling, the state ought to give up prosecuting Francis
on the remaining charges, Chertoff said.
</P>
<P>
	   Francis faced charges of attempted theft by extortion and misusing his
corporate powers relating to an effort to win the cleaning contract. Prosecutors
say his assurances that there would be no labor union problems if his company
got the contract were a veiled threat to mall owners.
</P>
<P>
	   He was initially charged in 1997 with orchestrating a conspiracy to conceal
alleged ties to organized crime from Whitman, and using his unpaid state post to
drum up millions of dollars' worth of business for his company. But those
charges were dismissed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-20-00 1638 </TRAILER>
