<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Democrats set agenda for legislative session  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - House Democrats say this year's legislative
session will include an effort to bail out the cash-strapped University of
Connecticut Health Center.
<P>
	   Education, job training and open space issues also will be priorities for
the 12-week session that begins Feb. 9. It will be the shortest session in the
history of the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
	   "We are very focused, we are very targeted and we are very realistic about
what could be accomplished during this session," House Speaker Moira Lyons said.
</P>
<P>
	   The UConn Health Center in Farmington - which includes the John Dempsey
Hospital and the university's medical and dental schools - poses an immediate
problem, Lyons said. Health center officials say they're facing a $21 million
deficit, and need $12 million from the state to keep the facility running.
</P>
<P>
	   Lyons and House Majority Leader David Pudlin said they want to keep Dempsey
open so the medical and dental schools and research programs don't risk losing
grants they receive by being associated with a hospital. But neither would say
exactly how much they're willing to give UConn.
</P>
<P>
	   "We are asking for an opportunity to maintain, as long as necessary, the
status quo while we have time to study what's wrong," said Pudlin, D-Hartford.
"That's not to say it's a blank check. That that is not to say that it's an
ongoing commitment or that it's not going to be without substantial oversight."
</P>
<P>
	   The state has made $8 million in loans available for other state hospitals,
and plans to conduct a $1 million study of distressed hospitals this session,
lawmakers said. A list of which hospitals will receive the loans is expected in
about a month.
</P>
<P>
	   The Democrats, who control the General Assembly, said they also want to
change the way school districts are funded so that aid no longer is capped.
Other education bills would fund more computers for schools and train more
teachers how to use them in the classroom.
</P>
<P>
	   Expanding the state's HUSKY health-care plan is also on the House Democrats'
agenda. The program was originally set up to provide free health care to
uninsured children, and the House leaders want parents to be covered as well.
</P>
<P>
	   The lawmakers also promised to focus on cleaning up some of the state's
worst polluting power plants.
</P>
<P>
	   Lyons said that while the state is in good financial shape, now is the time
to invest at least $15 million in open space preservation.
</P>
<P>
	   "If we do not take (open spaces) into the public purview and protect them at
this time, they may be lost forever," she said.
</P>
<P>
	   The state Department of Environmental Protection received 2,900 acres of
land in 1999, and Republican Gov. John G. Rowland said he wants to preserve
673,000 acres of land as open space by 2023.
</P>
<P>
	   But the Democrats and Rowland don't see eye to eye when it comes to cutting
the state's gasoline tax. Rowland has been working with his budget staff and the
state Department of Transportation to determine what it would cost to reduce the
32 cents-a-gallon tax - the highest gas tax in the country.
</P>
<P>
	   Lyons and Pudlin said such a cut is out of the question this year.
</P>
<P>
	   "We spend the money we get from the gas tax on the infrastructure of
highways and roads around the state," Pudlin said. "To deprive us of that money
I'm not sure is such a good idea."
</P>
<P>
	   The Democratic leaders will be coming out with another agenda within two
weeks that outlines their plans for reforming campaign financing and the
sheriffs system.
</P>
<P>
	   House Minority Leader Robert Ward, R-Northford, said the Democrats' session
agenda was "one of the weakest I've seen."
</P>
<P>
	   "There's no mention of taxpayers," he said. "It's just repackaging things
we've already done. There's nothing new there."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-20-00 1657 </TRAILER>
