<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 17:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gov't Urges Use of Polio Shots  </HEADLINE>
   By JUSTIN BACHMAN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ATLANTA (AP) -- The government Thursday endorsed polio shots for children
instead of the oral vaccine because of the very small chance that the oral dose
can lead to a polio infection.
</P>
<P>
	   The federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention followed the advice
of an advisory panel that decided last summer the benefits of the oral polio
vaccine no longer outweigh the risks.
</P>
<P>
	   The agency publishes its recommended immunization schedule each January as a
guide for state and local health departments and pediatricians.
</P>
<P>
	   This year's guide also added a recommendation that children get a hepatitis
A vaccine in Western states with historically high rates of the virus: Alaska,
Arizona, California, Idaho, Nevada, New Mexico, Oklahoma, Oregon, South Dakota,
Utah and Washington. Hepatitis A is a relatively mild form of the virus; most
patients require no medical care.
</P>
<P>
	   The CDC also removed a diarrhea vaccine because it can cause bowel
obstruction.
</P>
<P>
	   The oral polio vaccine, developed by Dr. Albert Sabin, has been used for
nearly four decades and played a major role in the elimination of polio. But
because it is made with a live virus, it causes about eight people in the United
States each year to become infected with polio.
</P>
<P>
	   The injectable vaccine developed by the medical pioneer Dr. Jonas Salk in
the 1950s relies on a killed virus. Salk had long insisted his vaccine was
safer, but other scientists said it was not as effective at providing lifelong
immunity.
</P>
<P>
	   According to the new CDC recommendations, the oral vaccine should be used
only in cases of widespread outbreaks, for children traveling to areas where
polio is endemic or epidemic and for children whose parents stop short of
pursuing all four shots in the polio regimen.
</P>
<P>
	   The oral vaccine's U.S. manufacturer, Wyeth-Lederle, stopped making it last
year and has agreed to refund any unused supplies doctors return.
</P>
<P>
	   The American Academy of Pediatrics said last month its members can continue
using their remaining supplies of the oral vaccine if given as the third and
fourth doses. The first and second doses should be the injectable vaccine, the
academy said.
</P>
<P>
	   Dr. Melinda Wharton, the CDC's chief of childhood vaccines and preventable
diseases, said the agency is investigating one report from 1998 of a child that
got polio after being given the half-oral, half-injectable schedule. She said
the case had not been confirmed.
</P>
<P>
	   Dr. Michael Gerber, a pediatrician in Bethesda, Md., and member of the
pediatrics academy's infectious diseases committee, said any such risk is
miniscule.
</P>
<P>
	   But to Informed Parents Against VAAP, a group of parents whose children
contracted vaccine-associated paralytic polio, even a miniscule chance of
infection is too much.
</P>
<P>
	   ``While the risk is small, why should we have any cases?'' said John
Salamone, a member of the group whose 9-year-old son contracted polio from the
oral vaccine in 1991.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-20-00 1708 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000120.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 17:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Navy chooses Camden over Bayonne as permanent home of USS New  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   WASHINGTON (AP) - The hulking battleship USS New Jersey, a decorated
veteran of four wars, will spend its retirement just across the Delaware River
from the shipyard where it was built under the dark cloud of World War II.
<P>
	   Navy Secretary Richard Danzig notified members of Congress Thursday that he
has approved a plan to turn the ship into a floating museum off Camden, N.J.,
near the former Philadelphia Naval Shipyard.
</P>
<P>
	   In choosing Camden, the Navy rejected the advice of a New Jersey state
commission that recommended the ship be placed off Bayonne in northern New
Jersey, across the harbor from New York City.
</P>
<P>
	   Launched in 1942, the battleship New Jersey employed its immense guns in
Korea, Vietnam and off the coast of Lebanon in 1983. It is one of only four
battleships left in the world.
</P>
<P>
	   Bayonne and Camden both advanced detailed arguments about why they would
they would be the best place for a floating museum.
</P>
<P>
	   Bayonne boosters cited the city's proximity to New York and other population
centers of northern New Jersey. The case for Camden included the ship's ties to
the Philadelphia shipyard and the idea that the Delaware River's freshwater
would be kinder to the ship's massive hull.
</P>
<P>
	   "This will be a great thing for the area, a great thing for the area's
veterans and a great thing for Camden," said Rep. Jim Saxton, R-Mount Holly, who
helped lead the Camden campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   Saxton and Rep. Rob Andrews, D-Haddon Heights, said Camden proved the more
economically viable location in part because another floating military museum,
the aircraft carrier USS Intrepid, already exists across New York Harbor from
Bayonne.
</P>
<P>
	   "It doesn't make sense to put two Wal-Marts within a mile and a half of each
other," Andrews said. "The (USS) New Jersey would be competition for the
Intrepid, and vice versa, and it didn't make any sense."
</P>
<P>
	   State Assemblyman Joe Azzolina, chairman of the state battleship commission,
promised to implement the Navy's decision even though it went against his
long-held belief that the ship should go to the former Military Ocean Terminal
in Bayonne.
</P>
<P>
	   "Congratulations to Camden!" he wrote in pen on the bottom of a press
release.
</P>
<P>
	   The battleship currently sits at the former Philadelphia Naval Shipyard, now
officially called the Philadelphia Naval Business Center. It was towed there
from Bremerton, Wash., last year on a 5,800-mile trip that included its 10th -
and final - passage through the Panama Canal.
</P>
<P>
	   The battle for the battleship opened a long-standing political rift pitting
North Jersey against South Jersey.
</P>
<P>
	   Eight northern New Jersey congressman advocated Bayonne, while three
southern New Jersey congressman endorsed Camden.
</P>
<P>
	   South Jersey advocates also secured endorsements from congressmen
representing parts of Pennsylvania, Delaware and Maryland, as well as members of
New York's delegation, who worried that a battleship museum in North Jersey
would compete for tourist dollars with the Intrepid, docked off Manhattan's West
Side.
</P>
<P>
	   Also weighing in for Camden was Andrew Cuomo, secretary of Housing and Urban
Development, who said a floating battleship museum would support federal efforts
to make the city an economic empowerment zone.
</P>
<P>
	   Closely divided, New Jersey's battleship commission voted in 1998 to berth
the warship in Bayonne. But several members supporting Bayonne did so with the
caveat that the ship should move to Liberty State Park in Jersey City if it is
ever renovated to accommodate such a huge vessel.
</P>
<P>
	   Jersey City officials subsequently agreed not to compete with Bayonne before
the Navy's ship-donation program. But Camden did file its own application.
</P>
<P>
	   Economics, not just pride, was at issue. Bayonne and Camden are both aging
cities that would welcome the boost of tourism dollars. Also, since the federal
government cannot subsidize a donated warship, a failed museum in either
location could force taxpayers to cover its expense.
</P>
<P>
	   Gov. Christie Whitman originally said she would abide by the advice of the
commission. But then she proclaimed herself neutral, pledging $6 million in
state money to restore the ship to museum readiness, wherever it ended up.
</P>
<P>
	   On Thursday Whitman said her administration is committed to help prepare the
ship for the public's enjoyment.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think she's going to do just fine in Camden," Whitman said. "She would
have done well in Bayonne; she'll do just fine in Camden."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-20-00 1708 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000120.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Camden To Be Ship's Retirement Home  </HEADLINE>
   By LAURENCE ARNOLD Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The hulking battleship USS New Jersey, a decorated
veteran of four wars, will spend its retirement just across the Delaware River
from the shipyard where it was built under the dark cloud of World War II.
