<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Connecticut braces for a less-than-wicked winter- so far  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - A green December and a sunny start to the new
year has some New Englanders shuddering at the late arrival of snow and subzero
temperatures.
<P>
	   "I think that people have all kinds of anxieties and the weather is a real
handy one," said Sarah Gamble, a South Windsor psychotherapist.
</P>
<P>
	   A forecast for flurries should be no shock in mid-January, but such
predictions are sending shivers down Connecticut's spine.
</P>
<P>
	   "Other states like Alaska where they get a lot of snow could laugh at us,"
said Gamble. "People in Connecticut are used to their lives being on a schedule
and being in control and this is real threat to that. I guess if we were good
Yankees, we'd all be stoic about this."
</P>
<P>
	   So far, it's been a weak winter, with snow waiting until last week to fall,
but that isn't stalling sales of snow supplies, school cancellations and overall
weather woes.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's a dry winter in terms of storms and a mild winter in terms of
temperatures," said Xiusheng Yang, an associate professor of meteorology at the
University of Connecticut. "We had about 300 days without snow. That's actually
a record for Connecticut."
</P>
<P>
	   As of late Thursday afternoon, 1 3/4 inches of snow had fallen in Waterbury;
about 1 1/4 inches in Milford, New Milford, North Canaan and Danbury; and less
than an inch had accumulated in most parts of the state, said Bill Simpson, a
meteorologist with the National Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
	   During an average year, Connecticut would get about 4 inches of snow per
week beginning in December and about 4 inches of rain per month, said Yang, the
acting state climatologist. This year, the first snow did not arrive until the
second week of January and there was only about 2 1/2 inches of rain in
December.
</P>
<P>
	   The past week's bitter cold aside, overall temperatures have been mild- so
far, said Yang. The average monthly temperature in December is 30 degrees, but
last month, the temperature averaged 34 degrees - 2 degrees above freezing.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think that television has become such an important factor in our lives
that when the big weatherman predicts these dire storms the viewer abandons his
usual common sense," said Al Primo, a Greenwich television consultant who
pioneered "Eyewitness News" for local TV.
</P>
<P>
	   Lynn Pilczak agreed.
</P>
<P>
	   "Sometimes I think they hype it up good," said Pilczak, who works in
downtown Hartford. Bundled in a hooded jacket and gloves, Pilczak stood alone
Thursday outside an Aetna building where several smokers usually congregate
around noon.
</P>
<P>
	   As of late Thursday afternoon, state highways remained relatively clear.
Plow trucks were out in full force as snow continued to fall, said Rick
DeMatties, storm monitor for state Department of Transportation.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think we're becoming a little complacent because of the mild winters,"
said DeMatties. "We do get some calls here asking 'Should I go out? Is it safe?
' "
</P>
<P>
	   Some airlines canceled flights to and from Bradley International Airport
Thursday because of weather conditions in destination cities, said Chris Failla,
assistant airport operations specialist.
</P>
<P>
	   "A lot of people do attempt to get out on an earlier flight" when a storm is
brewing, Failla said.
</P>
<P>
	   All it takes is a fierce forecast to get customers in the door at the
Franklin True Value hardware store, said owner Sal Ciciro.
</P>
<P>
	   "People panic for any little thing," said Ciciro. "Right now they're coming
in."
</P>
<P>
	   The good economy also fuel weather woes, said Primo, president of
Medium4.com. In what he called a "wimpy era" people have become "fat and happy,"
eager for an opportunity to stay cooped up.
</P>
<P>
	   For some business owners, the bad weather makes for better economy.
</P>
<P>
	   "Today is very busy," said Jose Sanchez, who delivered bundles of food to a
downtown office. "Everybody is cold, nobody wants to go out. But we've got to
keep going."
</P>
<P>
	   Outside his window, Primo could see people scurrying in and out of the Food
Mart to stock up on milk and other essentials should Mother Nature send them to
their rooms.
</P>
<P>
	   Several dozen public and parochial schools canceled or postponed classes
Thursday, particularly those located along the shoreline.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's been mild and that's wonderful, but this is New England and snow can
crop up at any time," said Tim Connors, superintendent of the Danbury public
schools. "It started to snow here at 7 a.m. ... Today we think it's a good
call."
</P>
<P>
	   Trumbull schools superintendent Ralph Iassogna also stood by his decision to
cancel school.
</P>
<P>
	   "You always have to make a decision that ensures the safety of the students
and staff coming in," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-20-00 1722 </TRAILER>
