<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trump, like McCain, facing ballot access problems in New York  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Like John McCain, Donald Trump faces possible
problems getting on New York's presidential primary ballot, officials said
Thursday.
<P>
	   And for a time, it appeared that even former Sen. Bill Bradley might face a
challenge over some of his primary petitions. That appeared to evaporate on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Unlike McCain or Bradley, Trump is not an announced candidate. Nonetheless,
the mega-developer is considering running for the Reform Party's presidential
nomination. In New York, the Reform Party goes by the name of the Independence
Party and some of its leaders are trying to get Trump convention delegate slates
on the state's March 7 presidential primary ballot.
</P>
<P>
	   But the effort has wound up in the middle of a battle for control of the New
York party.
</P>
<P>
	   The party's Democracy Coalition, led by leftist activist Lenora Fulani, has
filed challenges with the state Board of Elections to the petitions filed to get
Trump delegate slates on the ballot. The Fulani forces have also filed a state
court lawsuit. In a strange twist, Fulani is backing conservative Pat Buchanan's
run for the Reform Party's presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
	   Backing Trump is Jack Essenberg, who Fulani is battling to have removed as
state chairman of New York's Independence Party.
</P>
<P>
	   Cathy Stewart, the party's Manhattan chairman and a Fulani supporter, said
the Trump forces didn't file the necessary signatures of Independence Party
members to qualify for the primary ballot.
</P>
<P>
	   "They didn't comply with the petition requirements set out in
black-and-white in the election laws," coalition lawyer Gary Sinawski said.
</P>
<P>
	   To qualify for the primary ballot, candidates need the signatures of 5,000
party members statewide.
</P>
<P>
	   Trump campaign adviser Roger Stone said the legal requirements have been met
to get on the New York ballot. He would not say how many petition signatures had
been filed.
</P>
<P>
	   "The same taxes tactics that Mr. Bush is using against Mr. McCain, Miss
Fulani is trying to use on Mr. Trump," Stone said.
</P>
<P>
	   The McCain petitions for the GOP primary ballot have been challenged in New
York by supporters of Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
	   Trump did say Thursday he was worried about the infighting in the Reform
Party. "I am ... deeply concerned about growing divisions in the Reform Party,"
he said. "I strongly urge party leaders to sit down and negotiate their
differences out."
</P>
<P>
	   The state elections board could rule on petition objections early next week.
The lawsuits could last longer.
</P>
<P>
	   On the Democratic side, a slate of five prospective Bradley delegates in the
Bronx, including Nate "Tiny" Archibald, a Hall of Fame basketball player and
member of the Boston Celtics 1981 title team, had drawn a possible challenge
that seemed to evaporate Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   While general objections to the Bradley slate had been filed Jan. 12,
specific challenges had to be postmarked by midnight Tuesday. As of Thursday,
the state board had not received those. Without specific objections, the
challenge is thrown out.
</P>
<P>
	   Democratic sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said that while the
Al Gore campaign had vowed not to challenge Bradley's petitions, the general
objections had been filed by one of the vice president's top New York
supporters, Bronx Democratic Chairman Roberto Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
	   But on Thursday, Ramirez said: "From everything I know, Mr. Bradley's
petitions are not being challenged."
</P>
<P>
	   "As a general rule, as certainly as long as I've been part of the process,
we've always taken a look at the petitions," the state assemblyman added.
</P>
<P>
	   Filing a general objection to the petitions is a way to preserve the right
to later go ahead with a full-blown challenge, Ramirez said.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're hopeful there will be no challenges," Bradley spokeswoman Julia
Rothwax said.
</P>
<P>
	   Most of New York's top Democrats have endorsed the vice president over the
former New York Knick. Gore's New York campaign said Thursday that it knew
nothing about the challenges.
</P>
<P>
	   In New York, McCain is battling challenges to his petitions in 17 of the
state's 31 congressional districts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-20-00 1752 </TRAILER>
