<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CDC: Rabid Raccoons To Spread  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- A two-decade spread of rabies in raccoons in the United
States has advanced into Canada, the government said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   The outbreak was detected in 1977 along the West Virginia-Virginia line. The
Appalachian Mountains and rivers helped block the rabid raccoons' westward
spread, but only for a few years, said Candace McCall, an epidemic tracker with
the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
	   Eight cases of rabid raccoons have been confirmed in Canada since July, the
CDC said.
</P>
<P>
	   Researchers estimate the rabies virus in raccoons is advancing 18 to 24
miles west and north annually.
</P>
<P>
	   Rabies can spread to other animals and to humans through bites or other
wounds and can be fatal. The CDC recommends that household pets be vaccinated
against the disease.
</P>
<P>
	   Raccoons have represented the largest percentage of animal rabies cases
since 1990. From 1990 to 1998, a total of 35,264 cases of raccoon rabies were
reported in the United States, with 99.3 percent of those occurring in Eastern
states.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
