<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Advocates say what mayor calls help can actually harm  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - As the number of homeless people in the city has risen
in recent months, the Giuliani administration has implemented a series of
policies to get people off streets and into treatment programs.
<P>
	   But despite the good intentions, homeless advocates say the mayor is doing
little more than driving additional people out on the street during the coldest
time of the year. The advocates' most recent ammunition: A sweep early Wednesday
in which police arrested at least 125 people seeking shelter from the
20-below-zero wind-chill.
</P>
<P>
	   Advocates and some politicians fear the raids - which occurred at 4 a.m. in
at least seven shelters citywide - will mean that at least some of the city's
22,586 people who seek shelter each night will simply avoid help in the future.
</P>
<P>
	   Already, at least two homeless people have died in the city from
overexposure during the recent cold snap.
</P>
<P>
	   "The administration seems to be giving homeless people an ultimatum: Freeze
or face jail," Manhattan Borough President C. Virginia Fields said Thursday.
"There will undoubtedly be some people who will be afraid to go to shelters and
will be in grave danger of freezing to death."
</P>
<P>
	   The Police Department has released few details about the Thursday morning
raid, but most of those arrested appear to have had outstanding bench warrants
for minor violations, including public urination.
</P>
<P>
	   "They can't be treated any differently than anybody else," Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani said.
</P>
<P>
	   "There's no immunity in the law that says if you are homeless, you then get
away with committing a crime."
</P>
<P>
	   He said police made the shelter arrests because the homeless people were
suspected of violating various laws, and further, that the arrests will help
make shelters safer.
</P>
<P>
	   "Here's the reality the advocates have to face: 'There are some homeless
people that are criminals. Not all. Not most. Not a majority," said Giuliani. "I
can't ignore that. I'm the mayor of the city. I can't ignore the fact that among
homeless people are some dangerous criminals and some, not so dangerous, but
still criminals."
</P>
<P>
	   Advocates however, say they are particularly concerned by the raids because
they come after two other highly publicized initiatives: A city plan to deny
shelter to able-bodied, mentally stable homeless people who refuse to work; and
a crackdown that rounded people up off the street, and led to the arrests of
those who were uncooperative.
</P>
<P>
	   The work-for-shelter requirement - which is being held up in court - has a
provision that allows the city to take children away from parents who refuse to
comply with the rules. A judge would have to approve the removal of any children
from families.
</P>
<P>
	   Giuliani has more recently sought to explain his initiatives as
"compassionate" and "loving."
</P>
<P>
	   Advocates however, say that without adequate housing and drug treatment
programs, the policies are cruel.
</P>
<P>
	   They also note that the number of homeless people being placed in permanent
housing is down.
</P>
<P>
	   In the 1990s, the city and state funded an initiative which built 5,000
units of housing for low income city residents. A subsequent agreement however,
calls for building only 1,500 units over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
	   After several years of declining homelessness, advocates say the number of
needy is back on the rise.
</P>
<P>
	   The middle-of-the-night raid to arrest minor offenders, say advocates, only
makes matters worse.
</P>
<P>
	   "It is part of a series of very punitive policies on the part of the
Giuliani administration," said Patrick Markee, senior policy analyst for the
Coalition for the Homeless.
</P>
<P>
	   Giuliani however, said quality-of-life offenses cannot be ignored.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-20-00 1804 </TRAILER>
