<DOCNO> APW20000120.0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> University considering installing sprinklers after fatal fire  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   SOUTH ORANGE, N.J. (AP) - Seton Hall University is considering "anything
and everything" to improve fire safety following a fatal dormitory fire,
including the installation of sprinklers at all dorms, a spokeswoman said
Thursday.
<P>
	   The school will consider "anything that we can all do to make sure that
something like this never, ever happens again," spokeswoman Lisa Grider said.
</P>
<P>
	   When asked if the university would look into installing sprinklers in
six-story Boland Hall, she said, "Absolutely."
</P>
<P>
	   Gov. Christie Whitman also said Thursday she would consider legislation
requiring sprinkler systems in college dorms. " I don't think you could put a
price tag on human life," she said.
</P>
<P>
	   Three students were killed and 62 injured, six critically, in Wednesday's
blaze in a third-floor lounge at Boland Hall. Only the six patients remained
hospitalized Thursday, four still in critical condition.
</P>
<P>
	   Essex County Prosecutor Donald Campolo refuted a report Thursday in The
Star-Ledger of Newark that investigators had eliminated careless smoking and
electrical problems as possible causes.
</P>
<P>
	   "We are ruling out nothing at this juncture," Campolo said. He said
investigators were conducting a lengthy probe that includes interviews with at
least everyone hospitalized by the fire.
</P>
<P>
	   The Star-Ledger report also said that investigators were seeking three young
men whom a resident adviser had asked to leave the building less than an hour
before the fire broke out. Campolo declined to comment on the story.
</P>
<P>
	   Students at the Roman Catholic university continued to question how well the
university is prepared for fire, including its handling of the chronic string of
false alarms that have plagued Boland Hall.
</P>
<P>
	   "When I first heard the alarm, I thought 'I'm not leaving,"' said Marissa
Lorenz, an 18-year-old Scotch Plains resident who was released from the hospital
on Thursday. "I mean, there are so many alarms."
</P>
<P>
	   Omar Soriano, a 1997 Seton Hall alumnus, said Thursday that 25 false fire
alarms rang in Boland during one semester in 1994, when he was a resident
assistant.
</P>
<P>
	   Eighteen alarms have rung at Boland since September 1999. Grider said on
Thursday that in one of those cases, a fire was found in a Dumpster near the
dormitory. The others were false.
</P>
<P>
	   "A lot of people don't leave. They hide in closets, hide in bathrooms," said
university freshman Beth McCullough, 18, of Bloomsburg, Pa.
</P>
<P>
	   McCullough and Nathan Umbriac, another freshman, said they have not had to
undergo fire drills at the Aquinas Hall dormitory and that they didn't recall
resident assistants preparing them for a fire or warning them against pulling
alarms as a prank.
</P>
<P>
	   "If that was our hall, I'm just wondering if everybody would have been
prepared," said Umbriac, 18, from Danville, Pa.
</P>
<P>
	   The university released a page from its student manual on Thursday which
tells students what to do if a fire alarm goes off and warns that students can
be expelled for setting a false alarm.
</P>
<P>
	   Several students said that sprinklers should be installed in all of Seton
Hall's six dormitories. Two of the dormitories, Boland Hall and Aquinas Hall,
don't have installed sprinkler systems because they were built before such
systems were required by law. The dormitories are the only two that house
freshmen.
</P>
<P>
	   A rare fire alarm rang Thursday morning at Xavier Hall, evacuating nearly
200 students from the upperclassmen dorm. Grider said she didn't know the cause
of the alarm.
</P>
<P>
	   "I got up real quick for this one," said Guerschom Nazaire, 20, a junior
from Jersey City.
</P>
<P>
	   Many of the university's 10,000 students left campus following the fire.
Only two spent the night in a recreation center where makeshift beds were
created, Grider said. Many stayed with upperclassmen or went home.
</P>
<P>
	   About 150 sought grief counseling, Grider said, and others spent the day
quietly talking to friends, staying in their dorms.
</P>
<P>
	   "It affects the whole campus," said Nazaire. "The school is so small, so
everybody feels a little more connected."
</P>
<P>
	   The university suspended its guest pass policy for all university
residences. The guest policy was toughened last semester for security reasons,
Grider said. She didn't elaborate, but several students said there were problems
last year when fights between off and on-campus residents escalated.
</P>
<P>
	   The school canceled its weekend basketball games and extended its break from
classes until Monday, which president Monsignor Robert Sheeran said would be a
"university-wide day of mourning" for the victims: Frank S. Caltabilota of West
Long Branch, John N. Giunta of Vineland and Aaron C. Karol of Green Brook. All
were 18-year-old freshmen.
</P>
<P>
	   Sheeran said on Thursday that he and Newark Archbishop Theodore McCarrick
had walked through the third floor of Boland Hall on Wednesday and knelt by each
of the three bodies.
</P>
<P>
	   "We prayed over each of them, and we blessed them," Sheeran said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
