<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Restoring Jersey side of Ellis Island to cost $300 million  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - It will cost some $300 million to restore the
abandoned, 30-building complex on the New Jersey side of Ellis Island to a
useful purpose.
<P>
	   Fundraisers, start your engines.
</P>
<P>
	   A blue-ribbon panel headed by one of the Republican Party's top political
donors gave Gov. Christie Whitman its report on Thursday hoping to trigger a
decade of fund raising and construction projects.
</P>
<P>
	   Committee chairman Finn Casperson said for all the ambitious proposals,
including development of a commercial conference center, the immediate priority
was to keep the half-century old buildings from falling down.
</P>
<P>
	   "Ellis Island is a symbol of the neglect of our nation's historic
buildings," Casperson said. "Time is of the essence. The buildings are falling
apart.... We cannot put it off for another decade."
</P>
<P>
	   Whitman greeted the report by announcing she would include $1 million in the
upcoming budget to help save the largest building in the complex, the Baggage
and Dormitory Building. The state currently has put $2.3 million into saving the
island's main hospital, and a $2.2 million project is underway to save the ferry
building.
</P>
<P>
	   New Jersey officials became interested in developing Ellis Island after the
U.S. Supreme Court ruled in 1998 that most of the land lies in New Jersey.
Whitman appointed Casperson's panel to recommend how to proceed.
</P>
<P>
	   Ellis Island's main attraction, the Immigrant Museum with its Great Hall, is
on New York soil and has been open to the public since 1990. It was the
processing center for millions of immigrants from 1892 to 1954.
</P>
<P>
	   But the Supreme Court said the larger, southern half of the island, which
holds a complex of former hospital and quarantine buildings, was in New Jersey
jurisdiction. That part remains off limits.
</P>
<P>
	   The National Park Service actually owns and controls the property and has
proceeded on its own, retaining a consultant, The Sedway Group, to study the
best use of the abandoned complex of buildings.
</P>
<P>
	   Casperson's Advisory Committee on the Preservation and Use of Ellis Island
largely endorsed the findings reported in October by the Sedway Group, which
recommended saving all the buildings and renovating their interiors for use as a
commercial conference center and a public-health museum.
</P>
<P>
	   The committee Thursday also proposed using some buildings to house a center
for historic restoration, a place where preservationists could do research and
could educate other historians.
</P>
<P>
	   "The significance of Ellis Island and its peril is widely recognized," the
report said.
</P>
<P>
	   The committee said it would be too expensive to restore the building
interiors to their 1950s conditions, but the facades would be preserved as the
interiors are renovated for modern use.
</P>
<P>
	   Ambitious plans aside, Casperson and the committee said the immediate
priority was to make sure there are structures left standing to work with. Many
of the buildings are structurally unsafe, choked with plants and lacking basic
security steps as plywood to board up windows.
</P>
<P>
	   Casperson said these initial steps would cost $6.6 million just to make sure
there are buildings left intact to be preserved in future fundraising efforts.
</P>
<P>
	   Plans for a so-called "Ellis Island Institute" would include a policy
retreat with up to 100 lodging rooms, a center for immigration and ethnic
studies and a living history memorial. Officials hope to count it as a revenue
source to fund other work.
</P>
<P>
	   The Center for Immigrant Contributions and Ethnic Learning would include
multimedia exhibits on living conditions of immigrants throughout the world, and
a 100-to 200-seat theater for lectures, film festivals and performing arts.
</P>
<P>
	   The Living History Memorial would preserve selected rooms in the former
medical complex to recall the public health history of the island, according to
the proposal by The Sedway Group.
</P>
<P>
	   Sen. Edward O'Connor, D-Hudson, a committee member, said the conference
center "could have an enormously positive impact on the Hudson County economy
and on New Jersey's reputation as an international and national leader."
</P>
<P>
	   The report also endorsed a National Park Service finding that the island
would require improved access, including a permanent pedestrian bridge linking
it to Liberty State Park. Currently, visitors to Ellis Island must buy a ticket
for a ferry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-20-00 1816 </TRAILER>
