<HEADLINE> Fat-Trimming Activists Rip McCain  </HEADLINE>
   By KATHERINE RIZZO Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A pig rolls a barrel of dollars across Sen. John McCain's
Web site to illustrate his devotion to cutting pork-barrel spending. Rep. John
Kasich uses an icon of a ``wastebusters'' ghost to make the same point on the
site for the House Budget Committee he chairs.
</P>
<P>
	   But those foes of government waste did not always back up their tough talk
when it came to voting on trimming fat, some of their activist allies complained
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain, the Arizona senator who is seeking the GOP presidential nomination,
and Kasich, R-Ohio, were given only average voting scores in ``Green Scissors
2000,'' a report by three groups that identified 77 proposals and programs the
organizations deemed wasteful and environmentally unfriendly. All the items went
before Congress last year.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain was aggressive on a fight against sugar subsidies, but faded on other
issues and missed some key votes, Cuff said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``McCain talks the talk, but when it comes time for leadership, he walks,''
said Courtney Cuff of Friends of the Earth.
</P>
<P>
	   ``John Kasich, who a few years ago was our champion on this stuff, didn't go
down there and sponsor one amendment,'' she said. She worked closely with Kasich
on several earlier battles to abolish business subsidies, but complained that
last year he hid behind ``let's cut a small percentage across the board.''
</P>
<P>
	   Friends of the Earth, Taxpayers for Common Sense and the U.S. Public
Interest research Group produced the report, which tracked the votes of all the
members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
	   Aides to Kasich and McCain said the criticism was unfounded.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain spokeswoman Nancy Ives said for 17 years he has ``fought against
pork-barrel spending items in every appropriations bill,''
</P>
<P>
	   ``He has been front and center in Congress in cutting wasteful spending and
returning that money to the taxpayers of America,'' she said. That effort
includes compiling an itemized list of every non-requested, low-priority item in
each appropriations bill.
</P>
<P>
	   Kasich is preparing for a Feb. 2 hearing on wasteful government spending,
spokesman Bruce Cuthbertson said, and ``has been involved in virtual
hand-to-hand combat over corporate welfare for more years than anyone I know
of.''
</P>
<P>
	   Jill Lancelot, legislative director of Taxpayers for Common Sense, said she
was disappointed in the amount of time devoted to subsidy-fighting last year by
McCain and Kasich, both of whom were balancing congressional duties with
presidential campaigns. Kasich subsequently dropped out.
</P>
<P>
	   The Green Scissors report praised the work of Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., and
GOP Reps. Tom Campbell of California and Christopher Shays of Connecticut. They
voted against each of the issues identified by the groups and took the lead on
cutting items identified in a previous Green Scissors report.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   The congressional vote tally can be viewed at www.foeaction.org/tally99.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-20-00 1837 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000120.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First snowstorm brings only a few inches but lots of travel woes  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - As snowstorms go, the first this winter didn't pack
much fury, but Thursday's snow and bitter cold were more than enough to leave
roads icy, causing scores of fender-benders and a few more serious accidents.
<P>
	   Parts of two major highways were closed by wrecks, the New Jersey Turnpike
lowered speed limits, and state police urged residents to stay off roads.
</P>
<P>
	   "Driving is extremely treacherous," said New Jersey State Police spokesman
John Hagerty. "Limit driving unless you absolutely have to be out on the
highways."
</P>
<P>
	   The National Weather Service issued a winter weather advisory for the state,
predicting gusty winds, overnight wind chills as numbing as 20 degrees below
zero and 2 to 6 inches of snow, with the southern and eastern parts of the state
getting the most. It also warned that minor coastal flooding was possible during
Thursday evening's high tides as increasing winds pushed water onshore.
</P>
<P>
	   But by mid-afternoon, only a half-inch to 2 inches of snow had fallen on
northeastern New Jersey, and major roads remained clear in west and central New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
	   "I don't think the roads are that bad," said Cheryl McGuigan, 42, an
assistant mailroom supervisor for the state who lives in Trenton. "The sidewalks
are slippery," though, and she nearly fell while walking outside at lunchtime.
</P>
<P>
	   Lois Vereen, 34, a state Pensions Department employee, said the morning bus
she takes to work from north Trenton was delayed about 30 minutes, but the
weather wasn't bothering her.
</P>
<P>
	   "I expected worse than this," she said.
</P>
<P>
	   The turnpike cut its speed limit to 45 mph and banned motorcycles and
car-pulled trailers. NJ Transit spokesman Ken Miller, though, said its trains
and buses were running "fairly close to schedule."
</P>
<P>
	   Newark International Airport, as well as LaGuardia and Kennedy International
airports in New York, were reporting scattered 90-minute delays on flights and
some cancellations. Most of the trouble was caused by bad weather in other parts
of the country, including Washington, D.C., and Chicago, said Bill Cahill, a
spokesman for the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
	   Some businesses closed early, and at least 120 public schools were closed or
sent students home early. McGuire Air Force Base sent its approximately 1,000
civilian personnel, except those considered "weather essential," home at 2 p.m.
and gave commanders of the base's 5,000 active duty military personnel the
option to do the same.
</P>
<P>
	   The Meadowlands Racetrack canceled live racing Thursday because of the
weather.
</P>
<P>
	   The state government, though, didn't send its workers home early or open its
snow emergency center.
</P>
<P>
	   The Jan. 20 storm was the third-latest in central New Jersey with at least
1/10 inch of snow in the last 105 years, according to state climatologist Dave
Robinson.
</P>
<P>
	   "There were 13 years when the first snowfall didn't come till January," he
noted.
</P>
<P>
	   The latest snowfall recorded at New Brunswick was Jan. 31, 1921. Robinson
said the storm was far enough east that it would dump most of its snow onto the
ocean, and the storm could sap some of the energy from one expected Sunday.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's going to be another brutally cold day tomorrow," he added.
</P>
<P>
	   In Mercer County, huge stretches of the Delaware River glistened white
through a light fog as snow accumulated atop large sheets of ice.
</P>
<P>
	   It wasn't so pretty elsewhere, though.
</P>
<P>
	   Hagerty, the state police spokesman, said there were countless
"slip-and-slide accidents" on the state's major highways, including Routes 78,
80 and 278. Route 195 had more than 30 accidents during the morning rush hour
and on the stretch of Route 295 from Trenton to Bellmawr in Camden County, there
were about 40 morning wrecks.
</P>
<P>
	   On the Garden State Parkway in Lakewood, a tanker truck carrying fuel
overturned about 6 a.m., injuring the driver and spilling several hundred
gallons of fuel. An eight-mile stretch between exits 91 and 83 was closed into
the evening.
</P>
<P>
	   On the turnpike, a truck slid off the roadway in East Brunswick shortly
after 10 a.m., shutting down traffic in the southbound truck lanes.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, icy roads may have caused an incident on the Atlantic City
Expressway in Winslow Township. About 8 a.m., 12 cars on both the eastbound and
westbound sides lost control and ended up on the median and the westbound
shoulder, according to Peter Hartt, a spokesman for the South Jersey
Transportation Authority, which operates the 44-mile toll road.
</P>
<P>
	   "I wouldn't call it a pileup," he said. "I'd call it a scatter."
</P>
<P>
	   The island community of Brigantine had its only access road cut off for 2
1/2 hours Thursday after a weather-related fender-bender, police said. The
accident on the Brigantine Bridge - which links Brigantine with Atlantic City -
occurred about 12 noon and the span was closed until 2:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
	   Department of Transportation crews hit major roads as early as 5 a.m.
Thursday, spreading salt and monitoring road conditions, according to department
spokesman Jim Berzok. Once snow began to accumulate, about 565 workers operating
463 pieces of equipment - mostly snowplows - began clearing roads.
</P>
<P>
	   Berzok said the biggest problems likely would come at night, when a dramatic
temperature drop was expected to add to icing on roadways. He said the
department probably would keep some road crews on into the evening, after the
anticipated end of the snowfall around 7 p.m., and some crews might continue
salting and sanding roads overnight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-20-00 1839 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000120.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seton Hall students released from hospital share stories of fire  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   LIVINGSTON, N.J. (AP) - Seven of 13 freshmen students injured in a fatal
fire at a Seton Hall University dormitory and hospitalized at Saint Barnabas
Medical Center were released on Thursday.
<P>
	   The seven students, who all lived on the third floor of Boland Hall,
suffered from smoke inhalation. An eighth student, also suffering from smoke
inhalation, was released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Five others who remained hospitalized were Nick Donato, of Sparta, and Ben
Chibnik, both 19; and Thomas Pugilese, Alvaro Llanos, and Ken Simons, all 18.
Three were listed in critical condition in the intensive care unit suffering
from burns and smoke inhalation, one in the intensive care unit in serious but
stable condition, and one in stable condition, according to a hospital
spokeswoman. Their hometowns were not released.
</P>
<P>
	   The most seriously injured student suffered burns to more than half his
body, said Dr. Sylvia Petrone, associate director of Saint Barnabas Medical
Center's burn unit.
</P>
<P>
	   "For an 18-year-old with a 60 percent burn injury, there's a good chance of
survival, but it is a life-threatening injury," Petrone said.
</P>
<P>
	   At University Hospital in Newark, Dana Christmas, a 21-year-old resident
adviser with burns on 58 percent of her body, had her first surgery Thursday to
graft skin onto her back and hands. She will need between three and five
surgeries and is still is at serious risk of infection in her lungs and skin,
said her surgeon, Edwin Deitch.
</P>
<P>
	   Students released from the hospital shared tales of panic and despair as
they managed to find their way out of the third-floor dorm which quickly filled
with smoke and flames.
</P>
<P>
	   "I opened the door and there were flames," said Alyssa Merla, 18, of West
Long Branch. "(My roommate and I) started saying Our Father because I thought we
were gonna die."
</P>
<P>
	   Merla said calling 911 was difficult because students must enter a code to
dial out. The two eventually escaped through a suitemate's door.
</P>
<P>
	   Marissa Lorenz, 18, of Scotch Plains, said she was in her room with Justin
Fox, 18, of Paramus, along with two roommates, who had slept through the alarm.
</P>
<P>
	   "When I first heard the alarm, I thought, 'I'm not leaving.' I mean, there
are so many alarms," said Lorenz.
</P>
<P>
	   In the first semester alone, there were 18 alarms in Boland Hall, according
to a campus spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
	   Merla noted students last semester eventually ignored false alarms.
</P>
<P>
	   "During our final exams, between 1 a.m. and 6 a.m., there were three
alarms," Merla. "I called my Mom and said 'Do you hear this?' I went into my
closet to sleep because I didn't want to leave."
</P>
<P>
	   Lorenz and Fox said they then heard screams just outside their door.
</P>
<P>
	   "I took my sweater off and put it in my mouth and went to the door, and the
handle was already hot," said Fox.
</P>
<P>
	   "We pulled this kid into out room and shut the door," said Lorenz. "We
didn't know who he was, I mean, this boy was unrecognizable."
</P>
<P>
	   Lorenz said she tried to calm the student, and asked him to nod if he could
hear her, but he would only cling to her leg.
</P>
<P>
	   "The hair on his legs were singed. He was charred. His hands were black and
his whole face was charred black," said Fox. "He told us his name, but we don't
remember. There was so much commotion."
</P>
<P>
	   The students said they were not told what happened to the student after they
pulled him into their room and firefighters rescued him.
</P>
<P>
	   Romil Sumilang, 18, of Teaneck, said he crawled into the smoke-filled
hallway with his roommate and couldn't find a way out.
</P>
<P>
	   "I lost my roommate in the dark, and then I heard a voice in the stairwell
saying. 'If you can hear me, come to my voice!"
</P>
<P>
	   Sumilang escaped, but said heard a female student yelling for help, so he
went back inside the burning dorm and dragged her to safety.
</P>
<P>
	   Killed in the fire were 18-year-old freshmen Frank S. Caltabilota of West
Long Branch, John N. Giunta of Vineland and Aaron C. Karol of Green Brook. Two
were found in the lounge and the third was found in a nearby bedroom, said Essex
County Prosecutor Donald Campolo.
</P>
<P>
	   Candy Karol, Aaron's mother, said a viewing will be held Friday and Saturday
at Higgins Funeral Home in Watchung. The funeral will be held on Monday at St.
John's Church in Dunellan.
</P>
<P>
	   Ms. Karol said the family plans to establish a scholarship fund at Watchung
Hills High School, where Aaron graduated with honors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
