<HEADLINE> Indictment returned against top Wall Street executive and porn  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - An X-rated movie star and a top Wall Street executive
were indicted Thursday on insider trading charges.
<P>
	   James McDermott Jr., the former CEO at Keefe, Bruyette &AMP; Woods, was named in
the indictment along with Kathryn Gannon, 30, known as "Marylin Star" in the
adult film industry.
</P>
<P>
	   A third defendant, Anthony P. Pomponio, was also charged. McDermott, 48, of
Briarcliff Manor and Pomponio, 45, of North Caldwell, N.J., already have been
arrested and freed on bail. Ms. Gannon, 30, of Miami, Fla., remains a fugitive,
apparently living in Canada.
</P>
<P>
	   The New York investment bank chief was accused of tipping Ms. Gannon about
companies on the verge of mergers that would dramatically affect their stock
prices. Ms. Gannon then allegedly bought the stocks and shared the information
with Pomponio, a friend who also allegedly cashed in.
</P>
<P>
	   According to court papers, McDermott, 48, who is married, was intimately
involved with Ms. Gannon while the insider trading was going on.
</P>
<P>
	   Pomponio allegedly told investigators that Ms. Gannon not only worked in
adult films but also was a prostitute, with New York City clients including
"well connected Wall Street types" such as lawyers and stockbrokers.
</P>
<P>
	   The indictment accused McDermott of stealing confidential, non-public
information from his company and its clients and feeding the information about
six potential or actual mergers to Ms. Gannon, who then told Pomponio.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors allege the trio made more than $170,000 in illegal profits.
</P>
<P>
	   Keefe, Bruyette &AMP; Woods had been scheduled to go public with a stock
offering last spring but withdrew the plans suddenly in May. According to court
papers, the offering was canceled after McDermott told the company's directors
that a friend of his - apparently Ms. Gannon - was being investigated by the
Securities and Exchange Commission for trading in stocks he had recommended to
her.
</P>
<P>
	   McDermott, Ms. Gannon and Pomponio were each charged by U.S. Attorney Mary
Jo White with conspiracy to commit securities fraud and securities fraud.
Pomponio also was charged with perjury. A separate civil complaint was brought
by the Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
	   McDermott resigned from the bank in June. He remains free on $1 million bail
while Pomponio is free on $50,000 bail. Both have declined to comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
