<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dorm adviser tells of returning three times to burning floor  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   SOUTH ORANGE, N.J. (AP) - Twice, Daniel Nugent led disoriented students
through the smoke that was choking their dormitory to safety. Then he went back
again.
<P>
	   By then, "flames were wrapping around the door" to the third floor, the
floor where Nugent, a sophomore at Seton Hall University, was resident assistant
to freshmen.
</P>
<P>
	   The door was too hot to open. Retreating to the lobby of Boland Hall, Nugent
learned "there were people trapped in their rooms and screaming to get out their
windows," he recalled Thursday evening, some 36 hours after the fire killed
three of his charges.
</P>
<P>
	   A neighbor provided a ladder that Nugent and a fellow resident assistant
used to reach a third-floor window.
</P>
<P>
	   "We got the girls out first because they were really scared," said Nugent,
21, of Northfield in Atlantic County.
</P>
<P>
	   "We went to another window to help other kids. A badly burned kid had been
pulled into one room. I stayed in this room while other RAs took the ladder to
help more residents," Nugent recounted at a news conference, as his parents,
Kathy and Bill, stood by.
</P>
<P>
	   "I stayed with the injured resident. The kid who pulled him out of the fire
is a real hero - he would not leave the room until he knew that the injured
student was all right. I wet towels and put them on the kid's burned skin,"
Nugent said.
</P>
<P>
	   Nugent remained until firefighters came through the window and took the
injured student to safety, then directed firefighters to other rooms before
finally leaving the building, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The young man declined to answer any questions from reporters, asking to be
"left alone to deal with the deaths of my friends and residents."
</P>
<P>
	   "I want people to know that there were so many others - students and staff
members alike - who risked their lives to save other people," Nugent said.
</P>
<P>
	   The horror began when he was awoken by fire alarms about 4:30 a.m. on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   "When I opened my door, I saw smoke in the hallway. I walked into the hall
with my cordless phone and turned the corner to see the fire in the lounge. I
called security to confirm that there was a fire, and started banging on my
residents' doors," Nugent said.
</P>
<P>
	   "Freshmen students living on the floor came out to help me - walking under
the smoke to get through the hallways. We were all banging on doors until they
had to leave for their own safety," he said. But Nugent remained.
</P>
<P>
	   "I found one student in bad shape and grabbed her arms to help her to her
feet, down the stairs and to the lobby where Seton Hall Health Services were
waiting," Nugent said.
</P>
<P>
	   "I went back up to the third floor a second time - this time the smoke was
down so far I had to crawl," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   "I found more residents who did not know where they were going and were
walking in the smoke," Nugent said. "I told them to crawl - as I was taught in
training - and I yelled at them to use the stairs away from the fire."
</P>
<P>
	   After leading them to safety, Nugent returned to his floor via the ladder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
