<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Camden To Be Ship's Retirement Home  </HEADLINE>
   By LAURENCE ARNOLD Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The hulking battleship USS New Jersey, a decorated
veteran of four military conflicts, will spend its retirement just across the
Delaware River from the shipyard where it was built under the dark cloud of
World War II.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. Navy Secretary Richard Danzig notified members of Congress Thursday
that he has approved a plan to turn the ship into a floating museum off Camden,
N.J., near the former Philadelphia Naval Shipyard.
</P>
<P>
	   In choosing Camden, the Navy rejected the advice of a New Jersey state
commission that recommended putting the ship off Bayonne in northern New Jersey,
across the harbor from New York City.
</P>
<P>
	   Launched in 1942, the battleship New Jersey employed its immense guns in
World War II, Korea, Vietnam and off the coast of Lebanon in 1983. It is one of
four Iowa-class battleships, the biggest ever constructed.
</P>
<P>
	   Bayonne and Camden both advanced detailed arguments about why they would
they would be the best place for a floating museum.
</P>
<P>
	   Bayonne boosters cited the city's proximity to New York and other population
centers of northern New Jersey. The case for Camden included the ship's ties to
the Philadelphia shipyard and the idea that the Delaware River's freshwater
would be kinder to the ship's massive hull.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This will be a great thing for the area, a great thing for the area's
veterans and a great thing for Camden,'' said Rep. Jim Saxton, R-N.J., who
helped lead the Camden push.
</P>
<P>
	   Saxton and Rep. Rob Andrews, D-N.J., said Camden proved the more
economically viable location, in part because Bayonne would have had to compete
against an existing floating military museum, the aircraft carrier USS Intrepid,
located across New York Harbor.
</P>
<P>
	   But Rep. Bob Menendez, D-N.J., whose district includes Bayonne, accused the
Navy of caring more for ``the votes of the (House) Armed Services Committee''
than for the ship's future. Saxton and Andrews sit on that committee.
</P>
<P>
	   New Jersey Assemblyman Joe Azzolina, chairman of the state battleship
commission, promised to implement the Navy's decision even though it went
against his long-held belief that the ship should go to the former Military
Ocean Terminal in Bayonne.
</P>
<P>
	   The battleship currently sits at the former Philadelphia Naval Shipyard, now
officially called the Philadelphia Naval Business Center. It was towed there
from Bremerton, Wash., last year on a 5,800-mile trip that included its 10th and
final passage through the Panama Canal.
</P>
<P>
	   The battle for the battleship opened a long-standing political rift pitting
North Jersey against South Jersey.
</P>
<P>
	   Eight northern New Jersey congressman advocated Bayonne, while three
southern New Jersey congressman endorsed Camden.
</P>
<P>
	   South Jersey advocates also secured endorsements from congressmen
representing parts of Pennsylvania, Delaware and Maryland, as well as members of
New York's delegation who viewed a museum in Bayonne as potential competition
for the Intrepid.
</P>
<P>
	   Also weighing in for Camden was Andrew Cuomo, secretary of Housing and Urban
Development, who said a floating battleship museum would support federal efforts
to make the city an economic empowerment zone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-20-00 1856 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000120.0214 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Driver Evaluations Said Meaningless  </HEADLINE>
   By ALAN CLENDENNING Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Although bus and truck drivers must be medically
certified every two years, the system is useless because the exams are easy to
pass and there is virtually no government oversight, the chairman of the
National Transportation Safety Board said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   During a break from a hearing about a bus crash that killed 22 people in New
Orleans last Mother's Day, NTSB chairman James Hall said there is an ``absence
of any believable program'' for certifying commercial drivers.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Each and every day we are sharing our highways with drivers who are
unfit,'' Hall said.
</P>
<P>
	   Hall made the comments after transportation experts testified that
commercial drivers with serious health problems essentially shop around for
physicians who give easy medical exams. There was also testimony that doctors
are unaware of rules about driver health and that oversight by federal officials
is virtually nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
	   Such deficiencies were exposed last year in the New Orleans crash, when a
chartered bus carrying mostly elderly women on a day trip to a Mississippi
casino veered off Interstate 610 and overturned. Police said driver Frank
Bedell's use of marijuana hours earlier was the main cause.
</P>
<P>
	   Bedell, who died in August, held a commercial license even though he had a
history of failing bus company drug tests. That information was never passed on
to licensing officials because no federal rules required the disclosure.
</P>
<P>
	   NTSB investigators also found a doctor had diagnosed Bedell with congestive
heart failure in 1998 but still signed his medical certificate -- even though
federal law prohibits people with the disease from getting commercial drivers'
licenses.
</P>
<P>
	   Less than 12 hours before the crash, Bedell was treated in a hospital
emergency room for dehydration and extremely low blood pressure.
</P>
<P>
	   Doctors who perform the certification exams for bus drivers and truckers
never receive training on how commercial drivers should be assessed, and no one
monitors the doctors' performance, said Dr. Natalie Hartenbaum, a Philadelphia
physician who wrote a guide on medical certification for the federal Department
of Transportation.
</P>
<P>
	   ``To do a complete exam takes 20 minutes,'' she testified. ``Many of them do
it in five.''
</P>
<P>
	   The Federal Aviation Administration requires doctors to take a one-week
training course before they start giving medical exams to pilots.
</P>
<P>
	   All results are forwarded to the FAA for possible review. Also provided to
the FAA are results of drug and alcohol tests. Pilots who test positive are
grounded while they undergo treatment.
</P>
<P>
	   Hall said bus and truck drivers should be part of a similar system.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We already have a model at the federal level on how we can do a better
job,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-20-00 1857 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000120.0215 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawyer says his client is not cooperating with prosecutors  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - The lawyer for a Brooklyn man accused of helping an
Algerian try to smuggle explosives into the United States said Thursday his
client is not cooperating with authorities.
<P>
	   Roland Thau, the lawyer for Abdel Ghani Meskini in New York, said his client
had not spoken to law enforcement since Thau began representing him a few hours
after his arrest.
</P>
<P>
	   The attorney's comments came several hours after Meskini, 31, pleaded
innocent in U.S. District Court in Manhattan to charges of providing and
concealing support for Ahmed Ressam, an Algerian national accused of trying to
sneak explosives into the United States just before New Year's.
</P>
<P>
	   Another alleged accomplice, Mokhtar Haouari, 31, appeared in Superior Court
in Montreal Thursday morning for the start of court proceedings aimed at
bringing him to New York. He has been indicted on the same charges Meskini
faces.
</P>
<P>
	   Thau said prosecutors have told him Meskini made statements after police
arrested him Dec. 30 and it was possible that "cops coerced some kind of
statement from him."
</P>
<P>
	   But Thau said he hadn't seen any such evidence.
</P>
<P>
	   He said any statement made by his client most likely would have been to
declare his innocence or explain why he traveled to Seattle the week Ressam was
arrested in Port Angeles, Wash.
</P>
<P>
	   Ressam was arrested Dec. 14 on explosives smuggling charges after he
allegedly tried to smuggle RDX, a powerful demolition explosive, and timing
devices into Washington from Canada. The arrest increased fears of terrorism
planned to coincide with millennium celebrations, but no such attack
materialized.
</P>
<P>
	   In court papers, federal prosecutors allege Haouari asked Meskini to travel
to Seattle to meet Ressam.
</P>
<P>
	   The indictment against Haouari and Meskini accuses them of conspiring since
October 1997 to support members and associates of a terrorist group. Haouari
allegedly provided various forged identification documents while Meskini went to
Seattle to assist Ressam.
</P>
<P>
	   So far, court documents and statements by authorities have not indicated
exactly what the alleged terrorists had planned to do, or how many of them were
involved. Suspects in the case have been linked to the Armed Islamic Group,
known by its French acronym GIA.
</P>
<P>
	   According to documents filed in Montreal courts, Haouari said he fled to
Canada in 1993 because he was wanted by military police in Algeria over his
involvement with the fundamentalist Islamic Salvation Front. He said he left the
group in 1992 because "it is against my principals and religion to use any form
of violence."
</P>
<P>
	   In denying bail in Montreal Thursday, Judge Jean-Guy Boilard ruled that
evidence indicated Haouari was a member of an Algerian terrorist group and was
involved with Ressam in a plot to bring explosives into the United States.
</P>
<P>
	   The United States "seems to have credible proof implicating the accused,"
the judge said.
</P>
<P>
	   "The proof that has been revealed satisfies me that he belongs to a
terrorist organization."
</P>
<P>
	   The judge also said Haouari posed a flight risk, given his history of using
false documents and credit card fraud.
</P>
</TEXT>
