<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Safir adds pilot program to DWI seizure policy  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - In hopes of strengthening its legal case to continue
seizing the cars of drunken drivers, the NYPD has launched a pilot program that
would allow some people to get their cars back after completing an alcohol
treatment program and paying a fine.
<P>
	   The so-called settlement program, launched in late November, was announced
by Police Commissioner Howard Safir on Thursday during testimony before the City
Council's public safety committee about the NYPD's policy of seizing cars of
drunken drivers who are arrested. The policy went into effect in February 1999
and was enacted to prevent DWI-related accidents.
</P>
<P>
	   The seizure policy was roundly criticized by civil liberties advocates who
thought it too harsh to seize someone's car before they were convicted of a
crime. Under the law, the accused driver cannot get his car back unless he's
acquitted, and even then must go through a forfeiture proceeding.
</P>
<P>
	   The entire process can take nearly a year, lawyers have said.
</P>
<P>
	   Under the pilot program, there's a glimmer of hope for people to avoid the
court process. So is the NYPD softening its stance on DWI offenders? No, says
George Grasso, the department's deputy commissioner of legal matters.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're trying to modify behavior regarding alcohol abuse in order to reduce
DWI-related accidents, DWI-related injuries and fatalities, save lives and
prevent injuries," Grasso said.
</P>
<P>
	   Grasso also said the pilot program strengthens the NYPD's legal standing. So
far, the DWI seizure program has withstood a challenge in state court and the
appellate division, but is currently being reviewed by the Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
	   To qualify for the settlement program, a driver's blood alcohol level must
have been found to be lower than .20 - .10 is considered legally drunk. Also,
they must not have a significant prior history of driving while intoxicated or
impaired, or have been involved in a serious accident that resulted in injury or
property damage.
</P>
<P>
	   Individual cases are reviewed by the NYPD's civil enforcement unit.
</P>
<P>
	   So far, the department has reviewed 380 cases and deemed 100 eligible for
the pilot program, Grasso said. Letters have been sent to those 100 people
explaining the settlement program and so far, the department has heard from 41
recipients expressing interest, Grasso added.
</P>
<P>
	   It was not immediately known what percentage of DWI cases have been
reviewed.
</P>
<P>
	   But the settlement program has not eased the concerns of civil libertarians.
</P>
<P>
	   Michael Meyers, director of the New York Civil Rights Coalition, said the
pilot program is inconsistent.
</P>
<P>
	   "If people don't have a previous record of driving drunk, he's (the
commissioner) suggesting that this first instance is an indication of
alcoholism," Meyers said. "I certainly don't think it's up to the police
commissioner to become the moral monitor and to be the enforcer of such a law."
</P>
<P>
	   Norman Siegel, executive director of the New York Civil Liberties Union,
said the settlement program mitigates the harshness of the DWI seizure policy,
but fails to address the problems of people who are charged and later acquitted.
</P>
<P>
	   Siegel also complained that his client, Pavel Grinberg, was not told about
the settlement program.
</P>
<P>
	   "He fits every one of their tests," Siegel said. "He has no priors, he's
never been arrested for anything. He's a hardworking, conscientious guy."
</P>
<P>
	   It is Grinberg's case that's being considered by the Court of Appeals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
