<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain: Democracy's stronger in Russia than New York  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Still fuming over a state GOP effort to remove his name
from New York's presidential primary ballots, Sen. John McCain accused party
leaders Thursday of making New York less democratic than Russia.
<P>
	   McCain, who has chosen not to compete in Iowa's first-in-the-nation caucuses
on Monday, rode his campaign bus down Fifth Avenue in Manhattan while fellow
presidential hopefuls worked crowds in Des Moines and Ottumwa, Iowa.
</P>
<P>
	   The Arizona Republican pressed his fight to appear on ballots in New York's
March 7 primary, telling reporters outside the Russian consulate that voters in
Moscow and St. Petersburg would have a wider choice at the polls in March than
those in the Bronx and Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
	   "In Russia, there will be more than one name on the ballot" in the March 26
presidential election, McCain said. "In New York, unless something happens,
there will be only one name on the ballot. It seems to me that history has been
turned on its head."
</P>
<P>
	   In fact, both Texas Gov. George W. Bush and millionaire publisher Steve
Forbes are likely to appear on New York ballots, although others are skipping
the state altogether because of its notoriously stringent ballot requirements.
</P>
<P>
	   State Republican leaders have challenged McCain's petitions in 17 of New
York's 31 congressional districts, claiming he failed to obtain the required
number of signatures from party members. McCain is suing to get on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
	   Arizona state Sen. Scott Bundgaard accused McCain of hypocrisy, saying
McCain himself has used Arizona election laws to push his opponents off the
ballot.
</P>
<P>
	   "McCain went through the same process that the state party is going through
here," Bundgaard said. "If there is such a groundswell of support for John
McCain, then he should have no problems getting enough signatures."
</P>
<P>
	   In 1998, McCain challenged the petition signatures of a little known
opponent in the Republican primary for his Senate seat, forcing the opponent to
withdraw from the race. And in 1992, McCain mounted a similar challenge to
petitions filed by another Senate opponent, former Republican Gov. Evan Mecham.
McCain eventually dropped the challenge and handily defeated Mecham.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain said Bundgaard's accusations were untrue and that credible candidates
have never been removed from Arizona ballots.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain has hopped up and down the East Coast this week, raising campaign
cash from New York to Boston. He was scheduled to attend a closed fund-raiser
Thursday night at the Greenwich, Conn., home of HBO president John Billock.
</P>
<P>
	   Earlier Thursday, he talked campaign finance reform before a crowd of 900 at
the South Shore Chamber of Commerce in Randolph, Mass.
</P>
<P>
	   "The special interests have taken over: the trial lawyers, the labor union
bosses, the big corporations," said McCain, one of the Senate's most vehement
advocates of campaign finance reform. "This system is awash in big money that
deprives every one of you of your voice in Washington."
</P>
<P>
	   McCain said after his New York news conference that his attacks on politics
as usual are the reason party leaders oppose him in New York and around the
country. Republican leaders have lined up behind front-runner Bush in state
after state.
</P>
<P>
	   "Anybody who wants the status quo in Washington doesn't want me," McCain
said. "The establishment is threatened by my candidacy and I understand that,
and I respect them all."
</P>
<P>
	   He agreed on one point with Bush, who said Thursday that their campaigns'
public sniping over McCain's tax plan wouldn't weaken the two men's friendship.
</P>
<P>
	   "Of course we are friends," McCain said. "He's a fine man and you're not
going to hear anything negative from me about him. He's a very good man."
</P>
<P>
	   While competitors feverishly wooed Iowans, McCain had his sights set on New
Hampshire's Feb. 1 primary. And he says he's enjoying himself.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's 12 days, four hours and 37 minutes before the polls close in New
Hampshire," he joked. "But who's counting?"
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
