<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Whitman to boost education funding, will improve college saving  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Gov. Christie Whitman's proposed state budget is
expected to include more money for public education and improvements to a
college savings program that has drawn a lukewarm response since she set it up
in 1997.
<P>
	   Whitman's spending plan will call for an increase in direct aid to public
education "approaching" $500 million, spokesman Peter McDonough said. The
increase would be in direct aid to education, and does not include areas such as
school construction, a multibillion dollar issue lawmakers are still attempting
to solve.
</P>
<P>
	   The state budget that passed last June raised public education funding by
about $400 million. Whitman's proposed spending plan will be unveiled Saturday.
The governor will deliver her annual budget address on Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   Whitman said on Thursday that her proposed budget would include a plan to
strengthen her college savings program.
</P>
<P>
	   "One of the ways state government can try to make this a better state for
everyone is by helping families save money for college," Whitman said while
visiting a fourth grade class in North Brunswick.
</P>
<P>
	   Whitman announced her intention to launch a college savings program in
January 1997, but the NJ BEST program didn't draw much of a response from
parents.
</P>
<P>
	   As of February 1999, the program had netted only about 570 investors. New
York, which launched its savings program when New Jersey did, had 17,130
investors at that time. Maryland, Nevada, New Hampshire, Washington, and West
Virginia - which also all launched their programs around the same time as New
Jersey- had at least double the number of New Jersey subscribers. The New Jersey
program now has about 1,900 investors.
</P>
<P>
	   New Jersey's program works like an individual retirement account. Money
deposited in the NJ BEST account is not tax deductible, but interest earned on
the savings is not federally taxed until the money is withdrawn. At that time,
the earnings may be taxed at the college student's income tax rate, which is
typically lower than their parents' rate.
</P>
<P>
	   But the program wasn't yielding as high an investment as in other states,
and a higher management fee reduced that investment return even more. The return
rate, however, did improve by the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
	   Whitman said the investment fee will be slashed, and that the new program
will allow savings for younger children to be placed in more aggressive
investments to get a better return on the dollar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
