<HEADLINE> Notre Dame Amends Sweatshop Rules  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH BEND, Ind. (AP) -- The University of Notre Dame has decided to bar
manufacturers of its licensed products from using factories in countries that do
not allow workers to organize, including China.
</P>
<P>
	   University Vice President William P. Hoye said Thursday that the school is
tightening the code of conduct it already imposes on the manufacturers as ``one
of several ways you can improve the conditions for workers.''
</P>
<P>
	   Notre Dame's licensed products are made in factories all over the world. The
university has given licensees a June 30, 2001, deadline to comply with the new
requirements.
</P>
<P>
	   The University also said it is adding members of church, labor and human
rights organizations to the professional auditors who monitor the plants
producing Notre Dame merchandise.
</P>
<P>
	   Notre Dame is among a handful of universities that have instituted such
codes of conduct for the makers of merchandise that carry school logos.
</P>
</TEXT>
