<HEADLINE> Cohen Backs Swede for Iraq Agency  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Iraq shouldn't be allowed to dictate who is going to
lead the new U.N. weapons inspection agency, Defense Secretary William Cohen
said Thursday after a meeting with the U.N. chief.
</P>
<P>
	   Cohen flew to New York on Thursday to express U.S. support for Rolf Ekeus of
Sweden, a former chief Iraq weapons inspector and U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan's pick to head the new inspection agency.
</P>
<P>
	   Baghdad has questioned the choice, saying Ekeus' association with the
previous U.N. arms inspection agency made him unfit. Iraq's allies on the
Security Council, Russia, China and France, blocked the appointment altogether
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The United States has said Ekeus remains a candidate to head the new agency,
but Security Council members have decided to hold further consultations to try
to find someone all 15 can agree on.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The key to remember is we have to have an effective inspection regime,''
Cohen said. ``We can't allow Iraq to put itself in the position of exercising a
veto over who is going to be chairing or heading that verification and
inspection mission.''
</P>
<P>
	   Ekeus was the executive chairman of the U.N. Special Commission from
1991-1997 before becoming Sweden's U.S. ambassador. There have been no U.N.
weapons inspections in Iraq since arms experts withdrew in December 1998 ahead
of U.S. and British airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
	   U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said Thursday that Cohen and Annan also
discussed troop requirements and financing for African missions in Congo, Angola
and Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
	   Annan has recommended large expansions in the Congo and Sierra Leone
missions. During the meeting, the U.N. chief explained his reasoning and the
funding levels that would be required, Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
	   The United States is billed 31 percent of U.N. peacekeeping costs.
</P>
</TEXT>
