<HEADLINE> Judge OKs $2.2M Deal for Inmates  </HEADLINE>
   By DANA FIELDS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- A class-action lawsuit filed after videotaped
shakedowns in which Texas jail guards beat and kicked prisoners has ended with a
$2.2 million settlement for the inmates.
</P>
<P>
	   The settlement affects 2,100 inmates from Missouri who were sent to
privately run jails in Texas from 1995 through 1997 because of overcrowding.
</P>
<P>
	   The inmates will share $1.12 million, with individual portions based on the
severity of injuries. The rest of the money will cover attorneys' fees and legal
costs.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. District Judge Nanette K. Laughrey approved the settlement Jan. 14.
</P>
<P>
	   Capitol Corrections Resources Inc., the company that ran the jails, will
contribute $2.1 million. The rest will come from other defendants, including the
company that transported the Missourians to Texas.
</P>
<P>
	   The state of Missouri admitted no liability and will not contribute to the
settlement. The state did agree to a five-year moratorium on sending prisoners
to Texas or to any CCRI-run jails anywhere except in very narrow circumstances.
</P>
<P>
	   Many of the inmates contend Missouri officials ignored credible reports of
their treatment in Texas, and acted only after the public broadcasts of
videotapes showing prisoners being bitten by guard dogs and shocked with stun
guns.
</P>
<P>
	   The videotapes were made by deputies for training purposes on Sept. 18,
1996, at Texas' Brazoria County Jail and on March 2, 1997, in Gregg County.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
