<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain Denounces NY Primary System  </HEADLINE>
   By BETH GARDINER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Fuming over a state GOP effort to remove his name from New
York's presidential primary ballots, Sen. John McCain accused party leaders
Thursday of making New York less democratic than Russia.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain stood outside the Russian consulate and declared that voters in
Moscow and St. Petersburg have a wider choice at the polls in March than those
in the Bronx and Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
	   ``In Russia, there will be more than one name on the ballot'' in the March
26 presidential election, McCain said. ``In New York, unless something happens,
there will be only one name on the ballot. It seems to me that history has been
turned on its head.''
</P>
<P>
	   In fact, both George W. Bush and Steve Forbes have secured places on the
ballot for the March 7 Republican primary while others are skipping the state
because of what some say are New York's excessively stringent requirements.
</P>
<P>
	   New York could be an important state if McCain upsets Bush in the New
Hampshire primary Feb 1. Most public polls show the two in a statistical dead
heat, though McCain's pollsters believe his lead is in the high single digits.
</P>
<P>
	   State Republican leaders have challenged McCain's petitions in 17 of New
York's 31 congressional districts, claiming he failed to obtain the required
number of signatures from party members. The Arizona senator is suing in an
effort to get on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
	   At a separate news conference here, Arizona state Sen. Scott Bundgaard
accused McCain of hypocrisy, saying McCain himself had used Arizona election
laws in 1988 and 1992 to force his opponents off the ballot.
</P>
<P>
	   ``McCain went through the same process that the state party is going through
here,'' Bundgaard said. ``If there is such a groundswell of support for John
McCain, then he should have no problems getting enough signatures.''
</P>
<P>
	   McCain said Bundgaard's accusations were untrue and that credible candidates
have never been removed from Arizona ballots.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain in New York and Bush in Iowa resolved to maintain their friendship
despite the ballot dispute and sometimes-bitter attacks on each other's tax
plans.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He's my friend during the campaign and he's darn sure going to be my
friend after the campaign,'' Bush said, stressing that a TV ad criticizing
McCain's tax package was not a personal attack.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Of course we are friends,'' McCain agreed. ``He's a fine man and you're
not going to hear anything negative from me about him.''
</P>
<P>
	   Yet their campaigns continued to scrap.
</P>
<P>
	   The Bush camp rounded up half a dozen business leaders and accountants who
said McCain's plan to close supposed loopholes in the tax code would hurt
companies large and small and especially those using the Internet.
</P>
<P>
	   The McCain camp responded that Bush was catering to corporate interests
instead of the average taxpayers who would gain if excessive tax breaks were
eliminated.
</P>
<P>
	   Executives from several high-technology firms, in a conference call arranged
by Bush aides, complained to reporters specifically about McCain's proposed
changes in the way advertising expenses are deducted.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It would add millions to their tax bills,'' said Floyd Kvamme, a partner
in Kleiner, Perkins, Caufield, and Byers, a Silicon Valley firm that raises
money for Internet start-ups. He cast the idea as the ``first substantial tax
increase for the Internet'' even though it would affect all advertisers.
</P>
<P>
	   That was a swing at McCain's pledge to turn an existing moratorium on
Internet sales taxes into a permanent ban.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain is proposing to spread out the deduction, having companies take 80
percent in the year the ad costs are incurred and the rest over four years.
</P>
<P>
	   His campaign said the plan simply accords advertising the same treatment as
some other business expenses: When they provide a benefit that lasts for more
than a year, the deduction is spread over more than a year.
</P>
<P>
	   ``By closing more than 60 corporate loopholes, John McCain is able to move
more than 25 million middle-class Americans into the 15 percent tax bracket,''
his campaign said in a statement. ``By caving to the demands of the special
interests who have funded his campaign, Governor Bush would prevent those
millions of taxpayers from receiving necessary tax relief.''
</P>
<P>
	   The executives who spoke against the McCain plan said companies would end up
taking deductions several years after the product they advertised became
obsolete.
</P>
<P>
	   After advocating campaign finance reform before a Chamber of Commerce crowd
of 900 in Randolph, Mass., McCain said in New York his attacks on politics as
usual are the reason party leaders oppose him here and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Anybody who wants the status quo in Washington doesn't want me,'' McCain
said. ``The establishment is threatened by my candidacy and I understand that,
and I respect them all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-20-00 2040 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000120.0233 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NJ Gov Considers Dorm Sprinkler Law  </HEADLINE>
   By AMY WESTFELDT Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SOUTH ORANGE, N.J. (AP) -- A day after a dorm fire killed three college
students, Gov. Christie Whitman said she would consider legislation requiring
sprinkler systems in all college dormitories.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I don't think you could put a price tag on human life,'' the governor said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Sprinklers weren't required when Boland Hall was built 48 years ago at Seton
Hall University, where a fire early Wednesday killed three students and injured
62 people. Sprinklers have been required in dorms built since 1984.
</P>
<P>
	   Seton Hall will consider ``anything that we can all do to make sure that
something like this never, ever happens again,'' said school spokeswoman Lisa
Grider, including installing sprinklers in the six-story dorm.
</P>
<P>
	   Of the six people who remained hospitalized Thursday, four remained in
critical condition.
</P>
<P>
	   Essex County Prosecutor Donald Campolo disputed a published report that
investigators had eliminated careless smoking and electrical problems as
possible causes.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We are ruling out nothing at this juncture,'' Campolo said.
</P>
<P>
	   He declined to comment on a story in The Star-Ledger of Newark that
investigators were seeking three young men whom a resident assistant had asked
to leave the building less than an hour before the fire broke out.
</P>
<P>
	   Students at the Roman Catholic university continued to question how well the
university is prepared for fire, including its handling of a chronic string of
false alarms at Boland Hall.
</P>
<P>
	   Grider said on Thursday that in one case, a fire was found in a Dumpster
near the dormitory, but the others were false.
</P>
<P>
	   ``When I first heard the alarm, I thought `I'm not leaving,''' said Marissa
Lorenz, an 18-year-old who was released from the hospital on Thursday. ``I mean,
there are so many alarms.''
</P>
<P>
	   Several students said sprinklers should be installed in all of Seton Hall's
six dormitories. Only the two freshmen dormitories -- Boland Hall and Aquinas
Hall -- don't have sprinkler systems.
</P>
<P>
	   A fire alarm Thursday morning resulted in the evacuation of the
upperclassmen dorm Xavier Hall. Grider said she didn't know the cause.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I got up real quick for this one,'' said Guerschom Nazaire, a 20-year-old
junior.
</P>
<P>
	   Classes were canceled until Monday for the school's 10,000 students. Only
two spent the night in a recreation center where makeshift beds were created,
Grider said. Many stayed with upperclassmen or went home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
