<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Year's first snowfall causes minor problems  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - The snow fell softly, blanketing the metropolitan area
with its first white coat of winter Thursday - a seasonal postcard that
threatened to wreak some havoc overnight before slipping north into New England.
<P>
	   Forecasters warned that up to eight inches of snow could land on eastern
Long Island, with the city getting up to five inches. Dropping temperatures and
whipping winds, with wind chill readings of 10- to 20-below zero, could also
cause icy roads by Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
	   But on Thursday evening, there were only scattered problems, and a
relatively normal rush hour. In the northern suburbs, barely one inch was on the
ground; in Central Park, it was 2.5 inches, with 2 inches reported in Plainview,
on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's amazing how people panic with a little snow," said Marcia Bayer, who
was headed south from the Tarrytown train station for a Manhattan shopping
excursion. "This is nothing."
</P>
<P>
	   Two of the region's three major airports - LaGuardia and Newark - reported
delays of between 90 minutes and three hours and some cancellations Thursday
evening. Flights were delayed at Kennedy earlier in the day but were back to
normal by nightfall.
</P>
<P>
	   Port Authority spokesman Bill Cahill said most of those problems were caused
by bad weather in other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
	   In the city, trucks began scattering salt at 6 a.m. and quickly dumped more
than 5,000 tons across the five boroughs. There were also 1,000 heat complaints
called in by chilly tenants on Thursday, said Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
	   On Long Island, a wildcat sick-out by state Department of Transportation
workers left local authorities struggling to keep streets clean and ice-free. At
least 300 of a scheduled 440 drivers, snow plow operators, warehouse workers and
mechanics called in sick.
</P>
<P>
	   The job action, prompted by contract talks stalled since April, was
"completely irresponsible," said state DOT spokesman Michael Fleischer. "The
workers have put the health and safety of Long Island motorists in jeopardy."
</P>
<P>
	   Gov. George Pataki agreed, ordering the state attorney general to seek a
court order requiring an immediate return to work. "We will meet this ... with
swift and severe action," Pataki promised.
</P>
<P>
	   Stephen Madarasz, spokesman for the 77,000-member Civil Service Employees
Association, said union shop stewards had called snow plow drivers and urged
their return to work. The union had no knowledge of the sick-out, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Instead of the usual 200 snowplows on the job in Long Island, there were
only 40 to 50 on the roads, Fleischer said.
</P>
<P>
	   Scattered school delays and early closings were also reported in suburbs in
Westchester and Rockland counties and Long Island, but nothing widespread.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
