<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
   By The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
	   A major winter storm brought as much as an inch of snow per hour to
Northeast and Mid-Atlantic states Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Roanoke, Va., Baltimore and Beech Mountain, N.C., had received 5 inches of
snow by late Thursday, and as much as an inch an hour was falling in Delaware
and southern New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
	   The system was winding down over the Great Lakes region, where as much as 12
inches had fallen since Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Strong northwesterly winds behind the system brought gusts to the Great
Lakes, Ohio Valley and Appalachians. A wind gust of 53 mph was recorded in
Galax, Va., and Rochester, Minn., had a wind chill of 57 below zero. The strong
winds also created lake effect snows in Michigan, northern Indiana and Ohio.
</P>
<P>
	   High pressure centered over the Plains brought fair and dry weather to much
of the central and southern United States. A few rain and snow showers were
scattered across California and the northern Rockies.
</P>
<P>
	   The highest temperature in the Lower 48 states was 77 degrees in Key West.
The lowest temperature was 26 below zero in Eveleth, Minn.
</P>
</TEXT>
