<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Papers Have Gov't Anti-Drug Ad Deal  </HEADLINE>
   By JANELLE CARTER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Television networks are not the only media that have
advertising credit agreements with the White House drug policy office.
Newspapers and magazines also benefit from the program.
</P>
<P>
	   A 1997 law set aside $1 billion over five years for the agency to buy
anti-drug ads and commercials in media outlets around the country. The media are
then required to provide something tangible in return, such as discounts on the
ads or additional free advertising.
</P>
<P>
	   Networks that took the paid ads agreed to fill their obligation by inserting
anti-drug messages in popular shows like ``ER'' and ``Home Improvement,'' and
they recently came under criticism when it was disclosed that they allowed the
drug office to review the scripts before they aired.
</P>
<P>
	   The 250 newspapers that accept the drug office's ads typically meet their
obligation by providing discounts. Some papers, including The Washington Post,
fulfill part of their requirement by posting free anti-drug ads on their Web
sites.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This, as far as the Post is concerned, was an advertiser coming to the
Post to purchase ads,'' Post spokeswoman Linda Erdos said Wednesday. ``It was
treated no differently than we would have treated any company coming to us.''
</P>
<P>
	   The drug office gave The New York Times $100,000 to produce 30,000 booklets
under its Newspapers in Education program to help teachers deal with drug abuse
questions. The information was also posted on the Times Web site.
</P>
<P>
	   The office announced this week that it would no longer review TV scripts
prior to the shows being aired.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We are mandated under law to do the program,'' said Bob Weiner, a
spokesman for the office. ``We have never told the television networks or
newspapers what to do.''
</P>
<P>
	   The office plans to spend $11 million this year on newspaper advertising and
another $9 million for ads in magazines such as Time, People and Family Circle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-20-00 2117 </TRAILER>
