<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bradley Suffers More Heart Episodes  </HEADLINE>
   By MIKE GLOVER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MOUNT PLEASANT, Iowa (AP) -- Democratic presidential candidate Bill Bradley
said Thursday he has suffered four irregular heartbeat episodes since he first
disclosed his non-life threatening condition more than a month ago. The latest
reoccurrence was on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley said he would only make the episodes public if they required him to
seek a doctor's attention, and he dismissed any notion that the problem might
hamper his presidential bid. His campaign schedule had not been interrupted by
the irregular heartbeat, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It has absolutely no impact on the race or my capacity to have a schedule
or the intensity of campaigning,'' Bradley said at an impromptu news conference
where he took only a few questions.
</P>
<P>
	   He said the episodes are ``regular and predictable,'' although he conceded
that four episodes in a month is more than he's used to. ``It's more frequent
than I've had in the past. ... What you feel is your heart starts to beat
faster. It's been pretty regular,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The timing of the disclosure couldn't be more awkward, coming just days
before the first voting of the presidential year with Bradley competing in the
Iowa caucuses on Monday against Vice President Al Gore, who is the front-runner
there.
</P>
<P>
	   When his heart condition was first disclosed on Dec. 10, Bradley faced a
barrage of questions about his health, in part because he had not revealed the
condition he's had since 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   Asked Thursday night why he choose not to disclose the latest episodes,
Bradley bristled, saying, ``Because I didn't think we needed to disclose it.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``You don't want me to go around disclosing every time I flip out for an
hour, or two hours,'' he said. ``If I have to see a doctor or if there has to be
any medical attention given to it you will hear about it immediately. Otherwise
it's just the nature of the particular situation.''
</P>
<P>
	   Campaign aide Anita Dunn said Bradley had not seen a doctor, but had
contacted his doctors about the episodes, which began shortly after Christmas,
around Dec. 26-28. The most recent occurrences came on Jan. 6, Jan. 9 and on
Sunday, she said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They were all of very short duration,'' Dunn said.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley takes four doses of an anti-arrhythmic drug called Procanbid twice a
day and the irregular heartbeat almost never occurs when he regularly takes the
medicine, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Dunn said doctors are ``not sure why'' he's experiencing irregular
heartbeats, but have voiced no concern and have not recommended any change in
medication.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley's campaign chairman, Doug Berman, said the campaign decided not to
make the episodes public unless Bradley sees a doctor ``because it's a
non-event.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``The fact is it doesn't in any way interfere with his schedule,'' Berman
said. ``He goes forward. He has his full regular schedule so there's nothing to
report.''
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley was examined in a hospital last month for an irregular heartbeat --
a chronic condition that he previously has dismissed as ``just a nuisance.''
Doctors found no other heart problems.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is just one of those things, it's there, you live with it, it's no
problem whatsoever. It is common, it is something that doesn't effect my daily
activities,'' Bradley, 56, said at the time.
</P>
<P>
	   The Bradley campaign released the information after ABC News asked whether
the condition had reoccurred.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-20-00 2130 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
