<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Big Winter Storm Wallops East  </HEADLINE>
   By BOB MILLER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   Winter delivered its first major wallop to parts of the East on Thursday,
tangling air and ground traffic, closing scores of schools and dropping blankets
of snow on roads that until now hadn't seen a dusting.
</P>
<P>
	   The powerful, blustery storm blew through the eastern half of the nation
like a freezing pendulum, swinging down from the upper Midwest, crossing the
Appalachians and then scooting up the coast.
</P>
<P>
	   The thick, white coating it left behind -- starting with 9 inches in
Minnesota on Wednesday and continuing with up to 8 inches in West Virginia by
Thursday -- closed schools and caused several fender-benders.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The only complaint I have is that people don't know how to drive in it,''
said Lisa DeCicco of Philadelphia, which had about 2 inches of snow by Thursday
evening. ``It took me two hours to get to work today, and that's really
aggravating when there's almost nothing on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
	   Delaware Gov. Thomas Carper canceled his State of the State address, and
schools were closed across Virginia, North Carolina, Maryland and parts of West
Virginia. Hampton Roads, Va., received more snow Thursday than in the last three
winters combined.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'm just going to dig it out,'' said Rhoda Helmintoller, who cleared the
snow from in front of her apartment in Hagerstown, Md., before tackling the
slushy buildup on her car. ``I've got to bowl tonight. I don't like to drive in
it, but you've got to do something when it snows.''
</P>
<P>
	   Airline passengers throughout the region had to cope with delays and
cancellations. At Logan International Airport in Boston, U.S. Airways canceled
half its remaining flights after 3 p.m. The airline also warned that some
flights could be affected Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   The New York City area's three major airports reported up to one-hour delays
and some cancellations. Port Authority spokesman Bill Cahill said most were due
to bad weather elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
	   On nearby Long Island, a wildcat sick-out by state Department of
Transportation workers left local authorities struggling to keep streets clear.
At least 300 of a scheduled 440 drivers, snow plow operators, warehouse workers
and mechanics called in sick, and only 40 to 50 of the usual 200 snowplows were
on the road.
</P>
<P>
	   The job action, prompted by contract talks stalled since April, was
``completely irresponsible,'' said state DOT spokesman Michael Fleischer. ``The
workers have put the health and safety of Long Island motorists in jeopardy,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Near Washington, about a third of the flights out of Reagan National Airport
and Dulles International Airport were canceled Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   All of the city's public schools were closed, and the federal government
announced that nonessential employees could take a day off instead of trying to
make it to the office.
</P>
<P>
	   A mass of bitter, arctic air followed the storm from Canada all the way to
North Carolina, where the overnight wind chill in Raleigh was expected to drop
to 10 below zero.
</P>
<P>
	   The storm first brought treacherous driving to the Midwest, where the
weather was blamed for three traffic deaths in Iowa and one in Michigan on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   It continued to cause problems in the region Thursday. In Michigan, for
example, a 37-year-old woman was killed when she lost control of her car on a
slushy road and collided with a truck.
</P>
<P>
	   The relatively mild winter until now has been attributed to a number of
factors, including the La Nina phenomenon in which cool water sloshes across the
Pacific to replace the warm water that produced El Nino.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
