<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Air Force Launches Satellite  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- The Air Force launched a rocket Thursday night
carrying a $200 million communication satellite dedicated to national security.
</P>
<P>
	   The Lockheed Martin rocket blasted off at 8:03 p.m. with the Defense
Satellite Communications System satellite. It is the 11th in a series of 14
advanced DSCS satellites and should begin operating in May. The first was
launched in 1982.
</P>
<P>
	   The newer models are designed to provide high-speed communication to Army
and Marine personnel equipped with 33-inch-diameter antennas. The jam-proof
satellites also support military officials at fixed locations as well as the
diplomatic service and White House.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
