<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1st Lady Pushes College Tax Credit  </HEADLINE>
   By SHANNON McCAFFREY Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton used the power of the White House
bully pulpit Thursday to push an issue she is embracing as a candidate for a
Senate seat from New York -- making college tuition more affordable.
</P>
<P>
	   Mrs. Clinton said a new proposal for college tax credits could be to the
coming generation what the G.I. Bill was for World War II veterans. She noted
that average college tuition has doubled over the past 20 years, outpacing the
median income.
</P>
<P>
	   ``No one who wants to improve his or her prospects through education should
have to risk poverty to attain that education,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
	   President Clinton allowed that his wife and Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y.,
have ``lobbied me relentlessly on this for the better part of a year.''
</P>
<P>
	   Schumer first began pushing the college tax credit plan during his 1998
Senate campaign. The issue was popular for Schumer, especially among
middle-class suburban voters like the ones Mrs. Clinton must court to win the
Senate race next year. Her poll numbers have been shaky in the
politically-crucial suburbs of New York City.
</P>
<P>
	   The Clinton plan unveiled Thursday mirrored Schumer's, which died in
Congress last year. The centerpiece is a $10,000 tax deduction to help families
pay for tuition and other college costs. A family earning $120,000 or less
annually could receive the full deduction for tuition, fees and job-related
training under the plan once it was phased in by 2003. Alternatively, taxpayers
could seek a maximum credit of $2,800 a year.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart brushed aside reporters
questions about whether Mrs. Clinton's appearance at the White House was
appropriate given that she is planning to formally announce her Senate candidacy
next month.
</P>
<P>
	   He said the first lady's long-standing commitment to education was well
known.
</P>
<P>
	   ``There's certainly other people who come here to events,'' Lockhart said.
``They're up for re-election or running or something else.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
