</P>
<P>
	   "I think it's a much better opportunity now than in 1993 when Bill Clinton
tried to do it and failed," said Bradley. He said the number of uninsured has
grown since that time, as has cost and there is also increasing restiveness in
the medical community.
</P>
<P>
	   All that's combined to shift the political debate, he argued.
</P>
<P>
	   Mrs. Anderson said she was won over though "I still have concerns about
Congress."
</P>
<P>
	   Joyce Brown said she was sticking with Gore.
</P>
<P>
	   "I didn't hear anything to make me change my mind," Ms. Brown said. "I'm
glad Bradley's there offering competition because it's made Gore sharper.
Besides, Iowans like a good fight."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-20-00 2243 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000120.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 22:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
   By The Associated Press Don W. Samuelson
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BOISE, Idaho (AP) -- Former Idaho Gov. Don W. Samuelson died of a heart
attack Thursday. He was 86.
</P>
<P>
	   Samuelson was a state senator from Sandpoint in 1966 when he was elected
governor.
</P>
<P>
	   Despite a legislative majority of his own Republican party, Samuelson set a
record in 1967 when he vetoed 39 bills sent to him by lawmakers. He served only
one term.
</P>
<P>
	   Republican Gov. Dirk Kempthorne remembered Samuelson as ``an honest,
plain-speaking man whose solid conservative ideals shaped his personal and
public life.
</P>
<P>
	   ``His background as a small businessman helped him bring sound business
practices to state government,'' Kempthorne said.
</P>
<P>
	   Born in Woodhull, Ill., on July 27, 1913, Samuelson attended Knox College in
Galesburg, Ill., before entering the Navy in 1944 and serving as a gunners mate
at Farragut Naval Training Station in northern Idaho.
</P>
<P>
	   After his discharge in 1946, Samuelson lived in Iowa for a short time before
returning to Sandpoint to start a sporting goods store, the Pend Oreille Sport
Shop, where he did gunsmithing and fishing tackle repair for 14 years. He then
sold his business and started the Don Samuelson Equipment Co., selling and
leasing mining and logging equipment.
Isabella Yurieva
</P>
<P>
	   MOSCOW (AP) -- Isabella Yurieva, a celebrated singer of Russian folk songs
who was lively enough to perform as she entered her second century, died
Wednesday. She was 100.
</P>
<P>
	   Yurieva was well-known on Moscow's musical stages even in the 1920s, after
moving there from the southern city of Rostov-on-Don.
</P>
<P>
	   Her repertoire focused on urban and rural romance songs, even though the
genre was often discouraged during Soviet times.
Richard B. Caspari
</P>
<P>
	   RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- Dr. Richard B. Caspari, an orthopedic surgeon who
operated on gymnast Mary Lou Retton before she won her Olympic gold medal, died
Wednesday of an apparent heart attack while skiing in Vail, Colo. He was 57.
</P>
<P>
	   A former president of the Arthroscopy Association of North America, Caspari
performed arthroscopic surgery on Retton's knee six weeks before the 1984
Olympics. She went on to win a gold medal, two silver medals and two bronze
medals in gymnastics.
</P>
<P>
	   His other patients included journalist Ted Koppel, Cy Young Award-winning
pitcher Frank Viola and several members of the Washington Redskins.
John Chrystal
</P>
<P>
	   DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- John Chrystal, an Iowa farmer and banker who
followed in his uncle's footsteps as Cold War-era agricultural adviser to Soviet
leaders, died Wednesday of cancer. He was 74.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1959, then-Soviet Premier Nikita Khrushchev toured the United States and
made a much-publicized stop at the Coon Rapids, Iowa, farm of Roswell Garst,
Chrystal's uncle. Garst had already visited the Soviet Union as part of a farm
delegation.
</P>
<P>
	   From that time on, Chrystal traveled about every other year to the Soviet
Union at the government's invitation. He toured the land, dined with Khrushchev
and in the early '80s talked farming with Mikhail Gorbachev.
</P>
<P>
	   Chrystal was chairman and chief executive of Bankers Trust Inc. and a
partner with his brother on the family farm.
</P>
<P>
	   He unsuccessfully sought the Democratic nomination for governor in 1990.
Oliver Heard
</P>
<P>
	   SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- Oliver Heard, a San Antonio attorney whose
tax-collection company became nearly as universal in the state as taxes
themselves, died Wednesday during heart surgery. He was 56.
</P>
<P>
	   Heard was a principal of Heard, Linebarger, Graham, Giggan, Blair, Pena &AMP;
Sampson, which dominates the $2 billion per year tax-collection business in
Texas.
</P>
<P>
	   The firm represents 250 tax-collection clients in Texas, including the
cities of Dallas, El Paso and San Antonio, as well as Harris and Tarrant
counties and school districts throughout the state.
David Riley
</P>
<P>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- David Riley, the U.N. refugee agency's highest
official in Kosovo, has died of apparent natural causes. He was 50.
</P>
<P>
	   Riley joined the United Nations in 1981 and rose to become the top officer
overseeing U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees assistance projects worldwide. He
was named to lead UNHCR operations in Kosovo last June.
</P>
<P>
	   After the international peacekeeping force entered Kosovo that month, Riley
set up office in a warehouse outside Pristina, the province's capital. There he
began managing UNHCR's assistance program to help refugees from the war-torn
province return home.
</P>
<P>
	   Over the years, he served the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees in
Pakistan, Ethiopia, Malawi, and Bosnia.
Hazel Wolf
</P>
<P>
	   SEATTLE (AP) -- Hazel Wolf, a longtime environmental activist who helped
found 21 chapters of the Audubon Society in the Pacific Northwest, died
Wednesday. She was 101.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition to her Audubon Society work, she served as editor of the
newsletter of the Federation of Western Outdoor Clubs since 1978.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1979, Wolf laid the groundwork for Indian tribes and environmental groups
in Washington State to talk with one another, to share concerns, and find common
ground relating to issues affecting the environment.
George W. Williams
</P>
<P>
	   LAS CRUCES, N.M. (AP) -- George W. Williams, a former publisher of the Las
Cruces Sun-News and other newspapers in several states, died Tuesday in
Murfreesboro, Tenn. after a lengthy illness. He was 63.
</P>
<P>
	   He was publisher of the Sun-News from 1987 to 1990. He left the Sun-News
shortly after the newspaper was purchased from Worrell Newspapers Inc. by its
current owner, MediaNews Group Inc.
</P>
<P>
	   Williams worked for Worrell Newspapers for 20 years as a publisher in
several cities in Tennessee, Kentucky, Indiana, West Virginia and New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
	   After he retired as a publisher, he owned and managed the Northfield Mega
Video in Murfreesboro for five years.
</P>
<P>
	   Survivors include sons Keith Williams of Cookeville, Tenn., and John
Williams of Murfreesboro; daughters Gail Dietz of Elkhart, Ind.; Lea Ann Jarman
of Rushville, Ind.; Sheri Lenart of Mendon, Maine; Beth May of Noblesville,
Ind.; and Kara Cox of Fishers, Ind.; a brother and 21 grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
