<DOCNO> APW20000120.0261 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 23:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    Thursday, Jan. 20, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bradley Discusses Heart Problem
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   MOUNT PLEASANT, Iowa (AP) -- Democratic presidential hopeful Bill Bradley
said today he has suffered from episodes of irregular heartbeat but the
condition will not affect his campaign tour. He said the episodes are "regular
and predictable," although he conceded that four episodes in a month is more
than he's used to. Bradley was examined in a hospital last month for an
irregular heartbeat -- a chronic condition that he previously has dismissed as
"just a nuisance." Doctors found no other heart problems.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
EgyptAir 990 Crash Said Deliberate
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   NORTH KINGSTOWN, R.I. (AP) -- Officials close to the investigation of
EgyptAir 990 have said they are more convinced than ever that the jet was
crashed deliberately. The examination of the shattered Boeing 767 has revealed
no signs of a mechanical failure that would have caused the plane to plummet 40
minutes into its 11-hour flight. "Everything leads everyone to believe that the
plane was mechanically sound and it was doing what it was supposed to," one
government official told The Associated Press. "There's just no smoking gun" to
indicate mechanical failure. The FBI has been involved from the start and has
uncovered no evidence of terrorism or conspiracy, according to one of the
federal officials.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Elian's Grandmothers Get Visas To U.S.
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Elian Gonzalez's Cuban grandmothers have obtained visas
to come to New York and plead their case to take Elian back to Cuba. The U.S.
diplomatic mission in Cuba issued visas to the two women today as a group from
the National Council of Churches was flying to Havana from New York to meet with
them and with Cuban government officials. Sources said New York was chosen as a
destination because the welcome there would be far friendlier than in Miami,
where Elian has been living with relatives for almost two months and where
sentiment for his remaining in the United States is strong.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Colombia Drug War Progress Seen
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- In a visit underscoring the growing American
military role in strife-torn Colombia, U.S. Army Secretary Louis Caldera said
today a huge planned increase in military aid would yield "dramatic results" in
the war on drugs. Even as he spoke, officials traveling with him warned that the
booming cocaine trade from the South American nation to the United States will
likely get worse before it improves. The trip is the first in memory by a U.S.
Army Secretary to Colombia. It follows President Clinton's proposal earlier this
month of a $1.6 billion emergency anti-narcotics package for the world's
principal cocaine-exporting country.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Indians March on Ecuador Congress
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   QUITO, Ecuador (AP) -- Thousands of Indians marched on Ecuador's Congress
and the adjacent Supreme Court building Thursday, the latest in a month-long
series of protests seeking the resignation of President Jamil Mahuad. Riot
police guarding the government buildings maintained their distance during the
peaceful demonstration, which paralyzed downtown traffic in Quito. Indian
protesters say Mahuad should go because of his plan to make the U.S. dollar
Ecuador's official currency to halt inflation and stabilize the economy. Their
leaders charge the step will further impoverish the 7 million poor people among
Ecuador's population of 12 million.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Huge Dinosaur's Remains Discovered
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- Scientists in Argentina say they have found
partial remains of what may be the largest dinosaur species on record. Carlos
Munoz, director of the Florentino Ameghino Museum of Natural Sciences, said
today a team of paleontologists unearthed the bones of a huge plant-eating
dinosaur thought to have roamed Earth some 105 million years ago. Munoz said
scientists working on a tip from a villager found a femur and two parts of a
vertebra. The pieces of cervical vertebrae were nearly four feet high, he said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Fall
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks fell Friday following a decline on Wall Street,
with the Nikkei Stock Average dropping 145.88 points to 18,917.85 at midday. On
Thursday in New York, the Dow Jones industrial average closed down 138.06 points
to 11,351.30.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Rangers Beat Hurricanes 4-1
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- Radek Dvorak and Michael York scored 1:31 apart in the
first period as the New York Rangers defeated the slumping Carolina Hurricanes
4-1 today. The Rangers won their fourth straight and sixth in seven contests,
while the Hurricanes dropped their season-high fifth straight. The last time
Carolina lost as many was the final five games of the 1997-98 season. John
MacLean's goal 2:11 into the third period sealed the victory for the surging
Rangers, who scored three goals on their first 11 shots.
</P>
<P>
	   AP NewsBrief by PAULINE M. MILLARD
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-20-00 2302 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000120.0262 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 23:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Attempt at New Austria Govt. Fails  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIENNA, Austria (AP) -- Attempts to form a new Austrian government failed
Friday when the leading party broke off coalition talks with an opposition party
after more than three hours of closed-door negotiations.
</P>
<P>
	   Chancellor Viktor Klima of the leading Social Democrats announced the end of
the talks. He said he would propose to President Thomas Klestil that the Social
Democrats form a minority government.
</P>
<P>
	   The leading Social Democrats won the biggest share of votes in October's
parliamentary elections, but it was not enough for the party to form a
government by itself. On Tuesday, it appeared the Social Democrats had reached a
deal with the Austrian People's Party to form a coalition government, but the
deal collapsed after the sides disagreed over who should control key government
posts.
</P>
<P>
	   Klima said he and his negotiating team had gone to ``the limit of what is
tolerable'' in the talks with the People's Party. The People's Party had
demanded control of the Interior Ministry and the Finance Ministry, both Social
Democratic strongholds. Those and other demands were flatly rejected by the
Social Democrats.
</P>
<P>
	   It was not immediately clear if the president would let Klima form a
minority Cabinet, which would be the first such government since 1970. Another
likely alternative would be new elections.
</P>
<P>
	   Austria has been regarded as a model democracy known for political stability
and the absence of labor conflicts. But the political scene was thrown into
turmoil after the Oct. 3 elections, when populist Joerg Haider's far-right
Freedom Party finished second, outpolling the center-right People's Party.
</P>
<P>
	   Haider attracted growing numbers of disillusioned blue-collar workers and
employees, capitalizing on people's fears of job loss by stoking anti-foreigner
sentiments. His controversial right wing comments did nothing to discourage
potential voters.
</P>
<P>
	   But despite the Freedom Party's second-place finish, the Social Democrats
refused to work with Haider to form a coalition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-20-00 2306 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000120.0263 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 23:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush peppered with abortion questions, faces Forbes criticism  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   PELLA, Iowa (AP) - George W. Bush said Thursday that if the child of a
