<HEADLINE> Mexico Referendum Seeks Strike End  </HEADLINE>
   By LISA J. ADAMS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Teachers, students and employees of Latin America's
largest university voted Thursday on a proposal aimed at ending a nine-month
strike that has kept hundreds of thousands of students out of class.
</P>
<P>
	   The referendum at the 286,000-student National Autonomous University and
affiliated high schools asks voters whether they support a compromise proposal
from recently appointed rector Juan Ramon de la Fuente, and whether the proposal
should be used to end the strike.
</P>
<P>
	   De la Fuente's proposal would agree to some of the strikers' demands,
including a return to previous tuition levels. But it rejects other demands, and
the strikers vehemently oppose it.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I prefer a bloodstained people to a subjugated one,'' said UNAM political
science professor and strike supporter David Navarrete, 35. ``Either you have
school for everyone or you have school for no one.''
</P>
<P>
	   Results were not expected until early Friday. But an exit poll by the
independent firm Consulta Mitofsky said the proposal won the support of 90
percent of teachers, 89 percent of students and 87 percent of university
workers. The groups answered affirmatively in roughly similar percentages to the
of whether the proposal should lead to the strike's end received affirmative
answers of similar percentages, the poll reported.
</P>
<P>
	   The poll, taken at 150 voting booths, surveyed 8,000 students, 1,300
professors and 300 workers. No margin of error was given.
</P>
<P>
	   A group of increasingly radical students has kept the university and other
institutions closed since April 1999. As the strike has worn on, university
authorities have taken an increasingly hard line on the strikers' demands, which
include more student representation in university decisions.
</P>
<P>
	   De la Fuente's ``Proposal for a Consensus'' recommends a return to previous
tuition levels -- officials initially wanted to increase tuition from a token
few cents to the equivalent of $140 -- and the creation of a university-wide
Congress to work on reforms. The proposal also would agree to several other
student demands, including that the strikers not be punished.
</P>
<P>
	   In preparation for Thursday's vote, UNAM officials set up about 900 polling
places around the city, as well as at university branches in other Mexican
states.
</P>
<P>
	   Outside the gates of the school, 40-year-old Melania Alviter, the mother of
a university student, threw her arms in the air and begged for divine
intervention.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I'm praying to God that he will help to solve this conflict,'' she said,
sobbing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-20-00 2314 </TRAILER>
