<HEADLINE> Senators 1, Flyers 1  </HEADLINE>
    By KEN BERGER AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Rookie Brian Boucher made 22 saves filling in for John
Vanbiesbrouck, but the Philadelphia Flyers extended their winless streak to four
games Thursday night with a 1-1 tie against the Ottawa Senators.
</P>
<P>
	   The Flyers continued to struggle without injured captain Eric Lindros, who
might learn Friday when he can return from his third concussion in 22 months.
The Flyers have scored three goals during their 0-3-1 slide -- one in each game
Lindros has missed.
</P>
<P>
	   Shawn McEachern scored his 19th goal for the Senators, unbeaten in four of
five. Valeri Zelepukin scored the Flyers' first even-strength goal in five
games.
</P>
<P>
	   The Flyers had several chances in overtime, but Igor Kravchuk foiled the
best one when he tied up John LeClair as he tried to convert a centering pass
from Simon Gagne in front of the net.
</P>
<P>
	   Ottawa goalie Ron Tugnutt, who stopped 23 of 24 shots, poked LeClair's pass
to Mark Recchi away with 15 seconds left in regulation.
</P>
<P>
	   Ottawa's Magnus Arvedson was taken to a hospital after a brutal collision
involving Philadelphia's Marc Bureau with 5:12 left in the third. Arvedson, who
collapsed twice while being helped off the ice, had multiple injuries from his
head to his groin and was to be held overnight for observation.
</P>
<P>
	   "I don't think he lost consciousness," Ottawa coach Jaques Martin said. "He
went into the boards with his leg, his arm and his head."
</P>
<P>
	   Both were chasing the puck along the boards in front of the Flyers' bench as
Philadelphia defenseman Eric Desjardins was coming off the ice through an open
door at the end of the bench.
</P>
<P>
	   Arvedson collided hard with the corner at the door's hinges. Bureau also
went down hard as the crowd stood up like a wave.
</P>
<P>
	   Arvedson tried twice to get up with the help of teammates and trainers, but
fell both times. A stretcher was summoned, but Arvedson was helped off the ice
without it. Bureau escaped with only a stiff neck.
</P>
<P>
	   Lindros, who suffered a concussion Jan. 14 in Atlanta, skated with the team
for the first time Thursday morning. He was scheduled for tests Friday which
will determine when he can return. Lindros has said he wants to play Sunday at
Pittsburgh or Thursday at home against Florida.
</P>
<P>
	   Ottawa had shut out the Flyers in their last two meetings in Philadelphia --
5-0 and 3-0.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
