<HEADLINE> Bradley, Gore Wives Tout Pro-Choice  </HEADLINE>
   By DAVID HO Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- With their husbands campaigning in Iowa, Ernestine
Bradley and Tipper Gore made a rare joint appearance Thursday to reaffirm the
Democratic presidential candidates' support for abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
	   The two would-be first ladies spoke at a National Abortion and Reproductive
Rights Action League dinner commemorating the 27th anniversary of the Supreme
Court's Roe vs. Wade decision that legalized abortion.
</P>
<P>
	   Mrs. Bradley presented her husband as a staunch supporter of abortion
rights, saying his opinion has never changed during his public career.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Bill has always said that a woman's right to choose is an issue that is so
important that we must never play politics with it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore, who also supports abortion rights, has been criticized by some
activists for voting against abortion legislation 20 years ago as a Tennessee
congressman.
</P>
<P>
	   But Mrs. Gore gave no indication that he had been anything but a supporter.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We have to stand together to keep the White House pro-choice,'' she said.
``My husband is fully committed to our cause.''
</P>
<P>
	   Both women introduced video messages from their husbands, who were busy
campaigning in Iowa in advance of Monday's caucuses and could not attend the
event.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley, seated on a couch with his wife, offered a laid back
question-and-answer session. He voiced his support for women's rights between
light answers about his favorite moments and what he most admired in his
German-born wife.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore, flanked by an American flag, cautioned that if he and President
Clinton hadn't won in 1992, legalized abortion could have been outlawed. ``This
could very well be the anniversary of Roe's demise,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Introducing Mrs. Bradley and Mrs. Gore, former Texas Gov. Ann Richards
joked, ``These women are living proof that behind even the good men in politics
are women who could do it a lot better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
