<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 23:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eugene McCarthy Honored  </HEADLINE>
   By FREDERIC J. FROMMER Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Eugene McCarthy, the former Minnesota senator who
galvanized a generation of liberals in the 1960s with his antiwar presidential
campaign, received an award Thursday night from the most unlikely of
organizations: the Conservative Political Action Conference.
</P>
<P>
	   The group gave McCarthy its ``Defenders of the Constitution Award'' for his
role in challenging spending limits on political campaigns.
</P>
<P>
	   McCarthy, whose 1968 antiwar candidacy forced President Lyndon Johnson to
announce he would not seek another term, launched a third-party bid for the
White House in 1976, crusading against spending limits Congress had passed after
Watergate. He joined New York Republican Sen. James Buckley in challenging the
law, and in 1976, the Supreme Court struck down spending limits as
unconstitutional but upheld limits on contributions.
</P>
<P>
	   McCarthy and Buckley, now a federal appeals court judge in Washington, D.C.,
shared the award Thursday night on behalf of other plaintiffs in the case.
McCarthy, now 83, found himself sitting next to some resolute conservatives,
including former New York Republican Congressman Gerald Solomon and Wayne
LaPierre, executive vice president of the National Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
	   Referring to the term ``liberal,'' McCarthy said to laughs, ``It was a
pretty good adjective. Then it became a noun. Any time an adjective becomes a
noun, it's in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
	   In an interview in his Washington apartment before the dinner, McCarthy
didn't seem concerned about accepting an award from a conservative organization.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think they're right on this and the Democrats have been wrong from the
beginning,'' he said. ``We always had much less to spend than the Republicans,
so Democrats thought if they got federal financing they could win all of the
time. It was a real compromise of principle, especially for liberals.''
</P>
<P>
	   McCarthy has long argued that spending limits violate the First Amendment
and bolster the two-party system at the expense of third-party challengers. He
favors full disclosure and bans on contributions by corporations and labor
unions.
</P>
<P>
	   McCarthy isn't afraid to acknowledge money helped him in the '68 race, in
the days before campaign contribution limits.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We had a few big contributors,'' he said. ``And that's true of any liberal
movement. In the American Revolution, they didn't get matching funds from George
III.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
