<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-20 23:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lauries Call Off Grizzlies Effort  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Bill and Nancy Laurie, a billionaire couple that purchased
the NHL's St. Louis Blues in September, on Thursday called off their efforts to
buy the NBA's Vancouver Grizzlies and move the team to St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
	   The Lauries, from Columbia, Mo., announced in a statement that they had
terminated their agreement and would "explore other methods" of bringing an NBA
team to the city.
</P>
<P>
	   "That remains our objective, and we intend to explore all options, including
the possibility of securing an NBA expansion franchise," Bill Laurie said.
</P>
<P>
	   The Lauries signed a contract to buy the Grizzlies for $200 million in
September, about three weeks after they bought the Blues. The deal was
contingent on relocating the team, which would have given the Lauries two
tenants in the 5-year-old Kiel Center, but was met with resistance from NBA
owners.
</P>
<P>
	   Laurie said others in the league felt Vancouver hadn't been given an
"adequate opportunity to demonstrate their support for the Grizzlies."
</P>
<P>
	   The Kiel Center was included in the Lauries' $100 million purchase of the
Blues.
</P>
<P>
	   Nancy Laurie is an heir to the Wal-Mart fortune. Bill Laurie is a former
point guard at Memphis.
</P>
<P>
	   In April, the Lauries bid $400 million to buy the Colorado Avalanche of the
NHL, the Denver Nuggets of the NBA and Denver's new Pepsi Center, but lost to a
rival group that bid $461 million.
</P>
<P>
	   St. Louis has not had an NBA team since the Hawks left in 1968.
</P>
<P>
	   Orca Bay, the parent company that owns the Grizzlies, and the NBA were taken
completely off guard by Laurie's announcement, which was only released to media
outlets in the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
	   Curiously, Laurie's announcement came a day after the two sides held talks
in New York in an attempt to resolve the differences on the condition of sale.
</P>
<P>
	   At halftime of the Grizzlies game against the Utah Jazz Thursday night,
Loring Phinney, spokesman for Orca Bay owner John McCaw, said company officials
were still reviewing Laurie's announcement and would not have a statement until
at least Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think you can say we're surprised," said Phinney.
</P>
<P>
	   Grizzlies president and general manager Stu Jackson said the team can't
comment because it hasn't received official word from Laurie yet.
</P>
<P>
	   "We have to take it at face value," said Jackson. "We don't know concretely
that the deal has fallen through. Certainly, there are some issues to work out.
I think tomorrow we'll know exactly where everybody stands."
</P>
<P>
	   If true, Jackson called the news "terrific,"
</P>
<P>
	   With Laurie out of the picture, the Grizzlies will have to continue
searching for other investors. Orca Bay, headed by Seattle-based
multi-millionaire John McCaw, also owns the NHL Vancouver Canucks and their home
facility, GM Place.
</P>
<P>
	   The Grizzlies, now in their fifth year of existence, were established by
former Canucks owner Arthur Griffiths, who eventually sold off his interest in
the franchise to McCaw, a partner he originally brought in to help finance
soaring arena construction costs and the fees involved in landing the NBA
franchise.
</P>
<P>
	   Griffiths, attending Thursday's game, was cautious after hearing the news.
</P>
<P>
	   "It doesn't surprise me, although I'm not quite sure what it means long
term. But without a doubt it's a signal to us all, the fans, that there are
certain things we have to do in order to keep this team in the first place,"
said Griffiths. "Whether it's Mr. Laurie or Mr. McCaw or whoever owns this team,
it's incumbent that we all wake up and recognize that they could go quickly if
we don't pay attention to those concerns."
</P>
<P>
	   Grizzlies star forward Shareef Abdur-Rahim said he was relieved by the news.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's real good. It's better for the fans. It would've been tough for us to
move just because of all the relationships we built here in the city," said
Abdur-Rahim. "I'm very happy. It seems like we have some stability now."
</P>
<P>
	   As a result of the announced sale agreement last Sept. 23, and Laurie's
refusal to commit to keeping the Grizzlies in Vancouver, a grassroots-based
'Save Our Grizzlies' campaign was organized in an attempt to keep the franchise
in the city.
</P>
<P>
	   Immediately following the announcement, NBA commissioner David Stern voiced
his personal opposition to a relocation, citing the league's record of not
having any franchise migrations since the Clippers moved from San Diego to Los
Angeles in 1984.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's my goal to see the Grizzlies stay and succeed in Vancouver," Stern
said.
</P>
<P>
	   In October, the NBA board of governors finance committee raised concerns
over the terms of the deal, noting that it included many incentives to move the
team.
</P>
<P>
	   Citing the concerns, Orca Bay pulled the deal away before the NBA could vote
on it, in an attempt to try to renegotiate with Laurie.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-20-00 2342 </TRAILER>
