<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    Thursday, Jan. 20, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Moon Moves Toward Total Eclipse
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Across the Western Hemisphere wherever there wasn't a
curtain of clouds, one of the greatest shows on Earth played overhead Thursday
night. Starting about 9:30 p.m. EST with a shadow along its left edge, the moon
began moving toward total eclipse as it crept into Earth's shadow. The darkest
phase, when the moon climbed to its height over the East Coast, was to end at
12:22 a.m. EST Friday. The moon was expected to leave Earth's shadow at 2:24
a.m. EST. Snow spoiled the viewing in some places, especially in the Northeast.
And in much of the North, temperatures dipped into single digits or below,
turning eclipse watching into a test of hardiness.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
EgyptAir 990 Crash Said Deliberate
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   NORTH KINGSTOWN, R.I. (AP) -- Investigators closely involved with the
EgyptAir 990 crash told the Associated Press on Thursday they are more convinced
than ever that the jet was deliberately crashed. Careful examination of the
shattered remains of the Boeing 767 has revealed no signs of a mechanical
failure that would have caused the plane to plummet 40 minutes into its 11-hour
flight. "Everything leads everyone to believe that the plane was mechanically
sound and it was doing what it was supposed to," one government official said.
"There's just no smoking gun" to indicate mechanical failure. The FBI has been
involved from the start and has uncovered no evidence of terrorism or
conspiracy, according to one of the federal officials.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bradley Discusses Heart Problem
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   MOUNT PLEASANT, Iowa (AP) -- Democratic presidential candidate Bill Bradley
said Thursday he has suffered four irregular heartbeat episodes since he first
disclosed his non-life threatening condition more than a month ago. The latest
reoccurrence was on Sunday. Bradley said he would only make the episodes public
if they required him to seek a doctor's attention, and he dismissed any notion
that the problem might hamper his presidential bid. His campaign schedule had
not been interrupted by the irregular heartbeat, he said. Aides said doctors are
"not sure why" he's experiencing irregular heartbeats, but have voiced no
concern and have not recommended any change in medication.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Algerian Terror Suspect Denied Bail
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   MONTREAL (AP) -- An Algerian man facing U.S. terrorism charges was denied
bail in Canada on Thursday after police testified that he coordinated plans to
smuggle explosives into the United States, allegedly to be used in an attack.
The ruling in Montreal was one of several developments in the case Thursday.
Elsewhere, Ahmed Ressam, the man accused of trying to smuggle the explosives
from Canada into Washington state, was indicted on new charges in Seattle. And
in New York, a third man involved in the case pleaded innocent to supporting
Ressam.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mexico Referendum Seeks Strike End
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Teachers, students and employees of Latin America's
largest university voted Thursday on a proposal aimed at ending a nine-month
strike that has kept hundreds of thousands of students out of class. A group of
increasingly radical students has kept the university and other institutions
closed since April 1999. As the strike has worn on, university authorities have
taken an increasingly hard line on the strikers' demands, which include more
student representation in university decisions. Results were not expected until
early Friday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
N.J. Gov. Considers Dorm Sprinkler Law
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SOUTH ORANGE, N.J. (AP) -- A day after a dorm fire killed three college
students, Gov. Christie Whitman said she would consider legislation requiring
sprinkler systems in all college dormitories. Sprinklers weren't required when
Boland Hall was built at Seton Hall University, where a fire early Wednesday
killed three students and injured 62 people. Sprinklers have been required in
dorms built since 1984. The wing of Boland Hall where the fire started was added
to the building in 1971. Of the six people who remained hospitalized Thursday,
four remained in critical condition.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Fall
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks fell Friday following a decline on Wall Street,
with the Nikkei Stock Average dropping 145.88 points to 18,917.85 at midday. On
Thursday in New York, the Dow Jones industrial average closed down 138.06 points
to 11,351.30.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Hornets Beat 76ers 109-100
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Derrick Coleman and Eddie Jones each scored 23
points as the Charlotte Hornets rallied in the third quarter to finish with a
109-100 victory over the Philadelphia 76ers on Thursday night. The Hornets won
their third straight since losing seven in a row, and stopped Philadelphia's
winning streak at four. David Wesley scored 15 points, Ricky Davis had 13, and
Anthony Mason and Elden Campbell each added 10 for the Hornets.
</P>
<P>
	   AP NewsBrief by PAULINE M. MILLARD
</P>
</TEXT>
